<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (21): Private capital eases the travellers'
ride - Sally Bowen examines infrastructural improvements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOME OF PERU'S roads, such as the central highway into the heart of the
Andes, are unparalleled feats of engineering. Others, the jungle highway
built by former President Belaunde, for example, represent the triumph of
optimism over reason. Almost without exception, they are excruciatingly
uncomfortable to travel along.
But within the last few months, the Peruvian traveller is starting to see
the occasional stretch of perfectly smooth, uniformly grey asphalt - a
welcome, if brief, respite from the bone-shaking norm.
Peru's highways are finally under repair. Of some 70,000km of roads
throughout the country, just 10 per cent are at present asphalted. In total,
according to transport ministry estimates, only 1,000km of roads throughout
the country are in reasonable condition.
The InterAmerican Development Bank (IADB) is lending Peru Dollars 210m over
four years to help repair trunk roads. The Peruvian government is adding
another Dollars 90m. By December, 440km of the main coastal road, the
Panamerican highway, will be newly surfaced - and by the end of next year,
1,200km will have been completely rehabilitated.
In Peru's rugged interior, in provinces which are still in a state of
emergency because of lingering subversion, road-building is entrusted to
army engineering battalions. The Treasury has been able to budget Dollars
80m this year and Dollars 150m next for repairs to these badly-neglected
highways and for reconstruction of bridges dynamited by Sendero Luminoso
guerrillas during the past few years.
'Road-building is central to the government's strategy of integration,
development and pacification,' says Mr Dante Cordova, minister of transport
and communications. 'The army's doing something productive and at the same
time generating security. It also provides jobs for local people.'
Another loan of Dollars 220m is under negotiation with the World Bank to
rebuild and asphalt roads such as the Huanuco-Tingo Maria-Pucallpa link,
which runs through coca-growing territory. The initiative will help cut
exorbitant transport costs and thus, it is hoped, encourage coca-farmers to
switch to other crops.
It is not only in roads that improvements are now being seen. Deregulation
of ports and airports is bringing welcome benefits to travellers and
exporters.
Peru's ports used to be among the most expensive in the world. But in its
earliest months in government, the Fujimori administration managed to break
a fifty-five year union monopoly on stevedoring, cutting costs by around
three-quarters. More recently, port charges levied by Enapu, the state ports
authority, have undergone cuts of up to 40 per cent.
'Callao, Lima's port, is now one of the most competitively priced in the
world, cheaper than Guayaquil and about the same as Valparaiso,' says Mr
Cordova. 'Ilo and Matarani in the south can now compete on costs with Chile,
while Paita in the north is cheaper than its Ecuadorean rivals.'
Although the process is taking longer than anticipated, privatisation of
port and airport services is under way. Ramps, car-parking, duty-free shops
and restaurant facilities at Lima's Jorge Chavez international airport will
soon all be privately managed under a concession system. Corpac, the
airports authority which has traditionally run these services will be
reduced to a 'technical body, concentrating on air traffic control,' says Mr
Cordova. Meanwhile, small domestic airlines have proliferated and fares have
plummeted.
A special privatisation committee (Cepri) has been appointed to oversee
transfer of Enapu's seven Pacific seaports to the private sector. The
southern port of Ilo is being treated as a special case, with its own Cepri.
Great hopes hang on Ilo. In February last year, Peru signed a historic
agreement with Bolivia, giving its landlocked neighbour access to the sea
via a 'corridor'. Bolivian and Peruvian entrepreneurs will share an
industrial free zone in Ilo, while the Bolivians also now have rights to a
strip of Peruvian coast known as Boliviamar, which is slated to become a
popular seaside resort.
The Peruvian gesture is aimed at capturing the lion's share of Bolivia's
import and export trade, which currently brings in some 500,000 tonnes of
merchandise a year via the northern Chilean port of Arica. The plan depends
on the upgrading of the La Paz-Ilo road link. A team of engineers from South
Korea's Daewoo Corporation is already completing an initial study for the
road, which Peru's transport ministry expects to cost around Dollars 120m.
Even a cursory glance at the map reveals the strategic potential of a port
such as Ilo. The Fujimori administration would like to see it - or
neighbouring Matarani - become the gateway between Asia and Latin America.
More ambitious, and still very much at the drawing-board stage, is a plan
for a transcontinental highway linking Ilo with the Brazilian Atlantic port
of Santos.
The economic arguments for such a road are powerful. Brazil's soya,
concentrated in south-western Acre province near the Peruvian border, must
currently be transported some 4,000km for shipping from the Atlantic ports '
it is only 1,300km to Ilo. The cost of exporting Brazilian soya to Asia via
Peru would, says Mr Arturo Ramirez of the Cepri-Ilo, result in savings of
Dollars 23 per ton, or Dollars 500,000 on an average boatload.
With only minor improvements, Ilo could handle huge increases in trade -
currently under 12 per cent of port capacity is being used. The sell-off of
the state-owned Ilo copper refinery late this year, and forthcoming
development of the recently-privatised Quellaveco mine to the east of Ilo
could also boost total shipments.
The Dutch company Haskoning is presently completing a study on Ilo's
privatisation. Once evaluation is complete, a promoter will be contracted
and the port concession put up for international tender in March 1994.
This will be the pattern for future privatisations of infrastructure. New
Peruvian investment laws throw concessions for any of the country's roads,
ports and airports open to private bidders.
This could be the way ahead for the transcontinental highway. If
international organisations will not put up the estimated Dollars 1.4bn
required, 'maybe private Brazilian consortia will bid for a 60-year
concession and operate it as a toll-road,' says Mr Cordova. 'We're working
on stretches of it already, but Brazil will be the biggest beneficiary.'
