<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (19): Practical visionary / Profile of
Hernando de Soto
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHANGES have started to happen in Peru since the mid-1980s, when Mr Hernando
de Soto published one of the most influential works on political economy
ever to emerge from Latin America - but not influential enough for de Soto's
liking.
De Soto has demonstrated the power of the word. His book excoriated the
authoritarianism and the corruption of government in Peru, but its name, The
Other Path, together with its message, threw down the gauntlet in the
direction of Shining Path, the brutal Maoist revolutionary movement which
threatened the Peruvian state. One evening in July last year, as de Soto sat
in his office in Lima's Miraflores district, Shining Path tried and to blow
him and his organisation, the Institute of Liberty and Democracy (ILD) out
of existence with a 400kg car bomb. The attempt failed.
De Soto's achievement was to see, in Lima's teeming millions of hawkers and
hustlers, not the dubious activities of marginals but the great mainstream
of history.
He examined the consequences of the migration from country to cities over
the last 40 years, which has quintupled Peru's urban population. Drawing
parallels with the emergence of capitalism in Europe in the 19th century, de
Soto described Peru as a mercantilist state in which most participants in
the formal economy were concerned not with the creation of wealth but rather
with the extraction of favours from government.
This mercantilist system, bolstered by governments of both the left and the
right in Peru, resulted in thousands of regulations which effectively forced
most of the new migrants to work outside the formal economy.
Yet it was a mistake to see only chaos in the shanty towns around Lima:
internal rules were established; rights over property were often recognised,
and a system of security established. De Soto estimates that there are 30
informal banking systems in the country.
From an economic standpoint, the problem with this is that it is
tremendously inefficient. To use de Soto's metaphor, it condemns individuals
to an existence in small pools. By bringing these people into the formal
economy by means of big deregulation, they will be able to join the river.
Thus one of the book's central messages was a plea to unleash the energy of
the informal sector by abandoning the mercantilist approach which has linked
government with the private sector in Peru for so long. The informal system
'shows us that what Peruvians want, first and foremost, is firm property
rights, reliable transactions and secure activities.'
De Soto estimates that 92 per cent of all rural land holdings in Peru are
not in the formal economy sector. Similarly, 60 per cent of urban land
holdings are untitled. Land makes up 80 per cent of the assets of all
Peruvians - and more than 90 per cent of the assets of the poor. De Soto
argues that being able to establish formal title over property is the key to
prosperity, as it was in Britain in the second half of the 19th century.
If things have begun to change since he wrote his book, it is partly because
de Soto's organisation is pursuing land titling. Using simple forms and
computers, some 100,000 land titles have been registered in the last 15
months.
While this is only a start, De Soto says the titling has been done more
quickly and much more cheaply (Dollars 8 per title) than in similar
exercises elsewhere in Latin America. Only 5 per cent of claims have been
the subject of dispute.
In zones where the ILD have carried out titling campaigns, the price of
property has doubled immediately, and should continue to rise over time. He
says that terrorists have moved out (although not necessarily their
political organisations) and the level of violence has fallen. And banks
have moved in - because the titles provide physical evidence of ownership
and security for lenders.
Another practical consequence of The Other Path has been the successful
campaign to bring the thousands of companies operating in the informal
sector into the formal sector, through cheap and quick registration
procedures. As an example for the book, ILD's researchers, in the summer of
1983, had attempted to establish an imaginary clothing factory - legally. It
took a group of them 289 days of full-time labour. It cost Dollars 1,231,
including expenses and lost income; the equivalent of 32 minimum monthly
wages. Bribes were solicited on 10 occasions, but only two were paid.
Setting up a street kiosk required 43 days and Dollars 590.
Now the procedures require one day and the payment of a small fee. Although
moving into the formal sector brings the risk of having to pay taxes, says
de Soto, it allows small entrepreneurs to avoid paying bribes and, for
example, to advertise their existence to potential new customers. As daily
lines for registration continue to form outside the ministry of industry,
the number of businesses being registered has grown from 2,000 a month in
1990 to 11,000 a month now.
But if these have been modest successes for de Soto, there have been
setbacks. He was formerly President Alberto Fujimori's special adviser on
drugs; he resigned last year, frustrated at the lack of progress of his
plans. He had brought together 182 local leaders from the remote areas where
coca, the raw material for producing cocaine, is grown. The idea was to
drive a wedge between the traffickers, who would continue to be hunted, and
the growers, who would not be touched. After Mr Fujimori's auto-golpe on
April 5 last year, however, de Soto's plans began to run into the sand.
If he is less than sanguine about the long-term impact of the drugs trade on
those areas of the country where 1.6m people earn a living from the coca
plant, he credits the Fujimori government with making progress on the
economic front and introducing some deregulation.
He favours privatisation of inefficient state enterprises - a policy the
government is pursuing aggressively.
Yet while change has begun, most Peruvians have not noticed it.
'Deregulation has taken place at the top; yet there has been little or no
deregulation at the level of the poor,' de Soto says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>PEZ  Peru, South America.
</CN>
