<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (18): A mutually beneficial link with China /
Profile of Hierro Peru
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STUNNED silence descended on the makeshift auction room in Lima's mines
ministry when privatisation officials announced the winning bid for Hierro
Peru, the ailing iron producer, last November.
The Shougang Corporation of the People's Republic of China had offered
almost six times the base price. Adding in long-standing company debts and a
Dollars 150m investment commitment, the Chinese were paying about Dollars
312m for an operation most observers considered ready for the scrap-heap.
Reactions varied from the incredulity of rival bidders (a consortium of
prominent Chilean, Japanese and Mexican steel producers) to the nervousness
of Peruvian economic liberals.
It was hardly appropriate, they felt, for the first big sell-off to go to
communist buyers. Others were convinced that the Chinese had got their sums
wrong, and had failed to appreciate the disastrous state of the company.
'Absolutely untrue,' says a senior Shougang official. 'We knew exactly what
we were buying, all the problems. It was a question of opportunity cost.
China needs iron and here we could buy a deposit with huge reserves and an
immediate outlet to the sea. Few iron mines in the world can compare with
Marcona.'
Now, nine months after taking control of their new investment, Shougang
managers are happy. A Dollars 35m loss in 1992 has already turned into a
small profit.
Output in the first half of 1993 was two and a half times higher than the
same period last year, although, at 2.43m long tons of concentrate, still
well below current installed capacity.
Productivity figures have improved sharply - from 156 tonnes per worker per
month last year to 325 tonnes now. Production costs have been slashed by 60
per cent in six months, partly as a result of workforce reductions - from
3,300 to 1,700. Shipments are leaving on time. Equipment and administrative
systems are being overhauled.
It is a sharp about-turn in Hierro Peru's fortunes. From 1953 until its
expropriation by the Peruvian state in 1972, the rich deposits were the
property of the US-owned Marcona Mining Company. Since then, under first
military, then civilian governments, output and installed capacity both
inexorably declined.
Output peaked in 1970, when 9.7m tonnes of concentrates were produced,
mostly shipped to Asian buyers. By 1990, it had slumped by more than
two-thirds.
Shougang has already embarked on new investment - in the second half of 1993
it will top Dollars 37m. Much will go on new shovels and drills for the
mine, rebuilding stocks of essential spare parts and a modern communications
system. Wharf facilities at the deep water port of San Nicolas (one of the
best on the Pacific coast of Latin America, and an important company asset)
are being upgraded.
Future plans are ambitious. They include raising output to 5m long tons this
year, to 7.5m next year; 10m by 1995. Total investment of around Dollars
150m will be needed to expand current installed capacity. Low-profile
company officials are reluctant to reveal longer-term plans, although there
is talk of constructing a steel plant on site and, later, a factory to
manufacture Chinese-designed tractors for export to other Latin American
countries.
Shougang could also be interested in buying Siderperu, the state-owned
steelworks and, eventually, developing the country's other big iron deposits
of Huancabamba, in the eastern jungle. There is good news, too, on the
labour front. Workers who survived the swingeing job cuts appear to have
adapted swiftly to their new Chinese managers.
'After the long, no-hope years of falling production, we're glad to be in
work,' said one local miner. Colleagues agreed, praising initiatives such as
a new consumer co-operative which offers basic goods to workers at cost.
Shougang seems bent on bringing self-sufficiency to the 23,000-inhabitant
community of San Juan de Marcona, off the beaten track and traditionally
dependent on the Hierro Peru operation.
Two small trawlers have been imported from China to provide fresh fish for
locals and agricultural and livestock projects are under way. Company
officials say these small beginnings could lead to export ventures in
fishmeal (China is Peru's big customer) and agro-industrial products,
probably asparagus.
At present, all the evidence suggests that the Shougang venture is a success
for both Peru and its Chinese purchasers. 'We're really just like any
Western industrial company in that we want to make profits,' says a senior
Shougang official. 'But perhaps our great respect for our human resources is
a peculiarity. It is certainly fundamental for Shougang.'
</TEXT>
