<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (9): Sickened by violence - The problem of
terrorism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ON September 12, the first anniversary of his capture, a video recording of
the imprisoned founder-leader of the Maoist guerrilla group Sendero Luminoso
(Shining Path) was shown to the nation by a smilingly confident Mr Alberto
Fujimori.
'This is a defeated and demoralised man,' the Peruvian president claimed, as
the recording revealed Abimael Guzman pacing the patio of his high-security
cell, pensively smoking a cigarette.
Mr Guzman remains in solitary confinement; representatives of the
International Red Cross and 'occasional intelligence officials' are his only
visitors. He appears to be surviving the rigours of prison life, but he can
have little real notion of what has happened, since last September, to the
organisation which revered him as 'Presidente Gonzalo'.
His surprise arrest in a Lima suburban house last year provoked a domino
effect. Computer records, documents and information extracted during
interrogation led Dincote, Peru's counter-subversive police, to the
hide-outs of many more key leaders.
It is hard to over-estimate the importance, or the timeliness, of the Guzman
capture. It occurred at the height of a Sendero offensive against Lima when,
for the first time ever, civilians in the capital came under attack.
Mr Carlos Bolona, then the economy and finance minister, not a man given to
exaggeration, says: 'another major car-bomb in Lima and the military would
have intervened, arguing that the country was ungovernable.'
President Fujimori claims that 95 per cent of Sendero's 'political bureau'
and 'central committee' is now either dead or behind bars. Mr Raul Gonzales,
an expert on Sendero, recently concluded that the movement 'is no longer
capable of taking power or of destabilising the government or the political
system of Peru.'
Thirteen years of guerrilla warfare and state response - from Sendero's
emergence to burn ballot-boxes in May 1980, up to the present day - have
cost at least 26,000 Peruvian lives. Mr Enrique Bernales, the former senator
who has the most reliable historical statistics on violence in Peru,
estimates the total cost in material damage at between Dollars 22bn and
Dollars 23bn - about the same as Peru's external debt.
Now Mr Bernales' statistics confirm that attacks and killings have declined.
In January 1993, for the first time in 10 years, more Peruvians died from
common violence (in road accidents, domestic disputes and so on) than from
political violence.
Mr Fujimori claims that dismantling Sendero is a result of his 'new'
counter-subversive strategy which 'emphasises intelligence work and the
participation of the people'. He attributes intelligence successes to his
close adviser, the shadowy Mr Vladimiro Montesinos, and the current head of
the joint chiefs of staff, General Nicolas Hermoza.
But, without his institutional coup of last year, on April 5, Mr Fujimori
says that recent advances would have been impossible. His seizure of
quasi-dictatorial powers allowed him to decree sharply increased penalties
for convicted terrorists (terrorism became classified as 'treason'), and to
send suspects for trial by secret military tribunals, before masked judges.
Peru's pre-coup justice system was 'a mockery and a farce,' says Mr
Fujimori. Many terrorists were freed for lack of evidence or released after
serving minimal prison terms. He claims that more people were sentenced for
crimes of terrorism under the new laws in 11 months than in 10 years under
the previous legislation.
Another important element in the Fujimori counter-subversive offensive has
been the arming, nationwide, of ronderos, or civil defence militias. This
has undoubtedly proved a popular measure among defenceless peasants whose
communities were under threat from Sendero guerrillas - although there are
already disturbing indications in some areas (such as the jungle Apurimac
valley) that ronderos are using their new-found power against the state
which armed them, and forming alliances with drugs traffickers.
Psychological tactics have also played an important role. A television
advertising campaign advised guerrilla sympathisers to 'repent, die or spend
your life in jail', as a prison door clanged shut. Almost every night
alleged terrorists, already wearing their famous striped prison suits
(reportedly designed by Mr Fujimori himself) are paraded across the small
screen.
Peruvians, sickened by the long years of violence, generally approve the
Fujimori government's tough line with suspected terrorists. International
community concern focuses on two main issues: the new counter-terrorism laws
and continuing reports of human rights violations.
Amnesty International has objected to the now widespread system of trial
behind closed doors. It warns that, if the death penalty for convicted
terrorists is approved along with the new constitution, 'prisoners could be
executed . . . following conviction in military trials that fall short of
international standards.'
New legislation also facilitates 'unacknowledged detention' - according to
Amnesty 'an underlying cause of the high level of 'disappearance',
extrajudicial execution and torture in the emergency zones.'
Peru has had, for several years, the unenviable distinction of being top of
the world's league table for disappearances. This year the figures are down
 -to 55 in the first eight months of the year, according to Mr Francisco
Soberon of Aprodeh, a Lima-based human rights organisation. Aprodeh counts a
total of 556 'disappeared' in the first three years of the Fujimori
administration.
Despite fewer disappearances, Mr Soberon believes that 'there is a
correlation between that and the rise in the number of detentions.'
According to General Hermoza, more than 4,000 suspected terrorists have been
detained since last year's coup.
Some are undoubtedly innocent. Perhaps a third of all detainees have to be
freed for lack of evidence, says Mr Soberon. 'The military are under heavy
pressure to show they are effective, so are often over-zealous in detaining
people.'
Government authorities, meanwhile, have shown themselves flat-footed in
responding to particularly shocking human rights cases. The current
investigation of human remains in a series of shallow graves near Lima (the
charred bones may be those of some of the nine students and a teacher who
'disappeared' from the La Cantuta university last July) has been painfully
slow. Offers of help from international forensic experts were rejected.
Can Peruvians - and potential foreign investors - be satisfied that
'pacification' is finally on the cards, as new hoardings on the road from
the airport to the centre of town announce?
Most observers agree that Peru's second guerrilla movement, pro-Cuban MRTA,
is as good as finished. 'The remnants are unco-ordinated bands and act
almost like common criminals,' says Mr Bernales. 'There's nothing to
indicate that it is a political organisation any more.'
With founder-leader Mr Victor Polay and his senior lieutenants all serving
life prison sentences, many MRTA militants have taken advantage of the 'laws
of repentance' and have laid down arms.
The same, however, cannot be said for hard-line Sendero Luminoso. Although
Mr Bernales' statistics indicate the movement has lost a third of its
operational capacity, 'the organisation, though weakened, remains,' he says.
In some areas, such as the coca-growing Huallaga valley and the
north-central department of Ancash, it seems to be almost intact.
While the 'quality' of Sendero attacks has fallen, according to Mr Bernales,
he questions President Fujimori's claims about the efficacy of the
intelligence service.
'Attacks are not generally failing because they are detected but because the
perpetrators are inexperienced,' he says. The army has still not adapted its
traditional strategies to allow it to respond to guerrilla harassment.
Mr Bernales warns that society should not let slip its guard - 'Sendero is
too dangerous for that,' he says. 'It's not yet the moment to shout
victory.'
</TEXT>
