<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (8): Still a force to be reckoned with -
Military power is now probably subordinate to civilian power
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE appearance of tanks in April in the streets of Lima underlined the fact
that the military remain a force to be reckoned with in Peru.
The tanks' deployment, according to military experts, appeared to be a
clumsy - although apparently successful - attempt by General Nicolas Hermoza
Rios, the head of the armed forces, to deter Congressional investigations
into the disappearance and probable murder of nine students and a professor
at the Cantuta teaching institute in Lima in 1992.
The Cantuta affair has become a cause celebre for those who want to end the
continuing immunity of the military from prosecution for human rights
abuses.
But it is more than that: it is a stick with which the opposition can beat
the government. It has also become a lightning rod for apparent divisions
within the armed forces, which some military experts say have deepened under
the government of President Alberto Fujimori.
The students disappeared from Cantuta, a well-known nest of sympathisers for
the Maoist terrorist organisation Sendero - Shining Path - in July last
year, amid an outbreak of bombings in Lima. Documents published this year by
magazines in Lima, and allegations made by General Rodolfo Robles, the
former number three in the military hierarchy, implicated Gen Hermoza and
the president's adviser of intelligence matters, Mr Vladimir Montesinos, in
this and other human rights violations. Gen Robles took refuge in the US
embassy and is now in Argentina.
These developments followed an attempted coup - or at least a coup
conspiracy - by a group of officers, of which Gen Jaime Salinas was the
figurehead leader, against the high command in November last year. The coup
plotters were planning to justify their action by citing their right to
protect the constitution, usurped in April 1992 by President Alberto
Fujimori with the support of many in the high command.
Retired General Gaston Ibanez O'Brien says he saw the actions of generals
Robles and Salinas as reflecting their frustration 'at being passed over for
promotion'. Mr Enrique Obando of the Peruvian Centre of International
Studies says that under the pre-Fujimori regime - where the head of the
armed forces were changed annually - both generals could have expected to be
commander-in-chief.
'During the government of (President Alan) Garcia, the armed forces
appointed their own high command . . . with Fujimori, under a new law, the
president chooses all the high-ranking generals and admirals. The head of
the armed forces can also now remain in office for an entire presidential
term,' says Mr Obando. 'As a result, the choice of the high command has
become politicised.'
This creates a high command, he suggests, that is loyal not to the
constitution but to the president. He describes it as a system of
'co-optation' which has intensified under the current presidency. During the
Garcia period, says Mr Obando, 'the civil government chose the most corrupt
elements in the armed forces for important positions, knowing that the
threat of making public their illegal acts would allow them to be easily
controlled.'
In the Fujimori era, Mr Obando says there has been a struggle - 'very costly
and traumatic' - within the military between the institutionally-minded and
the co-opted senior officers, in which the latter group appears to have been
almost completely victorious.
Resentment among some officers may also have been increased by the power
wielded by Mr Montesinos, who is Mr Fujimori's senior adviser on military
and intelligence matters. (Mr Montesinos, a former lawyer to Mr Fujimori,
was cashiered from the army while a captain, for copying and passing on
information to the US Central Intelligence Agency.)
The choice of high command by the civilian president underlines a
paradoxical aspect of the Fujimori government: although it is often
described as authoritarian, the power of the armed forces at the centre is
probably now more subordinate to the civilian power than at any time since
the military government stepped down in 1980 after 12 years in power.
On the other hand, the power of the armed forces in the regions - given a
freer hand by Mr Fujimori - has increased.
Mr Obando says that like all systems of co-optation this one is dependent on
success for its perpetuation and is therefore inherently unstable.
Nonetheless he believes that the likelihood of further coups against the
Fujimori government is much reduced by the advances in intelligence
gathering. This, says Mr Fujimori, helped to bring about the successes
against Shining Path. Those with knowledge of military issues, however, say
that much intelligence activity has been directed at the armed forces
themselves.
'Vigilance against those who are against Fujimori is high,' says Mr Obando.
Suspicion is such that those visiting Gen Hermoza's office have to give up
their arms before they go in, he adds. 'There are few chances to meet
outside the barracks and nobody now in the armed forces speaks about
political issues - in contrast to the time of Alan Garcia.'
</TEXT>
