<DATE>930929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (6): Sell-offs will pay for improvements -
Sally Bowen watches privatisation speeding up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR a year widely billed as 'Peru's year of privatisation' 1993 has been
surprisingly uneventful so far. But the closing three months should see a
clutch of important state company sell-offs.
Barring unexpected hitches, the attractive, partly-developed copper deposits
of Cerro Verde will be sold on October 13.
This will be only the second big public auction of the year - and a full
nine months since January's sale of flag-carrier Aeroperu to a
Mexican-Peruvian consortium for Dollars 54m.
Cerro Verde's potential - with reserves to keep a 40,000 tonne per day
concentrator plant busy for 50 years - has drawn a collection of
international mining companies to register for pre-qualification. Big names
include Cyprus Minerals and Magma Copper from the US; Lac, Cominco and
Placer Dome from Canada, Japan's Mitsui and Marubeni and Outokumpu of
Finland.
Morgan Grenfell, the UK-based investment bank, is promoting Cerro Verde in
addition to Mineroperu's three other production units and a collection of as
yet undeveloped mineral deposits. It is also under contract to handle
December's auction of the telecommunications duo Entel (the 100 per cent
state-owned long distance operator) and CPT (Lima's telephone company, in
which the state has a controlling 20 per cent).
'We see this as a very exciting market,' says Mr David Suratgar, deputy
chairman of Morgan Grenfell International, on an early September visit to
Lima. 'Anyone who saw what happened in Argentina - and in Mexico before that
 -must find Peru very interesting indeed. We thought it better to be
involved at an earlier date.'
When the Fujimori government assumed office in July 1990, 11 of the
country's 12 largest companies were owned and operated by the state. Heavily
overstaffed, protected from international competition and often
incompetently managed by the recipients of political favours, the companies
 -more than 200 of them - were costing a bankrupt nation about Dollars 2.5bn
a year.
'The principal impulse to privatise came from the need for total structural
reform of the state,' says Mr Daniel Hokama, mines and energy minister and
president of Copri, the small, agile, government privatisation commission
set up early last year. 'It has taken an enormous effort to rationalise
public companies, reduce staff and make them viable for sell-off.'
So far, sales have netted a little over Dollars 250m in cash. But future
investment commitments by purchasers will raise that figure enormously. The
Shougang Corporation of the People's Republic of China is to spend Dollars
150m on upgrading iron producer Hierro Peru in the next three years; Mantos
Blancos, the Chilean subsidiary of South African mining giant Anglo American
could invest up to Dollars 500m on developing the copper deposits of
Quellaveco, which it picked up for just Dollars 12m last December.
Government officials also consider foreign investment through privatisation
the only viable way to improve Peru's run-down infrastructure. After years
of macro-economic mismanagement, local companies are severely decapitalised
and have long been unable to meet expanded demand for public services.
Telephones are a striking example. Peru has the worst level of provision in
the Latin American continent: 2.4 lines per hundred inhabitants. December's
sell-off of the two telecommunications companies should, if the buyer
complies with terms of sale, ensure that Dollars 1bn is poured into an
expansion programme over the next five years.
During the five-year period of exclusivity (or, as Copri prefers it,
'transition to full competition') the winning bidder will expected to double
the existing 630,000 lines.
Every town with more than 500 inhabitants will be provided with telephone
services. And the waiting time will be cut from the present - unbelievable -
10 years to one year by 1996, and to one month by the year 2000.
The companies which have already registered their interest are ATT, GTE and
South-Western Bell of the US; the UK's Cable and Wireless; France Telecom;
Telefonica de Espana; STET of Italy and Korea Telecom. They are likely to
form bidding consortia with already established suppliers such as Siemens,
Alcatel, Northern Telecom and Kanematsu.
'We're enthusiastic and we're on schedule,' says Mr Suratgar. 'With every
week that passes, international interest in Peruvian privatisation is
growing.'
Not all has been plain sailing. The institutional coup of April 1992, when
Mr Fujimori closed congress and suspended the constitution, threw the
incipient flow of foreign investment into reverse gear. For a six month
period, several sell-offs flopped.
Successes were confined to a series of relatively small auctions on the
floor of the stock exchange where a handful of local entrepreneurs and some
bold Chilean investors picked up bargains.
Peruvian privatisation has also suffered its share of errors and near
fiascos. Sometimes, exaggerated base prices scared away potential bidders.
On other occasions - notably with the sale of Aeroperu - technical errors in
the back-up documentation required by Copri raised doubts over procedural
transparency.
But the privatisers seem to have learned from their mistakes. 'The
government undoubtedly overestimated its capacity to handle sales,' comments
Mr Augusto Alvarez, an economic analyst and specialist in privatisation.
'But the process is now being managed much more professionally - I foresee
no serious problems.'
If all proceeds on schedule, Cerro Verde, the telecommunications companies
and Centromin, the mining and refining giant, will be transferred to the
private sector before the year's end.
So will a series of smaller but still important state holdings in two cement
companies, the Miski gold mine, the tomato-processing plant of Chao and the
Bolivian branch of the Banco Popular.
While Mr Hokama expects these to be readily saleable, state utilities
(particularly water and parts of the electricity network) will be a tougher
proposition.
'Some of the distribution networks are uneconomic or located in areas where
security problems remain,' says Mr Hokama. 'The Chileans are hugely
interested in the more attractive sectors, but we need to find other bidders
to compete with them.'
One privatisation card yet to be played is debt paper. Mr Fujimori has long
been reluctant to countenance its use, fearing it would mean a field day for
speculators.
But Copri has its plans laid and is 'ready to handle it the moment we're
given the political green light,' said one senior official.
Copri now predicts that all Peru's main state-owned companies, with the
possible exception of Sedapal, the water company, will be transferred to the
private sector by September 1994 - well before the next round of
congressional and presidential elections.
'But whatever happens politically, the privatisation process is already
irreversible,' says Mr Hokama.
</TEXT>
