<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (5): Price has risen steeply in two years -
Creditors have been asked to show imagination over debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN A LITTLE over two years, the price of Peruvian commercial bank debt on
the secondary market has climbed tenfold from 4 cents for every dollar of
face value to more than 40 cents. The price has risen as the government has
made great efforts to re-insert itself into the international mainstream of
finance.
Many followers of this market find it difficult to understand why the price
has remained at these lofty levels. The reason, in part, is that there are
few 'plays' left in the bank debt market for speculators and an inordinate
amount of interest has been funnelled into a small amount of debt.
According to bankers close to the talks which have restarted between the
government and its leading commercial bank creditors, the International
Monetary Fund is telling the bankers there is not much in the pot for debt
servicing until the end of the millennium.
The IMF figures suggest that paying interest on all public sector debt
should amount to just under 4 per cent of gross domestic product until the
end of 1995. This is more than 40 per cent of what the government is
collecting in taxes and represents already too heavy a burden on an
administration that needs to rebuild social expenditures after the
depredations of the 1980s.
However, according to prime minister Mr Alfonso Bustamante, there is some
leeway: 'There is room to pay something to banks.' However, since 'only half
of the Dollars 6bn is principal, the rest is interest. This makes it very
difficult.' In no large bank rescheduling so far has the ratio of past due
interest to principal been so high - a problem because commercial banks like
to penalise interest arrears in reschedulings so as to discourage them.
A further problem is the more than 50 pending legal suits from banks against
the government, the most difficult of which concerns a Dollars 20m loan from
Chemical Bank made in 1984 to the now defunct Compania Peruana de Vapores.
The government of President Alan Garcia repudiated the debt, claiming that
the transaction was fraudulent.
President Albert Fujimori has asked for imagination from creditors in
approaching the debt issue. Mr Jorge Gonzales Izquierdo, head of the
economic faculty at the University of the Pacific, says that imagination has
been in short supply.
Mr Gonzales Izquierdo calls for a three-track approach to the problem: ask
for a deep debt forgiveness, including from the Paris Club of creditor
nations to which Peru owes Dollars 8bn of its total Dollars 23bn foreign
debt; get waivers from banks to buy back the commercial debt in the
secondary market; and aggressively use the debt, heavily discounted, as
currency in privatisation programmes.
The approach has not been followed in part because of the deep dislike of
Japan to debt forgiveness on its own debts. Upsetting the Japanese
government by demanding debt write-downs would potentially jeopardise new
aid flows from Tokyo, which have become especially important with the hold
up of aid flows from the US because of human rights concerns.
Furthermore, the price of the debt at the moment would act as a deterrent to
a successful buyback programme. The government says it is working on the
debt-equity conversion idea, but the soundings coming from government
officials suggest it will be less than aggressive.
Mr Bustamante says: 'We are evaluating the debt-for-equity issue. We think
that where a company is very profitable we prefer to sell for cash. Where a
company is losing money, we can sell it for debt.'
Yet the rules are still to be worked out. If the privatisation programme
goes ahead as the government is envisaging, it had better get a move on.
