<DOCNO>FT933-303</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DI2CRAGDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Survey of Peru (1): A fragile confidence begins to return -
President Alberto Fujimori's government has embarked on a programme to
stabilise and deregulate the economy - and to battle against terrorism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FRAGILE confidence is returning to Peru after a decade of violence and
economic collapse.
The two men most associated with this dismal decade are - for now at least -
safely out of the way. Abimael Guzman, the provincial academic who led the
Maoist guerrilla group Sendero Luminoso in a battle against the state, is
behind bars, his campaign having caused the deaths of 26,000 people and
Dollars 22bn of damage.
The former head of state Alan Garcia, president from 1985 to 1990, is in
exile. His government turned the country into the pariah of international
finance by not servicing its foreign debt. Worse: it squandered the
resources that it gained by not paying. After a short state-financed boom,
the economy collapsed and hyper-inflation, peaking at 397 per cent a month,
ensued.
The two men were as much manifestations as architects of Peru's ills. The
society was as deeply divided on racial lines as any in South America:
Sendero's essentially middle-class leadership fed on the resentment among
the poor indigenous groups that this fostered. The Garcia government
meanwhile represented the corrupt culmination of years of statism which
intensified Peru's already profound poverty.
Given this, it would be unrealistic to expect an economic quick fix.
Nonetheless, matters have improved sufficiently for investors, internal and
external, to begin a gradual return to the country. Since the arrest in
September, 1992, of Guzman and the detention of other guerrilla leaders, the
political risk of investment is viewed as considerably diminished.
Furthermore, investor confidence has been spurred by the privatisation plans
of the government of President Alberto Fujimori - now apparently moving
ahead after numerous delays - and its investment and other reforms. The
government is back in the good graces of the international financial
institutions in Washington, having cleared its arrears to them and begun
negotiations with foreign commercial banks. Its foreign reserves, which were
negative at times in 1988, have risen to levels high enough to cover seven
months of imports, and inflation is down to double-digit annual levels.
In the last few months, the economic picture has improved further. The
economy has started to pick up this year, enough at least to erase the
effects of a weak 1992 when the austere fiscal targets of an International
Monetary Fund programme, terrorism and drought-induced electricity shortages
resulted in the economy shrinking by 3 per cent.
After falling sharply early in the Fujimori government, inflation became
sticky. Now it may be falling again. Mr Jorge Gonzales Izquierdo, the
Chicago-educated dean of the economics faculty of the University of the
Pacific, says the improvement follows a shift in central bank policy. This
year the bank stopped targeting the exchange rate - a policy which led last
year to a appreciation of the real value of the Peruvian currency, the sol,
to the displeasure of exporters - and now seeks to curb excessive money
supply growth.
Yet these advances have yet to show through as tangible benefits to a
population, nearly 60 per cent of whom were in absolute poverty in 1989,
according to the World Bank. Mr Fujimori remains popular because he is seen
as having brought security and a more stable economy, not because he has
advanced the material conditions of Peruvians.
Mr Fujimori, who took office in 1990 for a five-year term, is not a natural
economic reformer. It took time for him to be persuaded that privatisation
was beneficial. He emphasises his government's pragmatism, which liberal
critics read as a suggestion that his market-oriented policies depend on his
continued popularity.
Although Mr Carlos Bolona, economy minister for 23 months until he was
sacked in January, has regularly fallen out with the president, he gives him
the benefit of the doubt: 'It's true that Fujimori is not a convinced
liberal, but in his pragmatism, he has backed a programme that has seen
results.'
But even Mr Bolona says that the reform is not moving ahead as he would
like. 'Until now we are still on track. For two years we were moving ahead
with full speed. Now we are moving ahead by inertia.'
PART of the problem is the lack of a large team to push economic reform
forward. Only a handful of people is helping Mr Jorge Camet, the 65-year-old
minister of economy, a much smaller group than those who pursued reform in
Mexico, Argentina, or even Bolivia.
The small size of the group has also hindered implementation of legislation
already passed - the government's labour law reform is an example - because
there is nobody to draft the rules.
Furthermore, even according to its supporters, the government persists in
policies which continue economic distortions. The expensive support of
irrigation projects in the north and the continuing import taxes on
foodstuffs such as rice, wheat, sugar and milk, which overwhelmingly benefit
agricultural co-operatives in the north and do little to help the poorest
farmers in the mountains, are two examples.
On top of that, according to market-oriented economists, new distortions are
being introduced. The government is proposing that a 9 per cent tax paid by
employees to Fonavi, the state housing fund, should be changed, leaving 3
per cent to be paid by workers and 6 per cent by the companies that employ
them. What is in effect a new payroll tax could well deter future employment
and wage increases.
Mr Gonzales Izquierdo is also critical of the government for not placing
enough emphasis early in its term on social spending, for example on
education. Now that is changing, Mr Fujimori is emphasising physical
spending - for example on new school buildings and computers rather than on
quality of the education.
Tackling social problems is hindered by a lack of state resources, brought
about by problems with tax collection. Mr Fujimori has acknowledged this as
an issue constraining the government. Mr Gonzales Izquierdo says that the
state's poor performance in tax collection - along with a foreign debt
standing at a worrying five times annual exports - represents an Achilles
heel in economic policy.
'In the last three months, in real terms, tax collection has fallen. This is
very serious,' says Mr Gonzales Izquierdo. He calculates that tax collection
 -which he estimates will turn out at about 8.8 per cent of GDP this year -
will fall short of the 9.1 per cent called for in the IMF programme signed
earlier this year.
(This assumes that the actual size of the Peruvian economy is in line with
official figures suggesting a GDP of more than Dollars 40bn, which is almost
certainly an exaggeration. Given the size of the informal sector and the
high dollarisation of the economy, estimating GDP is pretty much guesswork.
Estimates vary between Dollars 20bn and Dollars 40bn. The University of the
Pacific, estimating that the informal economy accounts for 40 per cent of
all economic activity, has come up with a Dollars 30bn figure.)
The government inherited a tax system devastated by hyper-inflation. By the
end of the Garcia era, Peruvians were paying only 4.4 per cent of GDP, using
official figures, compared with an historical norm ranging from 15 per cent
to 20 per cent in exceptional years.
The IMF is seeking a tax collection target of 13 per cent (based on official
GDP statistics) by 1995. Whether this can be achieved depends on how much
GDP is being overestimated. If GDP is really only Dollars 20bn, tax
collection must actually rise to a figure of about 25 per cent to meet
targets which, given the extent of activity in the informal economy, mean a
heavy burden on the minority who pay tax.
Thus a potentially vicious circle is developing, with high taxes driving
more and more taxpayers either partially or wholly into the informal economy
and narrowing the tax base still further.
Still, it is credible to argue that the way forward for Peru has been
trail-blazed by Chile, which pursued growth by exploiting its comparative
advantage in the production of raw materials. In some areas, Peru's
comparative advantage is greater than Chile's, and the prices of assets in
Peru are significantly cheaper.
The question investors are asking, therefore, is whether the government can
retain the upper hand against terrorism, and what are the risks of a sharp
reverse in economic policy which would, for example, halt foreign exchange
remittances.
GIVEN the successes against the leadership of Sendero Luminoso, few people
in Lima appear to expect a resurgence of the bombings that so sapped
confidence in the capital last year. However, a few big bombs could
underline the fragility of this view.
Furthermore, even if Sendero is defeated in the countryside - and it is
still powerful in many areas - Mr Fujimori's policy of arming civilians to
fight terrorism means there are many more weapons in circulation in Peru. As
has already happened in some zones, banditry - often linked to the cocaine
trade - may replace terrorism as the number one security problem.
On the economic front, Mr Fujimori says a new constitution - to replace the
statist-inclined charter of 1979 - and his two further years in office will
be the true guarantor that economic change is permanent. The new
constitution, which will be put to a referendum on October 31, contains
important changes, some elements of which are seen as necessary - for
example a reform of a corrupt judicial system.
Yet, because the changes are so wide-ranging - they include a proposal to
reintroduce the death penalty - they may encourage a rainbow of opposition,
beyond the traditional political parties Mr Fujimori purports to despise.
Most opinion polls suggest the new constitution will secure a majority, but
unless that majority is large, the temptation will be great for a successor
government to change it again.
Constitutions in Latin America in any case often mean little. What worries
some people in Lima even more is the personal nature of Mr Fujimori's style
of government. Mr Fujimori is not viewed as an institution builder, and he
has centralised power since he took office. He has done little to establish
the rule of law - indeed he undermined it, by suspending the constitution on
April 5 last year. Human rights abuses by the security forces continue to
bring domestic and international condemnation.
'He has been good at destroying the bad; but he has been less effective at
creating something to take its place,' says Mr Augusto Alvarez, economic
analyst and editor.
While he is still popular with many poor Peruvians, who see him as an
outsider, like themselves, Mr Fujimori seems to trust few people. He appears
to owe few favours to the traditionally powerful in Peru. Yet, while this
has had the benefit of giving him a free hand in policy-making and has freed
most of his administration from the taint of corruption accusations, it may
also have encouraged policy mistakes. For example, he underestimated the
adverse international reaction to his April 5 usurping of the constitution,
a reaction that nearly killed off his economic programme.
This has also increased speculation about the few people he does appear to
trust, in particular his adviser on security and intelligence matters, Mr
Vladimiro Montesinos. In a survey carried out by a Lima magazine, the
little-known Mr Montesinos - who won a libel action against a publication
describing him as a Rasputin - was adjudged the second most powerful man in
the country.
Mr Fujimori paints himself as a new-style leader in contrast with the
corrupt traditional party politicians that went before him.
In some senses, this is true: he has no real party, which in part explains,
says Mr Enrique Obando of the Peruvian Institute for International Studies,
his reliance on the army. Yet in Mr Fujimori's authoritarian streak, many
see the stamp of the traditional Latin American leader.
Most people believe that Mr Fujimori wants a second term of office, though
he denies it, and one of the proposed changes to the constitution would
allow him to run again.
The president, therefore, has a fine line to walk. To win the election, he
may be tempted to depict himself as the only person who can save the
country. But to get the economy going again and to reassure investors, he
cannot afford to scare people too much about what will happen if somebody
else wins.
</TEXT>
