<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
DERIVATIVES markets continued to trade busily yesterday, with some of the
interest turning towards the individual share index options. Stock index
futures again led the stock market forward, and a 35 point premium against
cash on the December contract opened up the opportunity for significant
arbitrage trading.
After a slow start, the December contract strengthened again, quickly
showing the 35 point premium against the underlying market that it was to
maintain virtually thoughout the day. Dealers said that the lessening in
tensions in Russia, together with hopes for base rate cut at home, had
brought buyers back into index futures. Salomon, the US investment bank, was
an active player but was joined in arbitrage business by several UK houses.
December closed with its 35 point premium intact, showing a 24 point premium
over the fair value calculation which allows for dividend and financing
flows. Volume, at 9,428, was a shade below the previous day.
Traded options activity jumped from 23,835 contracts to 33,425, with the
FT-SE contract nearly doubling turnover to 18,907. Among stock contracts,
TSB traded 2,295 contracts on hopes that Hill Samuel, its merchant bank
subsidiary, will shortly be sold off.
The Euro FT-SE contract saw increased business to record 1,350 deals.
</TEXT>
