<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Blue chips consolidate as
bonds lose steam
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
BLUE CHIP issues spent the day consolidating their position after Monday's
strength on the back of a surge in bond prices, the latter being only
slightly higher by yesterday's close. But the over-the-counter stocks set
another record peak, agencies report from New York.
Amid the currents of quarter-end window dressing, the Dow Jones Industrial
Average blue chip indicator, which finished on Monday night some 24 points
higher, drifted within an 11-point band before ending 1.68 down on the day
at 3,566.02.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was off 0.27 at 461.53, but the
Nasdaq composite rose 3.71 to another all-time high of 763.66 and the
American SE composite was up 0.68 at 457.12. Trading volume on the New York
SE amounted to 243m shares.
Market participants commented that there was little news to affect the
overall market, although traders were keeping a watch on developments in
Russia.
The day's economic news did not inspire activity after the Conference Board
reported that its consumer confidence index had risen to 62.6 this month
from a revised 59.3 in August.
Analysts said they did not detect much reaction in the equity market to
congressional testimony by First Lady Hillary Clinton on health care reform.
She said a national board would study the suitability of drug prices, but
not set them. One analyst said some drug stocks reacted negatively to the
pricing comments.
Bookstore chain initial public offering Barnes &amp; Noble headed the Big Board
volume list, ending at Dollars 29 3/8 after being priced at Dollars 20.
Spectrum Information jumped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 6, topping Nasdaq
activity. It received a patent for technology connecting portable computers
to cellular telephones.
Among strong technology shares, Microsoft advanced Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars
84, while Intel rose Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 72 3/4 , Cisco Systems Dollars
1 1/8 to Dollars 52, Novell Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 18 5/8 and SynOptics
Dollars 1 to Dollars 25 1/4 .
Canada
TORONTO stocks finished lower after moderate activity, with little to
inspire the market, and dealers said the tone would remain soft as election
uncertainty mounts. An analyst said there was a little bit of end-of-month
window dressing. The TSE 300 index was off 5.0 at 3,978.8 and declines led
advances by 377 to 326 after volume of 51.3m shares.
The 14 stock groups were evenly divided between winners and losers. The
financial services index was down 1.03 per cent. Transportation stocks
recorded the day's biggest change, falling 2.12 per cent.
BCE dipped CDollars  1/4 to CDollars 44 3/4 . Its Bell Canada unit announced
a number of cost-cutting measures designed to reduce expenses by CDollars
466m in 1994. The measures include work cutbacks equivalent to removing
5,000 employees from its workforce. Bell added that it will cut its 1994
capital budget by CDollars 300m.
</TEXT>
