<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Biggest gold find yet reported
in Venezuela
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN and NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS, SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CANADA'S PLACER Dome has identified 150 tonnes (about 4.8m troy ounces) of
proven reserves of gold in Venezuela's traditional gold mining zone,
according to a report published yesterday in Economia Hoy, a Caracas
newspaper.
The report, which could not be confirmed immediately, said that the
newly-identified reserves lay in a mining concession called Las Cristinas
that Placer Dome shared with the CVG, a large industrial and mining company
owned by the Venezuelan government.
The concession area is to the south of the evocatively-named town of El
Dorado in the south-eastern state of Bolivar, where Venezuela's gold mining
activities are concentrated. Ore in the deposit holds 1.32 grammes of gold
per tonne, according to the report.
The deposit is about 2km long and lies at a depth of some 200m. It was found
after two years of prospecting and investment outlays of about USDollars
10m.
Depending on the extraction technique used, Placer Dome could produce up to
15 tonnes a year, the report said. That would far outstrip production by the
government's gold mining company, Minerven, which reached just over 2 tonnes
last year.
Venezuela's great potential for gold has been well known for many years, but
large-scale commercial development of both subterranean and sedimentary
deposits has been delayed, usually because of concerns over the legal status
of concessions, outdated mining laws and tax issues, among other reasons.
Shares in Samantha Gold were suspended at the company's request yesterday
after the Western Australian gold mining company reported a new gold
discovery at its main Higginsville prospect, to the east of Pioneer Dome,
writes Nikki Tait in Sydney.
Samantha said that follow-up drilling in its joint venture with Geographe
Resources and Great Southern Mines was obtaining 'very significant' results.
It commented that assay results indicated 'very strong values over the 80m
strike length tested to date, with wide mineralisation widths'. The company
added that these initial results indicated the first significant gold
discovery on that side of the Pioneer Dome site.
'The drill intersections are the best that Samantha has encountered since it
commenced operations at Higginsville and the new tenement areas are
considered to have substantial potential for further discoveries,' it said.
The company's shares are expected to start trading again today.
</TEXT>
