FT  29 SEP 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Buyers losing taste for
expensive natural vanilla - Overpricing is costing market share for
Madagascar's high quality product
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR GUILD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE INCINERATION ends, but the producers are still the big loosers
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
that was how one local newspaper headlined the recent destruction of 1,700
tonnes of vanilla stocks in the north-east of Madagascar.
Madagascar's vanilla, the country's number one export by value, fetches top
prices of more than USDollars 70 a kilogram. But the grower sees precious
little of that - the official farmgate price last year was MgFr2,000
(Dollars 1.04) for 1kg of pods.
In the 1960s a vanilla price stabilisation fund was established with the
intention of channelling investment into the industry. But it receives only
a small proportion of the 80 per cent levy on the export price. A growing
amount has been spent on keeping stocks, and much of the stockpile is
thought to be of either poor quality or 'phantom' pods. The cost of keeping
stocks increased from MgFr10m in 1980 to MgFr9bn in 1990, and the bulk of
what is left of the levy has been disappearing into the national treasury.
While the government has sought to control every aspect of vanilla
production, illicit exports of vanilla have been growing, a reflection of
declining morale, particularly among farmers. This year, unauthorised
shipments turned up in Singapore, Holland and France. This has been mostly
inferior quality vanilla, picked too early and offered at low prices,
undermining confidence among the major holders of vanilla stocks in
industrialised countries.
Vanilla was first introduced to Madagascar in the 1840s. Annual rainfall on
the north-east coast where the growing and processing are concentrated is
2,000mm, evenly spread over the year. Temperatures range from 18' C to 32'
C.
There are now about 55,000 farmers growing vanilla in Madagascar. The
cultivation and processing of the crop is skilled and labour intensive. A
skilled worker can pollinate between 1,000 and 1,500 flowers in a day, but
if over-pollinated a vine will yield small and low quality pods. Curing
takes many months of sorting, 'killing', sweating, drying, conditioning and
meticulous inspection to induce the development of the full aroma and
flavour.
Madagascar has built its reputation on its knowhow. It also has the labour
and production costs are low, estimated at less than Dollars 15 a kilogram,
compared with Dollars 35 for Indonesian vanilla and over Dollars 40 in the
Comores. Vanilla production is so labour intensive, that rapidly
industrialising countries, with increasing labour costs such as Mexico have
had to reassess their involvement with the crop.
But Madagascar has been rapidly losing its market share. In the early 1970s,
it supplied 70 per cent of the vanilla consumed worldwide. By the early
1990s, its share was down to 50 per cent. High prices and now illicit
shipments of poor quality vanilla are prompting consumers to look for
cheaper alternative sources.
The Indonesian government has been encouraging farmers to start growing
vanilla. It is also seeking to improve the quality of its pods, in
particular, to increase the aroma flavour, strength and character. For
instance, it is trying to educate farmers not to pick pods early. The curers
and Indonesian research institutes are working with the British Natural
Resources Institute to improve curing techniques, and in particular the
measuring of moisture content.
Vanilla production in Uganda, which ceased during the political upheavals of
the 1970s, is rising again. There are already more than 10,000 farmers
growing the crop and the price they receive is almost three times that paid
to growers in Madagascar. One of Uganda's processors, which produces two
thirds of the country's vanilla, uses a method of rapid curing, introduced
by the US spice company McCormicks. This cuts the curing time from six
months to four days. And the vanillin content is twice that of pods cured by
the traditional Bourbon method as used in Madagascar.
The high price of Madagascar's vanilla has been largely to blame also for
the increasing partial substitution of other natural aromas for vanilla and
the switch to cheaper synthetic vanillin flavourings. The cheapest, Chinese
vanillin has been selling at Dollars 11 a kilogram.
In the US, which consumes 60 per cent of the world's natural vanilla,
vanillin now takes more than 90 per cent of the market for that aroma and in
France it supplies about 50 per cent of the market.
'We've been selling a product which every year has been getting worse and
worse,' says the director of one of the largest vanilla exporters in
Madagascar.
'A lot of the experienced planters have been giving up vanilla, so the basic
structure from which new farmers could learn has been collapsing.'
This year, the government agreed to improve incentives to growers,
processors and exporters, doubling the proportion of the export levy they
receive over the next three years. But it has yet to agree to a
liberalisation of the sector, and in particular of pricing. According to a
World Bank report in 1991, Madagascar's vanilla would be more realistically
priced at about Dollars 50 a kilogram, the price of Indonesia's best quality
pods.
Liberalisation is being resisted, particularly by the large exporters. 'For
the past 30 years, Madagascar has managed to secure pretty much the price it
wanted. The effect of telling the country to liberalise has been to
destabilise the whole situation,' says the director of one vanilla exporting
company.
'In the short term freeing of prices might benefit the consumers, but sooner
or later the quality would be bound to suffer.'
Judging by market reports from the US, there is now a trend towards natural
vanilla in an increasingly health and environment conscious food industry,
especially in premium brand ice creams and drinks.
Vanilla is the only flavour specifically defined by the Food and Drug
Administration. According to FDA guidelines a product labelled natural
vanilla should use pure vanilla extract.
But according to the World Bank, Madagascar risks becoming a residual
supplier of the flavouring, supplying the market only when crops in other
countries fail. Unless it takes drastic action, says the bank, Madagascar
could cease being a vanilla exporter altogether by the end of the 1990s.
</TEXT>
