<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Copper close to six-year lows
as stocks surge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON METAL Exchange copper prices came under renewed pressure yesterday
from investment fund selling and was forced the market to retest the lows
reached last week in the aftermath of the sudden ending of the recent
technical supply squeeze.
With sentiment further depressed by news of another big rise in exchange
warehouse stocks of the metal the three months price fell by Dollars 42 to
Dollars 1,735 a tonne at one stage, just Dollars 2 above last Tuesday's near
six-year low. But support was again found at that level, largely from other
investment funds, which had already sold the market short and were now
making covering purchases. The price ended after-hours trading at Dollars
1,738.50 a tonne.
While copper's fundamentals remained far from encouraging, market operators
might be adopting a more cautious approach because of a growing awareness
that the market could soon become seriously oversold, Mr Ted Arnold, metals
analyst at the Merrill Lynch financial services group, suggested. He pointed
out that supplies of copper scrap tended to 'dry up' if the price price
moved much below 80 US cents a lb - yesterday's close worked out at 79 cents
a lb. At that price the flow of toll refined metal from the former Soviet
Union might also be expected to slacken, Mr Arnold added.
A study of the copper market published this week points out, however, that
more than 90 per cent of western world copper mine production was at cash
costs of below 80 cents a lb in 1992, while much of the new capacity
encouraged by relatively high prices for the metal in recent years uses the
low-cost solvent extraction or electrowinning technology.
AME Mineral Economics says in its report, Copper 1993 - Growth but no Cheer,
that this SX-EW capacity 'will stay in production regardless of copper
prices'. It also suggests that the former eastern bloc, which exported
nearly 450,000 tonnes of copper to the West last year, is 'another source of
inelastic supply'.
On the demand side AME sees newly industrialising Asian economies continuing
to be a strong growth area for copper. East Asia is already the leading
consumer of the metal, with demand having increased between 1980 and 1992 at
an average annual compound rate of 5.2 per cent, compared with 2 per cent in
Europe and 0.8 per cent in the US, the report points out. And the region's
economy is 'forecast to grow at one and a half times the world average in
future decades'.
AME concludes: 'These two forces in concert will usher in a period a period
of relatively strong growth in copper consumption in association with a
ratcheting down of price expectations. Despite the positive outlook for
copper offtake in Asia, new low-cost sources of supply will hold prices down
to 90 cents a lb or less over the next five years'.
Copper 1993 - Growth but no Cheer. Price USDollars 2,250 (ADollars 2,950),
from AME Mineral Economics, GPO Box 3602, Sydney 2001, Australia.
