<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Harvest hopes push Chicago
soyabean futures lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHIACGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROSPECTS FOR fine harvesting weather in the US pushed soyabean prices lower
at the Chicago Board of Trade yesterday and overshadowed forecasts for the
season's first killing frost. In late trading the January futures position,
which had fallen by 8 1/4 cents on Monday, was down another 8 1/2 cents at
637 cents a bushel.
'I'm forecasting open weather this week, and that will give the combines a
chance to roll,' said Merrill Lynch's chief meteorologist, Mr Thad Chupalio.
The dry weather will be welcomed by farmers, many of whom experienced
drenching, harvest-stalling rains last weekend.
Although Mr Chupalio and many other forecasters are predicting that there
will be a freeze over much of the central US maize and soyabean growing
regions, including central Illinois, by Thursday, traders have already taken
account of potential frost losses in their assessments of the market.
Soyabean prices have been creeping higher on frost fears since early
September, contrary to a seasonal tendency for prices to slump as harvest
approaches.
The higher prices may have discouraged export sales of the new crop. 'We
will lose some bushels to a freeze, but we will lose as much or more in
offsetting export demand,' says Mr Dan Cekander, a crop analyst with the
Chicago brokerage firm Rodman and Renshaw.
Mr Cekander expects US soyabean and meal exports to the European Community
to drop by as much as 7 per cent this year as the community's farmers switch
from soyameal to less expensive livestock feeds.
US soya products also face stiff competition from other producers. Brazilian
farmers begin seeding soyabeans this week, and could be encouraged to
broaden plantings if world prices, as reflected on the Chicago Board of
Trade, remain firm.
US soyabean exports in September are running nearly 50 per cent behind 1992
levels and export sales of the new crop beans are lagging by a similar
amount.
'Our export inspections were only half of what we need to meet the
government's export estimates,' said Mr Richard Feltes, senior analyst for
the Refco trade house.
The export figures, which were released in a weekly report Monday, prompted
many traders, including big futures funds, to lighten their holdings of
soyabean futures. The data showed only 20.7m bushels of soyabeans had left
US ports for export destinations since September 1, compared with 48m
bushels a year ago.
