<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / International Capital Markets: Bank supervisor calls for
tougher futures regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A LEADING international bank supervisor has called for separately
capitalised subsidiaries of securities houses which trade financial
derivatives such as swaps and options to be brought under regulatory control
in the US.
Mr Brian Quinn, executive director of the Bank of England, said he could see
no justification for derivatives subsidiaries of US banks and securities
houses not to be covered by consolidated supervision of the parent.
Mr Quinn made his call in a speech in which he warned of potential risks to
the stability of the financial system from the rapid growth in the Dollars
4,500bn market in over-the-counter derivatives traded by banks and
securities firms.
Mr Quinn, who was speaking at a seminar organised in Washington by the G30
group of banks and financial institutions, criticised part of a recent
derivatives study sponsored by G30 as 'somewhat complacent' over systemic
risk.
Mr Quinn's caution was supported by other supervisors. Mr William McDonough,
president of the New York Federal Reserve Bank said that it appeared that
credit risk was not yet fully reflected in the pricing of derivatives.
Separately, Mr Eugene Ludwig, the US comptroller of the currency and
administrator of 3,500 nationally chartered banks, called for the creation
of a task force to examine banks' derivatives activities.
Mr Ludwig said in a speech to the International Institute of Bankers that
national banks involved in derivatives should adopt 'no surprises'
techniques of risk management that were 'made concrete in systems and
controls'.
Mr Quinn's call for derivatives units to be regulated follows the
establishment of such units by Merrill Lynch and Salomon Brothers. Under US
law, they are not subject to regulation by the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
Mr Quinn said that the section of the G30 report on systemic risk 'struck me
as somewhat complacent' and the rapid growth of derivatives could be leading
to credit risk problems similar to less developed country debt.
He said the growth of banks seeking to enter the market could outstrip the
number of traders expert enough to handle derivatives. If so, 'there can
only be trouble ahead. Derivatives trading is for grown-ups,' he said.
He said the G30 report's assertion that market participants should judge for
themselves whether to deal with unregulated units 'certainly makes one stop
and blink'.
Sir Dennis Weatherstone, chairman of JP Morgan and the leader of the G30
study said the study had concentrated most on other aspects of risk, but
added that on systemic risk 'if several people thought it was complacent, it
probably was'.
</TEXT>
