<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / International Bonds: GECC draws German interest with L200bn
offering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE was a lull in the international bond market yesterday as the
International Monetary Fund meetings continued in Washington. However, the
volume of new issues is expected to pick up markedly in the next few weeks.
Belgium is likely to launch a five-year Eurobond issue of between Dollars
400m and Dollars 500m in the first half of October. Some syndicate managers
said that the sovereign borrower could achieve a better execution through an
offering of floating-rate notes (FRNs), as opposed to a fixed-rate deal.
News that Finland had made a Dollars 2bn shelf registration with the US
Securities and Exchange Commission on Friday has fuelled speculation that a
global offering will be launched soon, in spite of denials from the Finnish
finance ministry.
The European Community is reported to be considering a Eurobond issue of up
to DM2bn, or the equivalent in Ecus, while the Spanish region of Andalucia
is thought to be seeking to raise D-Marks or French francs.
Megal, the Franco-German gas pipeline group which has been absent from the
Euromarket since 1989, is looking to raise D-Marks.
Among yesterday's offerings, GECC launched a L200bn offering of five-year
Eurobonds, the proceeds of which were thought to have been swapped into
fixed-rate dollars at an all-in cost of 15 basis points below the London
interbank offered rate (Libor).
Some syndicate managers said the bonds were tightly priced but an official
at lead manager Paribas said the pricing was in line with secondary market
levels. The bonds traded at 99.75 in the afternoon, comfortably within fees.
The Paribas official said that there was particular demand for the bonds
from Germany but that investors in Switzerland and the Benelux countries had
expressed an interest.
Continued investor demand for high-yielding paper ensured an enthusiastic
reception for Philippine National Oil Company's (PNOC) first Eurobond issue.
Demand was such that the five-year offering raised Dollars 90m, compared
with a planned amount of Dollars 60m.
The bonds were priced to yield 265 basis points over the 4 3/4 per cent US
Treasury due 1998, well below the indicated yield spread of 270 to 290 basis
points.
Trading in the bonds opened at 100.50, well above the re-offer price of
99.63, and there were reports that the bonds traded briefly above 101.
An official at the lead manager JP Morgan said that over half of the bonds
were sold to investors in Asia Pacific while the remainder was divided
equally between Europe and the US. Private clients and emerging market funds
featured among the buyers.
PNOC's issue is expected to be followed by a five-year deal of about Dollars
150m from Philippine National Power Company, via Morgan Stanley.
The spread on the issue is expected to be tighter than PNOC's offering,
because it will be guaranteed by the government.
Continued demand for FRNs enabled Spintab, the Swedish domestic mortgage
association owned by Swedbank, to raise a further Dollars 100m by re-opening
its Dollars 250m FRN offering which was launched in late August.
Nordic borrowers have enjoyed a significant improvement in the spreads they
have to pay in the Eurobond market as investors take a more balanced view on
the region's creditworthiness.
</TEXT>
