<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / International Company News: Switch of focus expected from
Hutchison Telecom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEPARTURE of Hutchison Telecommunications managing director, Mr Richard
Siemens, has heightened expectations that the Hong Kong conglomerate is to
sell part of its UK telecommunications operations and focus future
investment on Hong Kong and China.
Mr Siemens' resignation followed that of Hutchison Whampoa managing director
Mr Simon Murray, who was the fellow architect of the group's billion dollar
expansion into mobile telecommunications in Britain. The group is developing
PCN and CT2 networks in the UK.
This expansion is now being curtailed. Mr Li Ka-shing, chairman, and Canning
Fok, Mr Murray's successor, have both expressed concern over the amount of
capital required, and the long-term nature of the investment.
Mr Siemens has been replaced by Khoo Chek-ngee, former vice-president of
mobile communications at Singapore Telecommunication. Mr Chek-ngee's Asian
experience further emphasises Hutchison's strategy of retrenching overseas,
but expanding in China.
Mr Siemens had run the group's telecommunications operations since 1985. The
Hong Kong business contributed an operating profit of around HKDollars 600m
(USDollars 77m) last year. However, this was almost entirely absorbed by
losses from the UK side.
Hutchison Telecommunications UK is 65 per cent owned by Hutchison
Telecommunications. British Aerospace owns a further 30 per cent.
