<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / International Company News: ITT buys 80% of GM automotive
offshoot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITT, the US conglomerate, is spending Dollars 400m to buy 80 per cent of a
General Motors automotive components company which makes motors and wiper
systems.
The deal marks a substantial expansion of ITT's already large automotive
components business and is part of a strategy by GM to slim down its
Automotive Components Group as it concentrates on restoring its North
American vehicle assembly operations to profit.
GM will retain a 20 per cent interest in the business, which will be managed
and operated by ITT and employ the unit's existing workforce of more than
5,400. GM will continue to buy components and systems from the company under
a long-term supply agreement. It is expected to account initially for 90 per
cent of its sales.
The business, which had sales of Dollars 760m last year and is said to be
profitable, is a leading supplier in North America of motors for windscreen
wipers, power antennae and seats as well as making complete wiper systems.
The acquisition appears a good fit for ITT, which is a leading supplier of
these products in Europe but has no US manufacturing presence in this area.
ITT's automotive parts business has annual revenues of around Dollars 3.5bn.
The GM business also makes air movement components and electro-mechanical
devices, which ITT said was an area of growth opportunity in Europe.
The unit has an engineering and technical centre in Dayton, Ohio and plants
in Rochester, New York, and Nuevo Laredo and Juarez in Mexico.
The sale is consistent with GM's policy announced last December of disposing
of automotive components businesses which were uncompetitive or required too
much capital.
Earlier this month it announced plans to sell five parts-making plants,
employing 6,800 workers, to American Axle &amp; Manufacturing, a company formed
to buy the assets.
The disposals come as GM and the United Auto Workers union are preparing for
talks over a new labour contract focusing on job security. The UAW is wary
of GM plant sales, though it will continue representing workers at American
Axle and those at the motors unit are represented by the International Union
of Electrical Workers.
Mr Timothy Leuliette, chief executive of ITT's automotive business, said the
deal reinforced ITT's commitment to the global auto industry. It would
'strengthen our position in these strategic product lines and further
balance our sales between Europe and North America'.
</TEXT>
