<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / International Company News: Fiat unveils L5,000bn
cash-raising package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FIAT, Italy's biggest private company, yesterday launched a large
cash-raising plan combining a rights issue and the sale of its Rinascente
retailing subsidiary.
The complex package also contained the surprise that Mr Giovanni Agnelli,
chairman, and Mr Cesare Romiti, managing director, will stay on two years
longer than expected, to mid-1996.
The group plunged into a L966bn (Dollars 612.6m) loss in the first half
against pre-tax profit of L655bn last time, reflecting the severe downturn
in the core car business and continuing difficulties at some of its other
industrial activities.
First-half sales fell 2.5 per cent to L29,393bn, principally due to a 11.7
per cent fall in sales of cars and a drop of almost 16 per cent in trucks.
Fiat forecast that full-year earnings, before extraordinary items such as
asset sales, would remain in the red because of the sharp fall in demand.
Reflecting the cost of its investment programme, the group's net financial
position rose to a deficit of L6,983bn from L3,849bn at the end of December.
The cash-raising plans were immediately seen by analysts as a defensive
move, and a step back from hopes to renew management, which has been largely
discredited by Italy's political corruption scandal.
Fiat will meet the heavy costs of its ambitious investment and model renewel
programme with a L5,000bn cash- raising package. About L3,235bn will come
through a two-for-three rights issue of new ordinary, preference and savings
shares, priced at L2,000. A further L194bn will come from new savings shares
for Fiat employees.
Warrants, linked to the new shares and exercisable by the end of next year,
will provide an additional L857bn by offering shareholders new ordinary
shares at L1,000 each.
Fiat will raise a further L615bn from Alcatel Alsthom, the French industrial
group which bought its Telettra telecommunications subsidiary in 1991.
Alcatel Alsthom will buy 18m Fiat shares at L7,000 each, and take up rights
to new stock, raising its stake in the group to 2.2 per cent from 1.
The French group will enter a 'hard core' of Fiat shareholders, which will
form a shareholders' pact to control 30 per cent of the group. The pact,
comprising Ifi and Ifil, two listed investment companies dominated by Fiat's
controlling Agnelli family, will also have Deutsche Bank and Mediobanca
among its members.
Separately, Generali, Italy's biggest insurance group, will buy 35m Fiat
shares and take part in the rights issue, giving it a 2.4 per cent stake. In
return, Fiat will spend about L160bn buying a 40 per cent stake in
Generali's Paris-based Europ Assistance insurance services subsidiary.
The Rinascente sale involves an offer to Fiat shareholders of the group's 58
per cent holding in the retailer's ordinary shares. Fiat share holders will
be offered four Rinascente shares for every 100 of Fiat's.
</TEXT>
