<PROFILE>_AN-DI2CRAEJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Overseas sales lift Watts Blake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRONG OVERSEAS sales and currency benefits helped Watts Blake Bearne lift
interim pre-tax profits from Pounds 3.74m to Pounds 4.26m, leaving the
world's largest supplier of ball clay on track for meeting its forecast of
Pounds 8.6m before the costs of fending off an unsuccessful takeover bid.
Profits for the six months to June 30 were struck after a charge of Pounds
475,000, about half the cost of defending the bid by Sibelco, a
privately-owned Belgian-based company.
The balance of costs will be booked in the second half.
Sibelco, which has boardroom representation, holds 46.8 per cent of WBB
after it bought out its two partners in a 45.2 per cent concert party and
gained 1.6 per cent during the mandatory bid which lapsed in September.
Under Takeover Panel rules, Sibelco may now buy 1 per cent of WBB's equity
every 12 months: 'Discussions with Sibelco continue but have not reached a
conclusion,' said Mr John Pike, the managing director.
'We are quietly confident of meeting the forecast we made during the bid,'
he said.
The company, which serves the sanitaryware and tile industries, had been
helped in the first half by an Pounds 550,000 increase in operating profits
from overseas operations and a currency benefit this time of Pounds 250,000.
The company was 'seeing the faintest signs of an upturn in the UK and are
looking forward to a recovery in the housing market which is traditionally
important to us'.
Traditionally strong first half cash flow reduced net debt from Pounds 10.9m
at the year end to Pounds 7.44m and interest charges fell to Pounds 432,000
(Pounds 457,000).
Gearing fell to 10 per cent (20 per cent) helped by a Pounds 16m addition to
assets, reflecting a surplus on the book value of mineral reserves which
were revalued at the end of last year.
The board declared an interim dividend of 3.5p (2.7p) and said it would pay
the 12p total forecast at the time of the bid.
Earnings per share rose to 12.6p (12p).
COMMENT
With 25 per cent of its sales outside Europe, WBB has some protection from
the difficult European market. Orders to the Far East continue strong and
the Far Eastern joint ventures and US operations are profitable. The company
should comfortably meet its full-year forecast, giving earnings of 26.5p and
a rating of 16 times. This looks somewhat undervalued for a company which
has generally traded at a premium because of the quality of its clay
deposits and its management.
</TEXT>
<XX>
