<DATE>930929
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Dorling Kindersley jumps 29% - Adult list
leads all-round advance with 31% rise in turnover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DORLING Kindersley Holdings, the publisher, reported full year pre-tax
profits ahead 29 per cent in its first set of annual results since its
flotation last October.
In the 12 months to June 30 profits were Pounds 9.65m (Pounds 7.5m) on
turnover up 23 per cent to Pounds 87.4m (Pounds 70.9m).
Fully diluted earnings per share were 9.9p (9.4p). A final dividend of 2.2p
is proposed making a total of 3.3p, against a notional 3p.
The profit was struck after a non-recurring Pounds 208,000 charge for
flotation costs and reflected the strong performance of most of the
businesses. Operating profits improved 17 per cent to Pounds 9.08m (Pounds
7.77m).
Mr Peter Kindersley, chairman and chief executive, said: 'It is pleasing to
report a sixth successive year of substantial profit growth. DK Adult's
success in increasing turnover by almost 31 per cent to Pounds 50.5m and DK
Children's resilient second half performance are especially creditable.'
Overall, the group printed about 30m books during the year, an 18 per cent
increase. Among the adult books, particularly successful titles included the
two Royal Horticultural Society gardening books while, from the children's
list, Stephen Biesty's Incredible Cross-Sections sold 650,000 copies.
Backlist turnover increased by 46 per cent to Pounds 31.4m, equivalent to 36
per cent of total turnover, up from 30 per cent in 1992. US turnover from
publishing under the DK imprint, which began two years ago, grew to Pounds
13.7m (Pounds 5.2m).
After concerns at the interim stage about trading conditions in the DK
Children's division, it had a resilient second half, but this was not quite
enough to claw back the first half shortfall and turnover slipped to Pounds
26.6m (Pounds 27.8m) reflecting difficult trading conditions in its main
markets.
New businesses, including DK Multimedia, boosted turnover from Pounds
400,000 to Pounds 4.4m.
COMMENT
Dorling Kindersley's results were in line with market expectations and
underline the depth and quality of the group's established operations,
together with the potential of its new businesses. The group continues to
attract a premium based on its promising CD-Rom multimedia business, but its
core business also has considerable strength as the growing revenues from
the backlist demonstrate. This year the group should produce pre-tax profits
of about Pounds 11.5m and earnings per share of 10.8p. Based on yesterday's
closing share price of 292p, up 3p, the stock is trading on a lofty
prospective p/e of 27, reflecting its glamour-stock status.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Dorling Kindersley Holdings.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2741 Miscellaneous Publishing.
    P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
