FT  29 SEP 93 / UK Company News: First half advance at London and Manchester
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON and Manchester, the life assurance group, increased its interim
dividend by 10 per cent from 4.65p to 5.12p after announcing a 24 per cent
rise in premium income in the first half of 1993.
Mr Tom Pyne, chief executive, said he was optimistic about full-year profits
because the group could distribute to shareholders part of the investment
return on the life fund. In addition, its non-insurance businesses had
benefited from a return to stability in the housing market.
London and Manchester is the only insurer with permission from the
Department of Trade and Industry to distribute part of the long-term
investment return on the shareholders' interest in the roughly Pounds 1.5bn
life fund.
This return will be shown on the profit and loss account with the full-year
results as part of the total annual transfer from the life fund.
In the first half, ordinary life single premiums fell 42 per cent to Pounds
10.4m (Pounds 17.8m). However, total income from single premiums, including
pensions and managed funds, rose by 43 per cent to Pounds 120.7m (Pounds
84.2m). Total annual premium income increased 6 per cent to Pounds 95.3m
(Pounds 89.8m).
The company said its residential mortgage book is 'exhibiting a much
improved performance'. Arrears and repossessions were lower and provisions
had returned to normal levels from last year's higher amount.
The commercial mortgage book has been closed for 18 months. It is now being
run down and the provisions made at the time of closure are considered
adequate.
</TEXT>
