<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Bass pubs sale to Mercury Leisure allows
building programme to go ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BASS, the brewery group, is selling 111 pubs to Mercury Leisure, a
privately-owned restaurants and night-club company, for an undisclosed sum.
The disposal of 73 managed and 38 tenanted pubs will enable Bass to proceed
with plans to build 150 new pubs over the coming year without breaching the
Department of Trade and Industry's ceiling of 2,000 outlets, which was
imposed on Britain's leading brewers following an inquiry by the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission.
The transaction will double the size of Mercury Leisure's existing property
portfolio, to be operated in future as Mercury Taverns.
Mr Tony Sanders, joint managing director of the Tamworth-based company, said
the acquisition would be financed through a mixture of new equity, funded by
NatWest Ventures and borrowing from Barclays.
The pubs, which are situated mainly in the Midlands, South Wales and the
north-west of England, will transform Mercury into a 'major new pub group',
according to Mr Sanders.
Although unwilling to reveal the price, Bass said the cash consideration
represented less than 1 per cent of the group's net assets.
</TEXT>
