<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Takare makes Pounds 68m cash call
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TAKARE, the nursing home group, is raising Pounds 68m net of expenses
through a rights issue in order to step up its expansion rate.
The shares fell 8p to 235p, compared with the rights price of 195p.
Takare has been adding beds at the rate of 1,200 to 1,400 a year. Mr Keith
Bradshaw, chairman, said the group was now capable of growing at a faster
rate but refused to say what the new target would be.
Takare accompanied the 2-for-5 issue with a forecast of pre-tax profits of
not less than Pounds 14.8m for 1993, including an exceptional profit of
Pounds 370,000 on the sale of a nursing home, and promised a final dividend
of 1.4p to make a total of 2.1p (1.8p), up 16.7 per cent.
The profits will be after capitalising interest of about Pounds 2.5m,
compared with Pounds 4.16m in 1992.
Mr Bradshaw said the group was continuing to see occupancy levels of 97 per
cent and prices were not under pressure from the new community care system
introduced in April.
Before this rights, Takare had raised Pounds 67.2m through three equity
issues since coming to the market in 1989. It has also raised Pounds 50m
through three tranches of a deben-ture.
Its last equity offer was in September 1991 when the group promised not to
issue more shares for two years.
In recent weeks Takare has attempted to dampen speculation that it would
make a rights issue this month, saying it could continue to expand with debt
finance until the second quarter of 1995 without excessive gearing.
Yesterday, Mr Bradshaw said that while a rights issue was not essential, its
advisers, SG Warburg, had suggested now would be a good time to make one.
He said he would make no promises now about the timing of any further issue.
Takare would have more than 10,000 beds by the end of 1995, he said, and
would reach 'critical mass', meaning it could fund expansion from cashflow,
'well before we are confronted with a gearing problem again'.
The group, which has debt of Pounds 50.8m and cash of Pounds 3.05m, will
have net cash following the issue. Mr Ron Reid, finance director, said that
if the group opened 1,400 beds a year gearing would reach 35 per cent by the
end of 1996. If it opened 2,000 beds a year gearing would reach 55 per cent
by that time.
COMMENT
The timing of Takare's heavy rights at the earliest practicable moment it
was free from its promise not to issue more shares confirms the view that
this is a sector with an insatiable demand for equity capital. Fortunately,
Takare has so far proven its ability to deliver the profits and earnings to
justify its demands. On the profit forecast, the prospective p/e is 17 which
looks reasonable.
</TEXT>
