<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / IMRO eyes marketing claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMRO, the self-regulatory body for the fund management industry, is
considering possible disciplinary action against Hill Samuel Investment
Management for overstating the performance record in marketing literature
for one of its most successful products.
The literature relates to HSIM's active quantitative fund management
product, an investment technique which relies heavily on using mathematical
models to select stocks based on analysis of large quantities of data.
While HSIM marketed its so-called AVM product using internally generated
performance measurement figures calculated by a Datastream software product,
most clients had their returns monitored by WM Company, an independent
performance measurement firm.
'The Datastream figures tend to be higher rather than lower' than the WM
figures, said Mr Richard Bernays, chief executive of HSIM.
He said that upon discovering the discrepancies last summer, Hill Samuel
brought the matter to Imro's attention itself.
The product, whose marketing literature showed it was able to produce
returns two to four percentage points above the FT-A All-Share Index, barely
matched the index in 1992 and had not performed particularly well this year
either, Mr Bernays said.
Performance returns are the single greatest determinant in a fund manager's
ability to win and keep pension fund clients.
Poor performance, or questions about the validity of a manager's performance
data, would be a serious blow to any investment firm, pension consultants
say.
The team which developed the so-called AVM product, widely regarded as among
the most successful of its type in Britain, left HSIM last October to work
for State Street Global Advisers, a division of the US-based State Street
Bank and Trust Co.
The move is a blow to Hill Samuel and to State Street, which is about to
launch a competing product of its own.
It is also a blow to the proponents of active quant techniques, just as they
were hoping to expand their toehold in the traditional UK asset management
industry.
Mr David Miller, managing director of SSAG, said while he knew of no
discrepancies generally between the way WM Company and Datastream calculated
total returns, 'we generally know of problems of people trying to rebuild
performance figures of earlier years'.
He said that Mr Alan Greenhorn, the architect of the AVM product now
developing a competing product for SSAG, had been asked to assist HSIM in
uncovering its problem.
But because of a confidentiality agreement SSAG could shed no light on what
the problems were.
SSAG agreed to confidentiality 'because Alan and two other colleagues were
former HSIM employees and there were certain restrictions in their HS
contracts which we managed to re-negotiate,' he said.
Mr Bernays suggested that some discrepancy might be explained by what the
possible existence of what he called a 'bug' in the Datastream software,
which affects the way rights issues and tenders are treated.
However, Mr Norman Ireland, marketing manager at Datastream, said he knew of
no problems with the performance measurement product.
'If that's the case, there are an awful lot of clients who use this service
and no one has complained,' he said. He also said he knew of no discussions
with Hill Samuel.
</TEXT>
