<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Yeltsin troops seal off parliament: Tension rises as Moscow
riot police disperse 3,000 demonstrators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Boris Yeltsin sealed off the White House, or Russian parliament,
with barbed wire, troops and trucks yesterday and ordered its defenders to
hand over their weapons by 11am Moscow time today - 9am in London.
The cordon, the biggest deployment of force since Mr Yeltsin's decree
dissolving parliament a week ago, is designed to step up pressure on
deputies and their guards. It may stay in place for some days.
With tension rising, about 3,000 anti-Yeltsin demonstrators last night
commandeered trolley buses and blocked two of Moscow's main roads near the
parliament. But the crowd never looked threatening and riot police with
clubs and shields dispersed them with little trouble.
Mr Oleg Soskovets, first deputy prime minister, said tough measures would
soon be taken to remove the 100 or so deputies and their supporters still in
the parliament building.
He repeated that the building would not be stormed.
People wanting to leave the White House were ushered through the security
cordon but not allowed back. The cordon was erected through main
thoroughfares, back streets, playgrounds and apartment block backyards,
including the US Embassy compound and the former Comecon building, now
housing - among others - the office of the International Monetary Fund.
Inside the darkened, unheated building, Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the
parliamentary speaker, told the few journalists who found themselves inside
the lines that surrender was not on his agenda. 'We are not going to use
arms (first) but if there is an attempt to storm it (parliament), we will
rebuff it,' he said. 'Blood spilt will be on the hands of those who support
the coup d'etat.'
The Interior Ministry said greatly increased security was justified, given
the number of weapons within the building, displayed by defenders before
television cameras in earlier days, and the mental state of those holding
them. It, too, said its troops were not about to attack.
An official of Krasnopresnenskaya district council, one of many in Moscow
that voiced opposition to Mr Yeltsin, said that deputies shut out of the
parliament were preparing a 'parliament in exile'.
Earlier, Mr Yeltsin ruled out any compromise - especially that which seems
to have most support, to convene simultaneous parliamentary and presidential
elections. He stuck to his plan for elections to a new-style parliament on
December 11-12 and presidential elections on June 12.
Meanwhile the Russian Orthodox Patriarch Alexei II - before whom Mr Yeltsin
took his oath of office as president - cut short a visit to the US to plead
with 'all branches of power in Russia' to 'reach a reasonable compromise' on
the political crisis.
