<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Councils will face cost of cover if firefighters strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRESSURE on local authorities to settle their pay dispute with
firefighters increased yesterday after Mr Michael Howard, home secretary,
told employers that they must meet the full financial cost of emergency
cover in the event of any strikes.
The employers said that would probably cost them far more than meeting the
pay claim in full.
Mr Howard gave an equally blunt message that the firefighters must not have
any wage rise in November higher than the government's 1.5 per cent
public-sector pay limit for this year.
'There is no justification whatsoever for giving firefighters preferential
treatment this year,' he told them. 'They are expecting a special deal when
over 3m employees - including doctors, nurses and police officers - have
already accepted pay settle-ments of 1.5 per cent or below.'
Mr Ken Cameron, the Fire Brigades' Union general secretary, said a dispute
now looked 'inevitable'. 'This is an extremely dangerous situation. To put
the public at risk for what is a marginal amount of money to settle the
dispute is a nonsense,' he said.
The local authorities may well decide to defy the government's pay policy by
meeting the firefighters' wage formula award in full to avoid industrial
conflict - although perhaps in stages.
The government's earnings survey for 1993, to be published tomorrow, will
provide the basis for the pay award sought by firefighters. Their pay rises
have been linked since 1978 to the annual increase in earnings of the upper
quartile of male manual workers. If this year's figure, based on the 12
months to April, is not much above 1.5 per cent, the employers are expected
to settle.
The crucial negotiating session between the employers and the leaders of the
FBU will be on Friday.
If that fails to secure a settlement, the union's 50,000 members will be
asked to vote from next Monday for a series of one-day strikes. They would
begin on November 8 or shortly afterwards if a majority support action.
Mr Howard told the employers the government had no objection to the
restoration of the firefighters' pay formula in 1994 but he also warned them
no extra cash would be available from the government to pay for it.
The employers told him that local authorities who had their spending
programmes already capped by the government might be unable to meet next
year's firefighters' pay award, while other councils would be forced to cut
staffing levels and safety standards in order to meet next year's wage bill.
Picture, Page 11
</TEXT>
