<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / The Lex Column: Siebe
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
There are two reasons why Siebe's management changes are more than routine.
The first is that they carry the personal stamp of Mr Allen Yurko, who is to
become chief executive next year when Mr Barrie Stephens hives that role off
from the chairmanship. The second is that they increase the group's focus on
the upper end of the system controls market which is grouped around Foxboro.
Such a shift in emphasis may be natural given the 16.3 per cent margins
Siebe earned from its controls division last year. But much of this
originates from Foxboro, where the earnings contribution has been boosted by
cost-cutting.
With the rationalisation phase now largely over, Foxboro must turn its
attention to increasing volume and market share. Its achievement in this
regard - its share of the US controls market has increased from 6 per cent
to around 10 per cent over the past couple of years - has already brought it
into head-on confrontation with Honeywell. Siebe is suing its rival over
marketing literature which it regards as defamatory. Since Honeywell will
not give further ground easily, Foxboro, whose tactic is to seek a
reputation for quality, may find its margins suffering.
Siebe may thus face a choice between the hard slog of organic growth and the
short cut of buying market share through acquisition. The hard part for Mr
Yurko will be to find the right companies at the right price. As other
acquisitive companies are finding, there are not many suitable targets
around.
</TEXT>
