<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / The Lex Column: Sears
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
To be fair, Sears' top management has never pretended that the company's
recovery would be rapid. A sleepy and introspective culture takes time to
shift and outdated retail operations take time to overhaul. The shortage of
good management throughout the retail industry makes it difficult for the
company to recruit enough of the people it needs. That said, many changes
have been made at lower levels within the operating companies and some of
the benefits have already been felt in the partial revival of the British
Shoe Corporation. Unnecessary distractions such as housebuilding, menswear
and a stake in Asprey have been dealt with.
Yet the company remains a sprawling empire, almost all of which still needs
serious attention. The Olympus sports goods chain may face competition from
out of town 'category killers' before long, but is as yet only testing its
own new format. British Shoe and Freemans still need a lot of detailed work,
while recently-acquired Richards lost money in the first half despite cost
cuts and Selfridges continues to absorb management time.
The strain shows in the way that the chief executive, Mr Liam Strong,
appears to be involved in quite detailed operational decisions. While that
is probably a good way for a non-retailer to get to grips with the business,
it may not provide the momentum required to deal with the competitive
threats and shock the organisation into a new attitude. Either Sears needs a
tighter focus or Mr Strong needs some new highly-powered lieutenants on the
company's main board. His desire to work with the existing structure is
laudable. But the need is pressing.
</TEXT>
<XX>
