<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / The Lex Column: Minorco digs deep
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The shuffling of assets between Minorco and its South African parents is
motivated by more than a desire for geographic neatness. Anglo American is
shedding mining assets which could require substantial capital expenditure
in currencies other than rand. Minorco has cash in abundance to fund such
investment, and can claim another stride towards becoming a genuine natural
resources group rather than a piggy-bank for South African interests.
Whether a wholly independent Minorco would have wanted to extend its
position in pulp and paper - or take a stake in TransAtlantic, Mr Donald
Gordon's insurance and property vehicle - is open to question.
If the deal helps close the discount to net assets at which Minorco's shares
now trade, shareholders might anyway applaud. But there is room for doubt in
this regard. By taking shares rather than cash, Anglo American's influence
over Minorco is increased. That will be scant comfort to investors wary of
buying into a minority position. The deal does nothing in the short term to
address the question of Minorco's Dollars 1.1bn cash pile. Without hard
evidence that management can spend wisely, the discount is likely to remain.
Still, Minorco seems to be buying some attractive base metals reserves at
the bottom of the cycle. Profits should eventually benefit further out when
metals prices rise. Exactly when that will show through in the form of
increased earnings per share is difficult to fathom. Profits from the
acquired assets will have to rise smartly from last year's meagre Dollars
30m to make up for the issue of another slug of shares. There could be
something of a wait.
</TEXT>
