<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / A walk on the wild side: What J P Morgan can gain from a
tie-up with a controversial Spanish bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER and PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two huddles are gathered outside the large, ornate office of Mr Mario Conde,
chairman of Spain's fourth-largest bank. In one are the relaxed doormen
employed by Mr Conde's Banco Espanol de Credito (Banesto). In the other are
the jet-lagged executives of J P Morgan, the US corporate bank. They have
also been hired by Banesto to open doors - in their case, to international
capital markets. They are working on a Dollars 400m convertible bond issue,
planned for next month.
J P Morgan and Banesto have virtually nothing in common apart from being
banks. The former is an august corporate bank that alone among its US peers
has retained the top AAA assessment of creditworthiness from rating agencies
despite a 20-year squeeze on margins in its old lending business. The other
is a 2,300-branch retail bank whose poorer credit rating has just been put
down a notch because of bad lending in the 1980s. It remains enmeshed in a
holding company with stakes in industries from cement-making to wine
production.
But Banesto's relationship with Morgan has transformed its image among
investors. Money has poured into Mr Conde's bank since Morgan disclosed in
February that Banesto would be the first investment to be made by Morgan's
Dollars 1.1bn Corsair investment fund, set up in the US to buy stakes in
undervalued banks. Banesto's shares have risen 50 per cent since the Morgan
announcement, despite its decision not to pay a final dividend for 1992 - it
may not pay one this year either.
Mr Conde's critics in Madrid's financial community still harbour their
doubts about Banesto, but it is difficult to dispute his assessment of the
bank's new-found popularity. 'Was there ever such a capital increase in the
history of the European banking system?' he asks. 'No] After that it is hard
for me to believe the market is sceptical.'
The Dollars 400m convertible bond issue will be the final part of an attempt
to lift Banesto's capital to the levels of other Spanish banks. Banesto has
already raised Pta94bn (Dollars 876m) capital by issuing new shares since
May. Mr Conde's personal purchase of shares worth Pta6.4bn has helped to
persuade thousands of first-time buyers to purchase shares worth Pta19.7bn
through Banesto's branches. But he does not deny that the link with Morgan
has attracted the solid US investors which own 90 per cent of the Corsair
fund. 'Would there have been a capital issue without J P Morgan? The answer
is no]' Mr Conde exclaims.
Banesto's relationship with Morgan has brought it undoubted benefits. The
unresolved question is whether Morgan will reap similar rewards. If Banesto
fails to transform itself into the efficient retail bank with superior
technology that Morgan believes it can be, Corsair's first venture will
fail. Morgan's image as a talented investor of other people's capital in
equities that are undervalued by world markets would also be tarnished.
Damage to its reputation could set back Morgan's own effort to change from a
lending bank into one modelled on British merchant banks of the past - with
relatively few blue-chip corporate clients, but offering a wide range of
services from advice to risk management and securities underwriting. Such
operations are less risky than lending, but alone may not provide high
enough returns on Morgan's capital base. So Morgan has also taken to
investing capital in equities.
Responsibility for the Banesto venture falls on Mr Roberto Mendoza, a
quietly spoken Cuban. Mr Mendoza, who is a Morgan vice-chairman and
Corsair's representative on Banesto's board, formerly headed its mergers and
acquisitions side. Morgan has only Dollars 17.5m of Corsair's total Dollars
175m capital at stake in Banesto. But he acknowledges the potential risk to
Morgan's standing. 'We must get it right because we are investing our
reputation. That is the biggest kind of risk we can take,' he says.
Morgan first encountered Banesto in November 1989 when it was hired to
advise Mr Conde. Its advisers, led by Ms Violy de Harper, a managing
director of its corporate advisory arm, set to work to untangle the
run-down, family-controlled bank taken over by Mr Conde two years before. It
had been founded to channel money into railways, construction and mining,
and remained half bank and half industrial conglomerate.
Mr Conde and a former friend, Mr Juan Abello, flush with the profits from
the sale of a Spanish pharmaceuticals company to Montedison, the Italian
chemicals group, bought a 4 per cent stake in Banesto just as its ageing and
fractious family owners had been shaken by the near success of a takeover
bid for Banesto by Banco de Bilbao, then one of Spain's big three commercial
banks. His arrival upset Spain's cosy banking fraternity and triggered the
collapse of the cartel within which Spanish banks determined interest rates
on investments and loans.
Banesto's management and organisation were in a mess. Little had been
invested in its branches since 1975. Its employees were poorly paid, and
many had second jobs. It had absorbed smaller troubled banks on the
suggestion of the Bank of Spain, the central bank, and in early 1988 was
told to set aside money against Pta100bn of poor loans. Mr Conde's first two
years were spent in a flurry of activity. 'There were few accounts. It was
impossible to tell where the losses were coming from,' he says. He chose not
to disclose the whole truth about Banesto's plight to shareholders.
'I could have gone to a shareholders' meeting and told them: 'Gentlemen, I
told you the accounts said the 1987 profit of the bank was this, but that is
not true. And we have to invest this amount . . . ' What would have been
their reaction? They would have left the bank,' he says. Instead, he started
to invest Dollars 600m in new technology, branch refurbishment and improved
wages. In 1990, he created a holding company to control the bank's various
industrial interests.
Morgan came to believe that Banesto's tangled history obscured its true
worth. Its shares were trading at a discount to the value of its assets in
1989; Morgan thought this value could be unlocked by stripping out the bank
from the holding company. This would also focus the management on its core
business. But the move was partly making a virtue of necessity; the Bank of
Spain told banks last year that they would have to reduce industrial
holdings not consolidated in their accounts to 20 per cent of capital by
1998. Banesto currently has 39 per cent of capital in such holdings and so
is forced to offload some of its industrial interests.
'It was not a matter of yelling 'Eureka' in the bathtub, but the more we
delved into it, the more we came to the view that Banesto had a very large
unexploited franchise value in the pure retail bank,' says Mr Mendoza.
Morgan believed Banesto had to do two things to realise this value. One was
to sell a significant proportion of the industrial assets. The second was to
raise capital in order to relaunch itself with the strength to deal
comfortably with its bad debts.
The need to raise capital has been questioned by observers. Banesto had less
capital than its Spanish peers, but its ratios of capital to assets were
already comfortably in excess of international standards. This has led some
analysts to ask whether it really wants the money to spend on as yet
undisclosed problems with loans or industrial assets. Mr Mendoza says the
capital partly provides comfort - stopping it from being rushed into selling
assets - but mainly allows a break with the past.
'If you are the least-well-capitalised retail bank among your peers, and
there have been controversies, it is clear that you derive competitive
advantage from putting the issue to rest once and for all,' he says. 'You
become the master of your own destiny.'
Banesto's attempts to change its destiny have opened up opportunities for
Morgan. The Spanish bank has provided a target for Corsair. The fund - named
after J P Morgan's yacht, bought in 1882 - operates at the boundary drawn by
the 1933 Glass-Steagall Act between banks and investment banks. J P Morgan
chose then to stay a bank, but has increasingly tested the divide as
corporate lending has lost its allure.
Although Morgan has a Dollars 1.3bn equities portfolio, Corsair is its first
equity fund since 1933. The idea is to acquire partners in equity
investments, since Morgan is barred by US regulators from holding more than
4.9 per cent of a company. Corsair now holds 7.9 per cent of Banesto. J P
Morgan believed that by combining its advisory expertise with what Mr
Mendoza calls the 'sponsorship value' of its name, it could spot undervalued
companies and realise annual returns of 30 per cent for investors.
Morgan is now considering funds similar to Corsair for insurance and real
estate investment, but banking was an obvious place to start. When Morgan
had the idea two years ago, there were many ripe targets in the US among
banks which had suffered asset quality problems in the 1980s and whose share
prices were low. But it hit regulatory obstacles from the Federal Reserve,
and bank shares had rallied by the time the deadline for investing in
Corsair passed in February. Morgan was forced to look elsewhere for
undervalued bank shares instead.
Despite the problems of poor loans common to most banks in the 1980s, Morgan
believed retail banks in particular were good long-term investments. There
is a wistful tone in Mr Mendoza's voice as he describes their attractions.
Spanish banks have an average margin between interest they pay on deposits
and charge on loans of about 3.8 per cent. This compares with a fraction of
1 per cent on big corporate loans. 'High-street banking may not appear very
glamorous, but it can produce glamorous returns. They say corporate banking
is more glamorous but anyone in it would wonder why,' he says.
Banesto was particularly attractive because its shares were trading at a
fifth of the price of Banco Popular, Spain's most profitable bank. Banesto
had also avoided any overlap between its branches because it was not the
product of a merger, like some rivals such as Banco Bilbao Vizcaya. But
these qualities had not attracted investors before it was given Corsair's
stamp of approval. This raises the question of whether there was a conflict
of interest in Morgan investing money in the shares of a Morgan client,
though there has been no regulatory disapproval.
Mr Mendoza seems hurt at the suggestion of conflict. 'I sincerely hope not.
That would be terrible,' he says. He argues that Banesto was simply the best
available investment, and Corsair is now considering other banks with which
Morgan has no relationship. Mr Mendoza is more concerned that Banesto will
not produce the returns that Corsair requires. Corsair is committed to
remaining as a Banesto shareholder, and 'intends' to stay for five years.
But the sharp rise in Banesto's shares will have to continue past the
initial burst of enthusiasm to meet its overall 30 per cent annual
investment return target.
A possible bone of contention is the degree to which Mr Conde shares the
vision of Banesto as a 'cleanly focused retail bank' that Morgan presents to
investors. Mr Conde says Banesto will be primarily a retail bank in Spain,
but will hold equity investments. 'We have the opportunity to use part of
our equity to invest in non-financials, and make capital gains. Let's do
it,' he says.
Mr Mendoza downplays the possibility of tension. He says that Corsair is 'in
the business of picking managements to back, not second-guessing them'. He
argues that Mr Conde's abrasive tactics may have upset traditionalists in
the Spanish banking sector, but a strong character is needed to revitalise
Banesto. 'This is a turnround, and a successful turnround needs decisiveness
and leadership,' he says. Morgan is also barred by US law from exercising a
'controlling influence' on Banesto. So Corsair may simply have to wait
patiently to see if its first bet pays off.
'My own sense is that this is very low risk, although you can argue as to
how good the returns will be,' says Mr Mendoza. But a safe, mediocre return
carries its own risk. If Banesto does not transform itself as Morgan has
predicted, investors will not have the same faith in Corsair's next choice.
It has already earned big fees for bringing investors to Mr Conde's door; it
remains to be seen whether its reward will be large enough.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Banco Espanol de Credito.
    JP Morgan and Co Inc.
    Corsair.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
