<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Observer: Morse code
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Eagle-eyed strollers in the scholars' garden of St John's College,
Cambridge, who spot the new sundial with its Latin inscription coelum indico
benignum (I indicate a clear sky) might wish to know its provenance.
It seems that former Lloyds Bank chairman, Sir Jeremy Morse, president of
the Chartered Institute of Bankers until earlier this summer, had
volunteered a suitable bon mot for the locally designed chronometer
dedicated by the institute to St John's where it has three times held its
international banking summer schools. The famously cerebrally unchallenged
Morse, who took a first in classics, is of course an Oxford man.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
