<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Observer: Benn on Benson
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour MPs may whinge about their colleagues from the Conservative party
having a monopoly on City sinecures, but one can perhaps see why. Ejected
from Labour's national executive at the beginning of the week, Tony Benn was
yesterday affecting a distinctly shaky grasp of demarcations in the British
financial world.
Deploring supposedly highfalutin media reporting of economic affairs and
pointing out that pensioners are not in the habit of dumping their D-Marks
after the TV evening news, Benn lamented how 'when there is a crisis, people
always go and ask some chartered accountant at Kleinwort Benson'.
Merchant bankers KB yesterday owned up to 51 accountants on the pay roll
'any of whom would be most flattered to be consulted in an economic crisis'.
</TEXT>
