<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / West's best bet: Boris Yeltsin's bid to broaden the
democratic base deserves support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD MORTIMER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Russian legislators are reported to be confused by western support for
President Boris Yeltsin's attempt to abolish the legislature. They are not
alone. Many people in the west instinctively condemn any ruler who dissolves
an elected parliament and asserts his own supreme authority. That was clear
enough in the past year, when Peru's President Alberto Fujimori suspended
the constitution and dissolved Congress, even though inside Peru his
popularity rocketed to unprecedented levels.
Since then, Mr Fujimori has managed to reduce inflation, to stabilise a weak
economy, and to conduct a successful counter-offensive against the Sendero
Luminoso guerrillas who were terrorising the countryside and, increasingly,
the cities. This was what Mr Fujimori was elected to do, and it had become
clear that he could not do it if he stuck to the letter of the constitution.
Easy enough for liberals in New York to purse their lips; not so easy to
offer a better answer to Peru's problems.
Yet the lip-pursing may have been right and necessary. But for the sanctions
imposed by the US (mainly through the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund), Mr Fujimori might have thought he could run the country in
such a manner indefinitely. At least now he is holding a referendum on a new
constitution, which will allow the election of a new congress; and he has
had to keep a tighter rein on human rights violations by his security forces
than he might otherwise have done.
Mr Yeltsin, for his part, knows very well he would not get away with
indefinite presidential rule. When he dissolved parliament last week he
simultaneously fixed new elections for December. This point is surely more
important than the question of the legitimacy of the parliament's original
election in March 1990.
At the time, the election was seen as a victory for democracy, or for
'pro-democracy campaigners', at least in the big cities. But, the Financial
Times reported, 'party officials have managed to hang on to control of many
outlying regional soviets (councils), and may still end up with a majority
in the Russian parliament'. The party in question was, of course, the
Communist party, by then beginning to disintegrate but the only party able
to contest the elections as even a semi-organised force. Its official
monopoly of power had been dropped from the Soviet constitution only the
previous month.
Mr Yeltsin was eventually elected president, or speaker, on the third
ballot, by a margin of four votes. Much more decisive was his election as
president by universal suffrage the following year.
But even if the election of 1990 were democratic, it would hardly change the
issue. What Mr Yeltsin is doing is something provided for in most west
European constitutions when there is an irreconcilable clash between the
executive and the legislature: you 'go to the country' and let the people
decide. That was what Mr John Major was threatening to do last July when he
made his handling of the social protocol to the Maastricht treaty the
subject of a vote of confidence. Had he lost, the Queen would have dissolved
Parliament and there would have been a general election.
The French president has the same power. Charles de Gaulle used it twice (in
1962 and 1968); Francois Mitterrand did so immediately on his election in
1981, and again on his re-election in 1988 - on both occasions because by
electing him the voters had, in effect, disavowed the sitting National
Assembly. It was logical to give them a chance to choose a new assembly
reflecting their current preferences.
In Mr Yeltsin's case, the electorate explicitly confirmed its confidence in
him and (by a narrower margin) his economic policies in a referendum last
April. In spite of that, he has agreed to hold a new presidential election
next June (two years before the expiry of his mandate). He might be better
advised to hold the two elections simultaneously, but he is surely not
obliged to do so, provided he accepts the parliament elected in December and
appoints a government that enjoys its confidence.
A majority of votes was also cast last April in favour of the dissolution of
parliament. Unfortunately he could not act on it because the constitutional
court had ruled that this required a majority of eligible voters. Thus those
who failed to turn out were counted as votes against.
Mr Yeltsin has now decided to ignore that ruling and to act as the majority
of those who actually voted wanted him to do. In so doing he has violated
the constitution. But that constitution dates from the Brezhnev era. It has
been amended about 400 times, but by parliamentary, not popular, votes. It
was written for a country which was part of the Soviet Union, and in which
the Communist party was to have a permanent monopoly of power. When that
monopoly was abolished and the Soviet Union broke up it would have been
logical for the Russian people, who were, in effect, founding a new national
state, to adopt a new constitution. But in revolutions things are not always
done logically.
The problems facing Russia now are hardly less than those that faced Peru
last year. In fact, given the size of the country, its ethnic diversity, and
the legacy (both economic and political) of 70 years of communism, they can
surely be considered much greater. Many Russians doubt whether they can be
solved democratically, or at all. So far, Mr Yeltsin is still trying to
introduce a democratic constitution, to carry the people with him at each
stage of his reforms, and to avoid a recourse to violence. So long as he
behaves like that, he deserves support.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
