<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Hot air rises round cool decisions: The economic and
political cases for breaking up British Gas look weak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The likelihood is growing that Mr Michael Heseltine, UK trade and industry
secretary, will reject the recent recommendations of the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission to break up British Gas.
Although the public consultation period still has a month to run, the
economic case for adopting them is beginning to look weak and, possibly more
important, politically unattractive. Moreover, some of Mr Heseltine's own
staff appear to disagree with the measures proposed by the commis-sion.
The 1,000-page report, published last month, recommended a nine-year
timetable for ending British Gas's dominance of the UK gas industry. It
concluded that British Gas's dual role as owner of the gas pipeline network
and supplier to the vast majority of consumers made true competition
impossible. So the commission called for the divestment by British Gas of
its trading activities by March 31 1997. It went on to recommend that
British Gas's monopoly of the market for domestic customers be abolished in
the period 2000-2002.
The problem with this timetable from Mr Heseltine's point of view is
twofold.
First, it postpones the move to free competition in the domestic market  - a
key government objective - until the end of this decade, at the earliest.
That is a long time to put off the benefits of lower prices and better
service which the government hopes greater competition will bring. Mr
Heseltine also needs to have something to offset the unpopular introduction
of value-added tax on home fuels at the end of this year.
Second, it gives priority to breaking up British Gas, which has never been
high on the government's list. In their evidence to the commission,
officials at the Department of Trade and Industry's oil and gas division
said that the question of who owned trading and transportation systems was
less important than promoting competition; ownership issues might even
recede once a free market opened up. They also pointed out the difficulties
of breaking up a company as large as British Gas (which would be the largest
corporate dismemberment seen in the UK).
Other details in the report would also present the government with problems,
for example the recommendation that the cost of splitting British Gas up be
passed on to the consumer rather than the shareholder, and the fact that
nowhere in the world has the break-up of an integrated gas monopoly been
attem-pted.
It is hard to see that Mr Heseltine is under any pressure to split up
British Gas at this juncture. Even Sir James McKinnon, the gas industry
regulator who was one of the early champions of dismemberment, seems to have
changed his tune, or at least softened it. He now believes that break-up is
less important than creating a competitive market for new suppliers to
enter, and he believes that this is what government and regulator should
concentrate on. The problem of British Gas's internal conflicts could be
satisfactorily dealt with by building 'Chinese walls' between the
transportation and trading divisions, he believes. 'The principle of
separation has been accepted,' he says.
Nor are British Gas's potential competitors gunning en masse for divestment.
Earlier this year, a group of independent gas companies put forward a
blueprint for a competitive market which did not envisage breaking up
British Gas; they only proposed a clear separation of its transportation and
trading arms.
'You don't have to go to the ultimate step of breaking up British Gas at
this stage,' says Mr Peter Bryant, deputy chairman of Utilicorp, one of the
companies which helped prepare the plan. 'This means that British Gas would
be left with a lot of power, but the regulator can achieve the necessary
transparency.'
The independents have an obvious motive in wanting the DTI to go for
deregulation first rather than a break-up. They would get access to a large
new market many years earlier than envisaged in the monopolies commission's
course of action, which proposed deregulation only after the year 2000. But
if Mr Heseltine does opt for this course, he will have to confront three
issues.
The first is the risk that true competition might never develop if British
Gas was left in one piece, however forceful the regulator. The internal
separation of the transportation and trading divisions would have to be
extremely effective to convince other users of the pipeline system that
British Gas was not giving preference to its own business. Although his oil
and gas staff seem to oppose a split-up, Mr Heseltine also has a competition
department which might view such a move, like the commission, as the
cornerstone of a free market.
The second is how to protect consumer rights. Under present arrangements,
British Gas has an obligation to supply anyone who lives within a reasonable
distance of a gas main and is willing to pay. But this obligation would be
harder to enforce in a more competitive market.
Various people have put forward ideas to deal with it. Sir James proposes
that would-be public gas suppliers (PGSs) would identify the geographical
areas they wanted to serve. Provided these were not obviously intended just
to 'cherry pick' the choicest neighbourhoods, the regulator would grant a
licence which would carry the obligation to supply all-comers in that area.
But even this arrangement runs the risk that a new PGS might fail, leaving
its customers in the lurch and the sensitive gas system out of balance.
Mr Jonathan Stern of Gas Strategies, a consultancy, believes that British
Gas would have to retain some kind of 'back-stop' role to guarantee the
supply and keep the system in balance. But British Gas would be most
reluctant to assume these responsibilities unless it was clearly compensated
for the additional cost. 'The biggest barrier facing the government is the
obligation to supply,' says Mr Stern.
The third point is prices. Would a free market really mean lower gas bills
for household consumers? British Gas has argued that 12m of its customers
are subsidised by the other 6m. This means that the 12m could actually end
up paying more as competition erodes the subsidy. The independent gas
suppliers are aware of the sensitivity of British Gas's claims, and they can
be expected to intensify their lobbying to reassure government that they are
wrong. They could point, for example, to the industrial gas market where new
competitors are charging as much as 15 per cent less than British Gas.
However, while the gas market presents complex technical issues, Mr
Heseltine's choice will ultimately be the political one of what garners the
most votes, though he would have to have good reasons for rejecting the
commission's recommendations. There can be little political mileage in
putting a priority on breaking British Gas up, but there may be votes in
stimulating competition to bring down prices for the domestic gas consumer -
though even this is questionable given the concern that consumer groups have
expressed about the impact of privatisation on utility prices.
But Mr Heseltine does have the option of opening up the market to
competition, using British Gas as a safety net for what would be a
pioneering move by world standards. This would have the additional advantage
of leaving the government with the option of breaking British Gas up at a
later stage if the experiment showed it to be necessary. This might also
give British Gas the incentive to ensure the experiment's success.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Gas.
</CO>
<XX>
