<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Letters to the Editor: No time to think of return to dark
mornings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From J H M COCKAYNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Why should the lives of millions of us be inconvenienced for the sake
of (at most) a few thousand businessmen who can't be bothered to get to work
an hour earlier (or have a sandwich lunch at their desks)? Their
counterparts in the US cope quite happily with five different time zones. So
Europe ought to be able to manage with just two.
And please let us hear no more of the other spurious argument that was
trotted out last time round: you state in your leader ('Times a-changing',
September 24) that the government will rely on evidence that 'lighter
evenings mean fewer traffic accidents'. Fewer accidents in the evenings,
perhaps - but what about darker mornings, and the corresponding increase in
accidents on the way to work or school?
Anyone who remembers those depressing dark winter mornings during the
year-long 1970s experiment will surely not wish to suffer a permanent switch
to a regime which, after having been given a fair trial, was then soundly
rejected.
J H M Cockayne,
23 St Paul's Square,
York YO2 4BD
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
