<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Letters to the Editor: Missed opportunity in new SE Yellow
Book
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr A DAWSON PAUL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The Stock Exchange's new Yellow Book has finally gone some way to
address the scandal of excessive compensation for directors of unsuccessful
companies ('Directors face tough SE rules', September 17). However, for most
shareholders, it is unlikely to be a practical proposition to make a journey
to inspect the relevant documents at the company's office or even during the
15 minutes before, and during, the annual general meeting, at which they
have to be on display.
What a pity that the Stock Exchange missed the opportunity to require listed
companies to set out the details of service contracts and other incentives
in the company's annual report and accounts, thus making the information
readily available to all shareholders. If the scandals continue, this
requirement should surely feature as an item to be considered when the
working of the new Yellow Book is reviewed.
In the meantime, it will be interesting to see what use the institutions
make of the additional information now available to them.
A Dawson Paul,
Dennis Murphy Campbell,
6 Broad Street Place,
London EC2M 7DA
</TEXT>
