<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Letters to the Editor: US public backs nuclear energy option
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Ms ANN S BISCONTI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, David Lascelles's article, 'Cold comfort in future' (September 14)
clearly fits the old paradigm of looking at nuclear power, which holds that,
if it weren't for the public's lack of support, nuclear energy would be
considered a viable energy resource for the future.
As the person responsible for public opinion research for the US nuclear
power industry, I believe that the large body of research supports a 'new
paradigm', which better fits the public's attitudes towards nuclear energy.
This new view allows for more choices: people might think of nuclear energy
as dangerous, but they also believe that nuclear plants are safe. They might
prefer solar energy, but they want nuclear energy to be one of their
options.
People view energy sources as complementary, not as competitors. More than
two-thirds of Americans think the US should be developing both nuclear
energy and solar for future energy needs, and three-quarters believe in
keeping the option open to build new nuclear energy plants. Public concern
for clean air and new public awareness of nuclear energy's clean air
benefits are increasing the appeal of this energy source as part of the mix.
When the need for new electricity-generating plants becomes clear, nuclear
energy may not be the first choice of all communities. But the public
opinion climate that exists today would allow nuclear energy to be at the
table for consideration on its own merits.
Ann S Bisconti,
US Council for Energy
Awareness,
1776 I St NW,
Washington SC 20006-3708, US
</TEXT>
