<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Arts: Strauss's 'Daphne' - Opera in concert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There was a time when Richard Strauss's 1938 Daphne was thought safest on
the concert platform. Not only because it was an unfamiliar opera in one
longish act, and thus a risky bet for expensive staging; but also because at
the end the carolling heroine must turn into a (wordless) laurel tree.
Since designers nowadays have cleverer technology at their disposal, that is
no longer the dismaying hurdle it used to seem. Furthermore, many
music-lovers have by now seen Daphne staged: by Opera North, or in almost
any German house and many French ones, though never yet in London. The
experience proves how much easier it is in an orchestra pit to keep
Strauss's band down to its intended pastoral-lyrical level. In the Royal
Festival Hall on Monday, Andrew Davis found that hard to manage with the BBC
Symphony. Too many orchestral voices vied for our attention; too many
interesting ripples, too little serene flow.
For all that, it was a sound, graceful performance, and had it not been so
decisively outclassed a couple of years ago by Norman del Mar and the
Chelsea Opera Group in the Queen Elizabeth Hall (semi-professional
orchestra, mostly younger and less experienced singers) one might have
warmed to it more. If the two performances were not fairly comparable, given
their different circumstances, they certainly afforded different
experiences. In the larger hall the BBC version - the opening shot in their
'Strauss/Stravinsky Season' - exerted no spell, tamed the much-needed
ruderies of the shepherds' music, never lit up Strauss's magical pianissimi.
Another Daphne might have inspired them more. Janice Watson's fresh,
attractive soprano is more distinguished for energy than for long, floated
lines or liquid legato, which are the prerequisites for her fey,
other-worldly role. Besides, though she took its taxing high range nicely in
her stride she made very little of her words. Among all his rapturous
soprano monologues, there is not one that bears singing 'just for the
tunes'.
Josef Gregor's stiff libretto gives us a timorous adolescent Daphne, beset
not only by an impractical yen for union with plants and trees - rather
than, say, men - but by competing tenors. Young Jon Fredric West sang the
masterful god Apollo with high efficiency, and even conveyed some vital
feeling. Like his compatriots Jess Thomas and James King before him, West is
a specialist in Strauss's strenuous, somewhat thankless Heldentenor parts. A
brighter ring in the voice would have enlivened this one; perhaps he was
jet-lagged. As Leukippos, Daphne's greenstick swain from childhood, Vinson
Cole was as usual faultlessly musical, transparent and affecting. Why do we
hear so little of this excellent artist in Britain?
The only other halfway-decent roles in the piece are Daphne's parents,
Peneios and Gaea. Peneios, seriously under-composed and under-dramatised,
needs at least to wield a grave, imposing bass; for all David
Wilson-Johnson's virtues, he had no such thing in his kit. In Gaea's
strangely quiet, withheld music - which goes down to an unheard-of and
possibly unheard E-flat - Jadwiga Rappe found a more penetrating note. The
marginal parts, shepherds and maids, were cast from strength. What we heard
was nevertheless a sum of uneven parts.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
