<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There can be only one choice tonight for Morse addicts who in Inspector
Morse (C4, 8.30) are offered their last sighting of Oxford's most famous
fictional inhabitant - last, that is to say, until the next season of
repeats comes round to lighten our screens. Strangely enough, our farewell
to the mild-mannered introspective will not be taking place against a
backdrop of college quadrangles but in the brisker air of the Australian
outback.
It seems feeble that they could not have come up with another title for
tonight's Timewatch; The Mother of All Battles (BBC2, 8.00). That was a
great phrase when it fell from the lips of Saddam Hussein, redolent of a
particular time, place, and culture. Now it has become just another boring
journalistic cliche. The programme describes the course of what was the
greatest armoured battle in history, the Battle of Kursk in the Ukraine.
The Late Show (BBC 2, 11.15), looks at another battle, to save the soul of
Croydon, one of the south-east's least appreciated towns. A group of
architects are invited to explain what they would do to make Croydon lovely.
</TEXT>
<XX>
