<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Business and the Environment: Accounting for 'green' efforts
 -Ian Rodger scrutinises Ciba's new environmental report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Big companies, especially big chemical companies, are constantly searching
for new ways to allay deep-seated public suspicions about the damage their
operations do to the environment.
Most now devote large sections of their annual report and accounts to
descriptions of their environmental protection activities in addition to
other published brochures and data.
Ciba, the huge Swiss chemicals and pharmaceuticals group, is well known for
its efforts in this sensitive area.
It has just gone a step further, publishing what it calls a 'Corporate
Environmental Report 1992'.
Clearly modelled on the typical annual financial report, the 28-page glossy
brochure provides a combination of statements of policy from the chairman
and chief executive, detailed descriptions of progress achieved during the
past year and several pages of statistical data with helpful explanations of
their meaning.
The report will be published regularly, and possibly annually like the
group's financial report, although Ciba says only that 'it will be updated
regularly'.
It is published in German and English, is well written and illustrated, and
will undoubtedly be useful as a handout to concerned shareholders, employees
and various interested groups in the communities where Ciba has operations.
The first section of the report, setting out Ciba's environmental policies,
is particularly clear and the group's goal, sustainable development, is
particularly well explained.
'We must help meet the needs of today without compromising the ability of
future generations to meet their own needs,' Ciba says.
On the whole, however, the report is less than satisfying. The items in the
descriptive section, perhaps necessarily, are repetitive variations on a
theme. One describes how Ciba has improved its use of resources in
Argentina, another how it virtually eliminated waste water at Toms River,
New Jersey, another how it developed a new process to recover waste at a
chemical plant in Spain, and so on.
The result is a report with a slightly surreal 1950s optimism - everything
is getting better and better every day in every way.
Ciba's editors may have sensed this. A section entitled 'Incidents'
describes soberly the group's two plant accidents that occurred last year,
one at Grimsby in the UK and one at Schweizerhalle in Switzerland, and
explains their causes and effects.
There is also a startlingly punchy question and answer section with the
group's environmental directors. Sample question: 'Ciba had to pay Dollars
9m (Pounds 5.8m) in fines and penalties in the US for violations of waste
disposal regulations at your Toms River site in New Jersey. How does this
accord with your commitment towards complying with the law?'
The answer regrettably was much less punchy than the question.
The statistical section likewise has a slightly off-beat quality.
Unlike corporate financial reports, where one is accustomed to viewing
charts where the bars march confidently upward to the right, here we are
invited to take some comfort from seeing the charts all march smartly
downwards.
Water and CFC usage, emissions of nitrogen oxides, sulphur dioxide
emissions, discharges into the river Rhine - have all declined over the past
three years.
A few indicators are still rising, such as energy consumption and carbon
dioxide emissions, and the explanations provided point to an inevitable
paradox in the group's efforts to lessen environmental impacts of industrial
activity.
'The rise in carbon dioxide emissions is mainly due to our growing use of
waste to produce energy through our own incinerators . . . A further reason
is the increased energy requirements of air pollution control equipment.'
</TEXT>
