<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Management: Poet in the boardroom / Interview with Gertrud
Hohler, Germany's outspoken 'powerfrau' and a non-executive director at
Grand Metropolitan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Gertrud Hohler can surely be forgiven for sounding a touch smug. Three years
ago she seemed poised to take over as head of communications at Volkswagen,
Europe's largest car group. But in an about turn which obviously still
rankles today the company's supervisory board ignored the wishes of the then
chief executive Carl Hahn and blocked her appointment to the DM500,000
(Pounds 200,000) a year post.
'They didn't like the idea of Hahn bringing a woman to such a senior job,'
says the 52-year-old literature professor turned management guru.
Not surprisingly, Hohler has been a more than normally interested observer
of this summer's industrial espionage allegations against VW's Jose Ignacio
Lopez de Arriortua, an episode widely seen as a public relations disaster
for the car giant.
'Piech (VW's chief executive) has behaved in a thoroughly warlike way,' she
suggests, agreeing with those who say that the VW chief has had no public
relations policy, veering from injured silence at one moment to ill-thought
aggression at another.
Hohler has long been a familiar figure on the German corporate scene, but
her international profile was raised last November when she became a
non-executive director of Grand Metropolitan, the UK-based food and drinks
group. GrandMet was specifically looking for a foreigner and she was chosen
after a search by headhunters.
Hohler's outspokenness, in itself unusual in Germany, is not the only way in
which she differs from the ranks of Germany's management gurus. She is a
woman, moreover, and one taken seriously in the higher echelons of the
German business world where the female sex is not well represented.
She is also a former poetry prize-winner, professor of literature at
Paderborn University and author of a book on the poetry of Rainer Maria
Rilke.
She has subsequently written around a dozen books on management issues (the
latest one is entitled Rules of the Game for Winners), and for three years
worked as a close adviser to the board of the Deutsche Bank, Germany's
biggest bank. She has had her own television shows and has advised leading
politicians, and was tipped once as a possible member of Chancellor Kohl's
cabinet.
This cross-over into commercial life is again highly unusual in Germany; it
is almost unheard of for someone with a liberal arts background to make a
business career in Germany, where a doctorate on engineering or business
economics seems to be the sole passport to a management position.
In an environment where Edzard Reuter, chief executive of Daimler- Benz,
Germany's biggest company, stands out simply because he is a member of the
Social Democratic party rather than the conservative Christian Democrats,
Hohler provides a rare dash of corporate colour. This has been acknowledged
by the city of Aachen which honoured her with its prized 'Anti-Deadly
Seriousness' award.
Critics of the Hohler style - and there were believed to be many in the
conservative environment of the Deutsche Bank - say that her contribution to
the problems facing German managers is insubstantial and light-weight. They
point out that for all her promise she has never quite held on to the
position within the German political or industrial establishment which her
well-publicised talents would appear to justify.
Tall, striking and often sporting the 'Powerfrau' outfit of bright red
jacket and striped shirt, Hohler now runs a one-woman communications
consultancy in Berlin. But it is her vantage point in the boardroom of a UK
company - where she is a double rarity as a woman and foreigner - which is
perhaps most intriguing.
A specialist on corporate culture, she says she has been pleasantly
surprised at what she has learnt at Grand Met about the way the British
business world runs.
'British people tend to think that Germans are stiff and unfriendly, but the
reverse holds true as well,' she remarks. 'Germans have this idea of a
formidably formal upper-class business community. This impression is
reinforced by the formal way English people dress.
'This is true, but what has really astounded me is the mixture of formality
with a relaxed approach to doing business. They (the British) laugh more
than Germans and board meetings are less structured, without the deadly
seriousness which surrounds board meetings in Germany.
'But this doesn't stop meetings being disciplined and effective. That
English people should be so nonchalant without being in any way less
effective is difficult for Germans to grasp. There is an extremely quick
reaction to problems and mistakes. For example, in Germany the tendency is
to cover problems up in the hope that they will go away, to think that if we
don't notice the press won't notice either.
'Perhaps the biggest difference is in the attitude to profits. German
managers have the reputation for being hard-nosed businessmen but in reality
they are nervous about making money. In public they excuse themselves by
saying 'yes we want to make a profit but we are nice people as well,
really'. For British managers there is absolutely no contradiction between
morality and profit.'
Hohler clearly feels herself much more at home at Grand Met than at Deutsche
Bank (she is legally bound not to talk about her time there), although last
week's unexpected promotion of George Bull to the position of chief
executive of the UK company suggests that boardroom life in Britain can be
every bit as mysterious as in Germany.
Her main asset in the British boardroom, she says, is that 'I am much closer
to the consumer than my fellow directors', adding that she is probably the
only member of the board who has recently been shopping in a supermarket.
'Top managers tend to become a little isolated from reality,' although she
thinks this is less true for British businessmen than for Germans.
</TEXT>
