<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / The Labour Party Conference: Hackles raised over
one-member-one-vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEFENDERS of Labour's union links failed yesterday to persuade the party
conference to support an emergency resolution blocking the leadership's
plans for reform.
But traditionalists promise a further battle today when the national
executive committee's proposals to 'modernise' the link are presented by Mr
John Smith, the party leader.
Attention has focused on plans to democratise the selection of parliamentary
candidates by limiting the franchise to individual party members - ending
the unions' right to cast up to 40 per cent of the vote.
This proposal, referred to as one-member-one-vote, is opposed by many
unions.
Their alternative would give an individual vote to union members who pay the
political levy which helps to finance Labour, most of whom are not party
members. Union leaders refer to this as every-member-one-vote.
Voting on the proposals will be complex. Delegates will be asked first to
approve a statement by the national executive committee setting out Mr
Smith's proposals.
Then there will be votes on eight resolutions followed by votes on five rule
changes to give effect to the NEC proposals.
For the leadership, the key will be the rule change votes. If approved, they
will take precedence over any successful resolutions.
The NEC statement makes three main proposals:
Parliamentary candidates would be selected by individual members voting in
their constituencies, instead of jointly by individuals and affiliated union
branches. Union members would have a vote, but only if they paid the
political levy and a further fee of Pounds 3 to join the party. Union
branches would retain the right to nominate candidates and to take part in
running constituency parties.
The leader and deputy leader would be elected by an electoral college giving
a third of the votes to each of three groups: unions, members of the
Westminster and European parliaments, and individual members. Unions have 40
per cent of the votes in the existing college, with the balance split
between parliamentarians and constituency parties.
The block vote would be weakened by forcing unions to split their votes
between individual delegates. However, unions would still be able to control
delegates by mandating them in advance. The unions' 70 per cent share of
conference votes would be reduced to 50 per cent, but only if party
membership increases from 260,000 to 300,000, reversing a long-term decline.
The rule changes required to give effect to these proposals will be
determined in a series of five 'card' votes, in which union leaders will
vote - under the existing rules - on behalf of all members who pay the
political levy.
The resolutions will matter only if one or more rule changes fail to pass.
Two are straightforward: composite 55, moved by the rightwing Amalgamated
Engineering and Electrical Union, broadly supports the NEC, and resolution
375, moved by Leicester East constituency party, supports the retention of
block voting.
Opposition to the leadership will centre on composite 58, moved by the TGWU,
and composite 57, from the GMB general workers' union. The GMB motion seeks
to preserve one third of selection votes for union levy payers, who would
vote through their unions without being required to join the party as
individuals.
The TGWU motion seeks to reserve 40 per cent of selection votes for levy
payers voting through their union, and to preserve the block vote. The
motion also instructs the NEC not to use its reserve powers to introduce a
revised system.
This is intended to block the leadership's fallback plan to impose
one-member-one-vote if the rule changes are defeated. If that happens, the
leadership's best hope is composite 56, which says that levy-paying union
members should participate in selections as individuals 'on a fairly agreed
basis.' The leadership says this phrase could be interpreted as
authorisation for the NEC proposals.
</TEXT>
<XX>
