<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / The Labour Party Conference: Fresh battle looms over social
chapter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Labour party yesterday warned that it plans to re-open wounds in the
Conservative party over the Maastricht treaty by forcing a new Westminster
battle over Britain's contributions to the European Community.
Mr George Robertson, the party's European Affairs spokesman, said that
Labour planned to link its support for legislation to increase the EC's 'own
resources' ceiling with government acceptance of Maastricht's social
chapter.
The strategy raises the possibility of a re-run at Westminster of the final
stages of the Maastricht debate, in which the opposition parties and Tory
Euro-sceptics took Mr John Major's government to the brink of defeat on the
social chapter.
A parliamentary battle over financing would also threaten to keep
Conservative divisions over Europe in the spotlight as next summer's
elections for the European parliament approach.
The government has to bring forward legislation to allow increased
contributions to Brussels following an agreement at last December's to raise
the allowed ceiling on the Community's expenditure.
But some of the Tory Euro-sceptics who were forced into line over Maastricht
by Mr Major's threat of a general election have indicated privately they are
ready to oppose the legislation.
Mr Robertson said that, as with the legislation to implement Maastricht,
Labour would not seek to 'wreck' the passage of the financial bill. But it
would 'tie its conclusion to signature of the social chapter'.
Mr Robertson said: 'I am sure it will be possible to devise an amendment
which will tie the government's hands'.
Adding that Labour would table other amendments to the proposed bill to
secure more European funding for regional and social spending, Mr Robertson
said: 'This bill must get through but it is already in trouble. The
government simply does not have a majority'.
Whitehall officials indicated yesterday that they were relaxed about such a
possibility, suggesting that only a handful of Tory Euro-sceptics would be
ready to oppose the government.
Mr Major would also hope to be able to secure the tacit support of the
Liberal Democrats and, possibly, the Ulster Unionists.
But one leading Tory Euro-sceptic said yesterday that the issue of increased
funding for Brussels could well provide another battleground with the
government.
Many of the opponents of Maastricht remain unconvinced of the more sceptical
stance towards Europe adopted by Mr Major in his declared approach to the
EC's medium-term agenda.
Lord Tebbit, one of the fiercest opponents of the treaty, is expected to
call for a much tougher stance against integration at next week's
Conservative party conference in Blackpool.
</TEXT>
