FT  29 SEP 93 / The Labour Party Conference: Pressure mounts on smaller
delegations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUPPORTERS of Mr John Smith's reform proposals were yesterday involved in a
frantic last-minute scramble to persuade union delegations and constituency
party delegates to switch their votes behind the Labour leader, David
Goodhart writes.
Mr Neil Kinnock, the former leader, addressed the seven delegates of the
Northampton-based knitwear workers' union NKFAT who were said to be
impressed by his visit but still undecided.
The left-led engineering section of the National Communications Union was
also visited by Mr Rodney Bickerstaffe, general secretary of the Nupe public
services union, and his deputy, Mr Tom Sawyer, both of whom still carry
influence with the left in the unions. The NCU is expected to take a final
decision today.
The MSF technical union, which also has a left-dominated delegation, has
still not reached a final decision on the crucial rule change, and is sure
to come under further pressure today.
Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, last night appealed to leftwing
unions and undecided delegates at the annual Tribune rally, saying that the
recent clarification of the one-member-one-vote policy allowed mandated
delegates to change their positions.
Earlier the GPMU print union, another small union opposing reform, was also
subjected to strong pressure from the Labour leadership but refused to
budge.
There was also dismay from reform supporters when it was discovered that the
Fabian Society, usually associated with party modernisation, was unable to
cast its small number of votes for the leader because of a policy of
remaining above factionalism in the party.
