FT  29 SEP 93 / Patten attacks 'duff' schools
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Patten, education secretary, said yesterday that he had a list of
several hundred 'duff' schools - mostly in inner cities - where the march of
reform was being 'debauched'.
Mr Patten said he was considering replacing local authority control of the
schools with management teams called 'educational associations'.
Mr David Hart, general secretary of the National Association of Head
Teachers, said the issue of educational associations could become a
'battlefield' for the next few years.
Mr Patten said: 'There are clusters of schools who I think are
short-changing pupils horribly.
'The march of reform is being debauched in those areas. There will be action
after January 1.'
Speaking to business leaders at the launch of Education in Industry, he said
that he would act on the advice of inspectors who are reviewing the schools.
He refused to name them, but said most were in inner cities with
concentrations in a few London boroughs.
Teachers' union leaders said the comments suggested that educational
associations would be used to force more schools into opting out of local
education authority control.
Mr Peter Smith, general secretary of the Association of Teachers and
Lecturers, said that Mr Patten's new power 'had always been justified as a
last-resort measure'.
He said Mr Patten would need to have the 'firmest evidence' before sending
in educational associations to remedy a problem.
Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary of the National Union of Teachers,
described the remarks as insulting and unhelpful, adding that they did not
help the situation.
