<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Pit roof-bolting cleared by HSE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
OLD WORKINGS and waste material were the principal causes of the roof
cave-in at Bilsthorpe Colliery in which three people died, an interim report
published yesterday by the Health and Safety Executive has found.
It says the controversial roof-bolting system was the primary means of
support in the area of the Nottinghamshire mine half a mile below the
surface in which the fall occurred. But the size of the collapse was such
that any free-standing support would have been unable to withstand the load.
The inquiry team's main conclusion in a highly technical 40-page document is
that the presence of an old roadway and associated waste were the principal
factors contributing to last month's collapse.
Mr Brian Langdon, deputy chief inspector of mines, said: 'Common features of
the major falls, such as the one at Bilsthorpe, are their unpredictability
and suddenness of collapse, giving little or no chance of escape to those in
the immediate vicinity.'
Mr Langdon said strata behaviour was not an exact science and more work had
to be done to obtain greater understanding and to be able to measure more
accurately the effects of coal pillars on mine workings.
'Until there is a clearer understanding, the practice of 'skin-to-skin'
working - whereby a new road is driven immediately alongside an old road and
adjacent waste with no intervening coal pillar - has been discontinued by
British Coal in this and other mines.'
Mr Langdon's interim report will be followed by a full report later. The HSE
has drawn no final conclusions or made any recommendations on the findings
to date.
British Coal said the inquiry's conclusions were 'substantially in accord'
with its own. 'The report acknowledges that the roof-bolting standards at
Bilsthorpe were good,' said the corporation.
Mr Langdon said he had found no evidence to suggest that safety standards
were being marginalised in the privatisation of the coal industry.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Coal Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
