FT  29 SEP 93 / Ministers hold key to Swans' EC funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SWAN HUNTER, the threat-ened Tyneside shipbuilder, can be considered for an
intervention funding subsidy only if the government can prove the yard is of
strategic military importance, the European Commission said yesterday.
A delegation of Labour MPs, MEPs and shop stewards from the company, which
has been in receivership since May, met Mr Karel Van Miert, EC competition
commissioner, to press Swans' case for the 9 per cent EC subsidy on merchant
shipbuilding orders.
Swans' chances of finding a buyer could be enhanced by funding eligibility,
and the delegation argued that Swans was the only European shipyard building
merchant and naval ships without any subsidy.
Until now the emphasis of the campaign has been to stress Swans' involvement
in merchant shipbuilding, for which Continental shipyards have been able to
claim intervention funding subsidies.
The EC's stance at yesterday's meeting unexpectedly switched the emphasis to
Swans' place in the UK's defence capability.
Mr Alan Donnelly, Tyne and Wear's Labour MEP, said: 'The only condition that
the EC will accept in granting subsidies to Swan Hunter is if the British
government can prove the yard is of strategic military importance.' Mr Van
Miert had stressed that the argument had to come from the government,
particularly the Ministry of Defence.
</TEXT>
