<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Cases Lautro tries to prevent
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TYPE of cases Lautro is trying to prevent:
A couple take on a five-year interest-only loan. At the end of five years,
they will have to find the cash to pay the capital balance.
An enterprising insurance sales agent, following the principle that
suitability means the most suitable product sold by his company, signs up
the couple for a 10-year savings policy intended to pay off the loan. His
company simply does not offer a five-year product.
This is a real example, and not surprisingly, when the loan matured, the
savings policy could not pay it off.
Lautro also cites the case of a young man in temporary employment who was
sold a long-term savings plan. 'There was no evidence on the fact-find that
the investor wished to save for that period; indeed, he appeared unlikely to
be able to maintain any rate of savings commitment,' Lautro noted.
In similar vein, Lautro notes the case of a divorcee who wished to invest
Pounds 15,000 in a school fees plan for the education of her three sons. The
sum fell far short of what would be needed to cover fees, but the adviser
placed her investment in a highly volatile Japanese fund. Although returns
in some previous years had been extremely rewarding, the woman could well
have been forced to cash the investment in during a severe downcycle. Thus,
the investment was unsuitable.
These are among several examples cited by Lautro of sales of unsuitable
products.
The life insurance industry has maintained for years that the sale of
unsuitable products is rare and that most people do obtain best advice.
</TEXT>
