<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Red line opts for bottom line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RED ARMY is finally succumbing to capitalism. Russian army officers made
redundant after the collapse of the Communist regime are to be taught by
British university lecturers how to set up and run small businesses.
Officers trained to revile western ideals will be urged to embrace them
under a government-backed scheme unveiled yesterday. Starting in November
and funded by a Pounds 317,000 Foreign Office grant, courses will be offered
in financial management, accounting and marketing.
The initial course will involve more than 800 officers who lost their jobs
when the Soviet armed forces were disbanded.
Former intelligence officers, submarine commanders and logistics chiefs are
expected to be among the trainees at four new business centres established
in Moscow, Tula, Tomsk and Nizhny Novgorod by lecturers from Coventry
University.
The lecturers say they are ready to launch an offensive on the old ideals of
men and women who had spent most of their lives in a managed economy.
Mr Noel Hibbert, director of the university's European Training Agency,
said: 'We've already found a big problem with their marketing skills. They
hit upon ideas for a business without finding out if there's any demand.'
While setting up a separate course in democracy, lecturers had to persuade a
former nuclear submarine commander that there was no demand for a company
selling reconnaissance film.
Another officer with experience of ground-to-air weaponry was dissuaded from
planning a toy company making boomerangs.
The three-week training schedule promises to be an assault course in finance
with tests in auditing and management skills.
The final obstacle for officers hoping to join the ranks of entrepreneurs
targeting Mother Russia will be an interview with officials of the staunchly
capitalist European Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
In return for an equity stake in any company it deems worthy of backing, the
EBRD will offer credits worth up to Dollars 30,000 (Pounds 19,500).
'They're queueing up to join the courses,' said Mr Hibbert. 'It means we can
assist with the demobilisation of Russian armed forces.'
Aware of the sensitivity needed to deal with the one-time elite of the
Warsaw Pact, the university has decided to train 36 senior Russian officers
in Coventry as lecturers in the new year.
They, in turn, will spread the capitalist message to some of the 450,000
military personnel made redundant after the fall of communism.
</TEXT>
