<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Lautro tightens rules on finance product sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAUTRO, the self-regulatory body for the life insurance industry, has issued
a guide for sales agents spelling out circumstances in which they should not
recommend a purchase of any of their products to a client.
The rules, which dwell on the issue of 'suitability', define much more
narrowly the kind of product which can be recommended in certain
circumstances, and are likely to have a significant impact particularly on
insurance companies which market a limited product range.
Sales agents have been interpreting rules on suitability to mean the product
offered by their employer that comes closest to meeting the client's
specific needs, even though it may not meet those needs exactly. Lautro
warned in a bulletin issued yesterday that its enforcement staff and its
complaints subcommittee will 'routinely look particularly closely at queries
about 'best advice' which arise in the context of such members'.
The Financial Services Act requires sales agents to give best advice about
which product to purchase.
Industry regulators have said one of their chief aims is to curb the sale of
'unsuitable' products. Sales of such products often lead to early encashment
of insurance policies. The front-ended nature of most insurance contracts
means that those who cancel early lose most of the premiums paid in the
first year or so, costing investors millions of pounds every year.
In its enforcement bulletin 23, Lautro said it was trying in response to
enquiries from members to clarify an earlier statement. That statement had
told members how to check that sales agents had ascertained a client's needs
and had recommended only the purchase of a suitable product.
'Some members then ask: 'How is suitability to be defined?',' Lautro said.
'It will be clear . . . that in general terms the monitoring committee does
not regard suitability as synonymous with the closest match.'
Among factors to be taken into consideration are whether a client is likely
to need the proceeds of any investment before the investment matures.
If so, will the value of the investment be sufficient to meet client needs,
and will it represent a reasonable rate of return?
Also, the client must demonstrate his ability to meet the costs of the
investment. A product which requires too great a proportion of a client's
disposable income will not be deemed suitable.
</TEXT>
