<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Tory councils block tendering drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVE-controlled local authorities have taken the lead in thwarting
the government's compulsory competitive tendering programme, a survey
revealed yesterday.
They are doing so using the Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of
Employment) regulations 1981. Where Tupe applies, a successful bidder must
take over the workforce on the existing terms and conditions. Of councils
which have tendered contracts stating that Tupe applies, 36 per cent were
Conservative, while only 26 per cent were Labour-controlled and 5 per cent
were held by the Liberal Democrats.
The survey of 50 contractors by the Clause 26 lobby group showed deep
disquiet with the government's response to the Tupe issue - 97 per cent
labelled it unsatisfactory. Almost half (45 per cent) would not have entered
the market in local authority services in 1988 had they known that Tupe
would be an issue.
Mr Cliff Davis-Coleman, director of Clause 26, said that Conservative
authorities' reaction was due to the Department of the Environment's
'confused legal position'.
He added that this had been worsened by Monday's consultative paper. Under
the proposed guidelines, if a local authority has legal advice that Tupe
applies but the bid assumes that it does not, the contractor should be
invited to reconsider the bid. If the contractor refuses to revise a bid,
the authority can reject it even if it is the cheapest.
Mr Davis-Coleman said this means that 'only a lawyer employed by a local
authority can determine whether Tupe applies'.
</TEXT>
