<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Confidence 'declining' in northern England
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFIDENCE is declining in the north, says the sixth survey in two years of
about 800 companies by Latham, Crossley and Davis, the Manchester, Wigan and
Chorley accountancy firm.
The firm says the recovery in northern England is in danger of stagnating
because too few companies are looking for new markets, developing new
products or finding alternatives to the banks for financing growth.
The research, completed two weeks ago, asked companies to rate their
confidence on a scale of one to 10. The average rating in the latest survey
was 5.3 compared with 5.5 in the middle of last year, 6.5 last November and
6.25 in April this year.
'The drop in confidence reflects the patchy nature of the recovery,' Mr
Keith Seeley, the firm's managing partner, said yesterday. 'Leasing
businesses and automotive services companies expressed continued high
confidence, but engineering companies scored their optimism much lower.'
Nearly two thirds of companies in the survey expected any increase in orders
to come from established customers buying existing products. Only 26 per
cent were developing new products or seeking new markets while only 10 per
cent foresaw exports as their main sales boost.
Nearly half expected to use a bank overdraft or loans to finance growth,
while 39 per cent were trying to use cash retained in the business.
</TEXT>
