<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / BCCI official sentenced to six years for fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR SYED ALI AKBAR, the former Bank of Credit and Commerce International
official who admitted frauds involving more than Dollars 745m connected with
the bank's collapse, was yesterday sentenced to six years in prison.
However the former head of BCCI's treasury division is likely to be released
after serving only 12 to 18 months. Mr Justice Scott, at the Old Bailey,
ordered that the two years he had already spent in French and British jails
be taken into account.
The judge also told Mr Akbar that he was reducing his sentence considerably
following the banker's decision to co-operate with Serious Fraud Office
investigators and to plead guilty to 16 charges of false accounting. This
meant the prospect of another enormously expensive 'mega-trial' had been
avoided, he said.
If Mr Akbar had been convicted after pleading innocent he could have
expected a sentence of between 10 and 11 years. Mr Justice Scott told him:
'You have pleaded guilty to an international fraud on a massive scale
between 1982 and 1986. You were the chief architect of the bogus deployment
of millions and millions and millions of dollars.'
Mr Akbar was not responsible for all BCCI's financial problems but the
bank's eventual collapse cast a shadow over the whole banking world, he
said.
'The losers included not only the big battalions of banks, insurance
companies and local authorities but individuals and small businesses, and
for some of them the loss was fatal - that's what makes it so serious.'
Although Mr Akbar stands to be released from prison after 12 to 18 months,
it is likely he will be immediately re-arrested and made to face further
charges in the US. He has already been indicted in Tampa, Florida, over
allegations that he laundered money stolen from the Panamanian National
Guard by the country's former head of state, President Noriega.
The judge said Mr Akbar had personally gained or misused Dollars 61m of BCCI
depositors' funds - money which he used to set up Capcom, a futures dealing
company which handled most of the bank's dealing business.
Investigations were unable to establish whether Mr Akbar had hidden any
money for future use. According to Capcom records, all money was lost
through Mr Akbar's unsuccessful dealing.
</TEXT>
