<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Thatcher fires a warning shot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BARONESS THATCHER has granted an interview to a Sunday newspaper in a move
timed to cause maximum discomfort to the Tory leadership ahead of next
week's annual conference in Blackpool.
The interview, which is expected to be published in the next Sunday Times,
follows Lady Thatcher's inflammatory remarks on the government's tax and
European policy during a private dinner attended by Tory activists on Monday
night.
At last year's conference, the former prime minister used an article in The
European newspaper to launch a vitriolic attack on the Maastricht treaty in
a move which shattered Mr John Major's hopes that divisions over Europe had
been put to rest.
The Sunday Times is also serialising Lady Thatcher's forthcoming memoirs but
will not start publishing extracts until after the conference, in accordance
with the conditions of its serialisation contract.
Lady Thatcher's outburst on Monday - in which she criticised the
government's plans to extend VAT to domestic fuel - reopened Tory divisions
over the proposals and undermined the party leadership's hopes of a quiet
week in the run-up to the conference. In a wide-ranging speech to party
activists in Southend, she warned it would be very damaging for the Tories
to become known as the high-tax party.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, said he strongly agreed with
Lady Thatcher's emphasis on the need to 'get the nation's finances right'.
He added: 'I do not like putting VAT on fuel. We have, nevertheless, to get
some revenue. If we do not get this revenue here, we would have to get the
money from somewhere else.'
Mr William Powell, MP for Corby and one of two Tory MPs who voted against
the plan, said he was 'glad' Lady Thatcher had spoken out. But he doubted
whether Mr Major would pay much attention.
Sir Marcus Fox, chairman of the influential 1922 committee of Conservative
backbenchers, said there was 'enormous sympathy' for the views she
expressed. But 'we must leave every option open in dealing with this massive
deficit or we cannot look forward to a prosperous future.'
Mr Peter Temple-Morris, Tory MP for Leominster, said the speech was 'frankly
not quite the behaviour we expect from an ex-prime minister . . . a period
of restraint and a period of political dignity would not go amiss'.
</TEXT>
