<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Big order saves IBM factory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of IBM Havant in Hampshire, one of four large European
manufacturing plants threatened with closure earlier this year by the
computer giant, looks secure for the foreseeable future, Alan Cane writes.
Western Digital Corporation, a large US-based computer memory manufacturer,
yesterday said it had placed a contract with Havant for the assembly,
testing and packaging of its most popular personal computer disk drives.
Mr Ken Wilkie, IBM Havant chief executive, said the deal secured Havant's
future and the jobs of its 2,000 workforce. He believed, however, that
Havant would have been safe even without the order. The plant was also
building drives for IBM and special electronic circuitry for other
manufacturers.
Mr Charles Haggerty, Western Digital's chairman, president and chief
executive, said the deal would provide the company with a European source of
drives.
The Havant contract is initially for 18 months and Western Digital envisages
Havant producing 400,000 disc drives a year. The drives will go to customers
throughout Europe. Last year the company's European subsidiary shipped about
a million disk drives.
</TEXT>
