<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / World Trade News: US accused of 'foul play' in Gatt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPE's three leading aerospace companies - British Aerospace (BAe),
Aerospatiale of France and Deutsche Aerospace (Dasa) - yesterday accused the
US of foul play by attempting to use current international trade
negotiations to undermine the Gatt subsidies agreement for large civil
aircraft.
The European manufacturers, all partners in the Airbus consortium, said they
had become increasingly concerned by US efforts to include civil aircraft
subsidies into the broader subsidies code to be adopted in the Gatt Uruguay
Round trade package.
'By attempting to lump the existing sectoral agreement for aircraft
subsidies into the Uruguay Round, the US is attempting to get the issue lost
amid all the debate on subsidies to other industrial and agricultural
sectors,' said Mr Syd Gillibrand, BAe deputy chairman and president of the
European aerospace industry trade association.
European companies fear the EC may be prepared to trade off the interests of
the aerospace industry for a compromise with the US on farm subsidies.
'Important as agriculture is, you are also talking about the survival of
European high-technology and aerospace capabilities,' Mr Gillibrand said.
The three companies said in a joint statement that the European aircraft
industry currently employed directly 400,000 people and provided work
indirectly for more than 1m.
European manufacturers also claimed the US was 'back-peddling' on last
year's Gatt civil aircraft agreement between the US and the EC reached after
more than five years of negotiations. Under the pact, the EC agreed on a 33
per cent ceiling on direct subsidies for new aircraft development programmes
in return for a limit on indirect government support for civil aerospace
projects based on 3 per cent of an individual company's annual sales or 4
per cent of the country's civil aerospace industry turnover.
European companies accused the US of seeking to impose even tougher limits
on direct subsidies while maintaining indirect support through government
agencies for civil aircraft programmes. EC companies have traditionally
relied on direct supports while US rivals Boeing and McDonnell Douglas have
relied essentially on indirect support mechanisms.
There was evidence the US government was planning a sharp increase in
support for aeronautical research and development. Nasa's aeronautics budget
would increase by about 60 per cent over two years and already exceeded
Dollars 1bn (Pounds 660m) a year, the three companies said.
'All the evidence is the US is showing bad faith on the non implementation
of the indirect subsidies part of the Gatt aircraft agreement,' Mr
Gillibrand said. By attempting to move the current aircraft sectoral trade
agreement into the general Gatt subsidies code, the US was seeking to
tighten the ceiling on direct subsidies from 33 per cent to 20 per cent for
new aircraft programmes without facing similar restrictions on indirect
supports.
</TEXT>
