<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Clinton appeals for UN to step up Somalia efforts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton yesterday called on the United Nations to step up its
efforts to create a new government in Somalia so that the troops in the
multinational peacekeeping force could leave, writes George Graham.
'There has to be a political strategy that puts the affairs of Somalia back
into the hands of Somalis,' he said before a meeting with congressional
leaders, who expressed concern about the continued US involvement in
Somalia.
'We were not asked to go to Somalia to establish a protectorate, or a trust
relationship, or to run the country,' Mr Clinton said.
'That's not what we went for.'
Members of the US Congress have become increasingly sensitive about the
Somali peacekeeping operation since the killing on Saturday of three US
soldiers in Mogadishu, and the Senate has passed a resolution calling on Mr
Clinton to seek congressional approval by November 15 for keeping US troops
there.
Somalia has also loomed ominously in congressional discussions on the
possibility of sending up to 25,000 US troops to Bosnia to enforce an
eventual peace settlement.
But Mr Tom Foley, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, sought to
minimise the significance of the battle the UN faces in its pursuit of
General Mohammed Farah Aideed, a Somali warlord.
'That's in one part of Mogadishu, in southern Mogadishu,' said Mr Foley
after the White House meeting.
'In other parts of the country village elders are taking over responsibility
for governing the country, people are being fed, crops are being planted,'
he said.
Earlier this week, in a speech to the UN General Assembly, Mr Clinton said
the US would ask hard questions before getting involved in future
peacekeeping operations.
The US will send 600 troops to Haiti from next week to help peaceful
transition to a democratic government there, the Defence Department said
yesterday, Reuter reports from Washington. The Pentagon said the troops,
including engineers, doctors and military trainers, were part of a six-month
UN operation backing the restoration of President Jean-Bertrand Aristide to
power on October 30, and 'will be fulfilling a non-confrontational role'.
