<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Britain urges UN to update peacekeeping role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN yesterday called for far-reaching reforms of United Nations
operations, to make its role more effective in combating international
conflict and disorder.
Speaking to the UN General Assembly, Mr Douglas Hurd, UK foreign secretary,
urged wide-ranging modernisation of the UN approach to peacekeeping. He
suggested that certain countries with well trained, equipped and available
forces might be asked to be ready to provide the first wave of a
peacekeeping force, giving other countries time to train and equip follow-up
forces.
But the corollary of early deployment by some countries must also be that
they would end their deployment early, he insisted. 'A commitment to deploy
early would of course need to be matched by a UN commitment to agree a firm
end-date for the deployment. Exits are as important as entrances,' he said.
Mr Hurd also recommended that many peacekeeping operations might be run more
effectively by regional organisations or even by single countries on behalf
of the UN.
He repeatedly stressed there were bound to be quite finite limits to what
the UN could do in the peacekeeping field, and he called for greater efforts
to ward off impending conflicts by preventive diplomacy.
Only the UN, he said, had the legal powers to act for the maintenance of
world peace, and it could be helped to improve its record. But he warned it
could not guarantee solutions to civil wars, 'nor even to that pernicious
variant of a civil war which we see today in Bosnia'.
Mr Hurd's insistence that the UN must be clear on its objectives before
launching peacekeeping operations echoed remarks on Monday by President Bill
Clinton.
'Any operation must have clear and achievable objectives, linked to a
political process which offers reasonable hope of a solution and to which
all parties should be committed. The mandate must be precise and finite.
That means the Security Council must resist the temptation to become
involved in the detailed conduct of operations.
'Where the UN is charged with executing as well as authorising a
peacekeeping operation, all aspects of it should be handled by a single
department in New York. That is why we have suggested the creation of an
expanded Planning and Operations Staff for Peacekeeping'.
In a reference to large arrears owed by the US to the UN, Mr Hurd urged all
countries to pay their contributions in full and promptly.
Moscow has called on the UN for an offical mandate to justify Russian
peacekeeping operations in the neighbouring countries of the former Soviet
Union, and appealed for voluntary contributions from other countries to help
finance these operations.
Speaking to the UN General Assembly, Mr Andrei Kozyrev, Russian foreign
minister, made a renewed attempt to counter international reproaches over
Russia's UN contribution arrears: Dollars 261m (Pounds 169.4m) for
peacekeeping, and Dollars 81m on the regular budget.
He said the international community should recognise that Russia had a
legitimate interventionist role in its region.
</TEXT>
