<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Squabbles over IMF credit fund: The struggle to finance one
of the Fund's most successful ventures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE International Monetary Fund and World Bank are never so happy as when
producing acronyms.
But during this week's IMF and World Bank annual meetings, one choice
specimen - ESAF, standing for the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility -
has been cropping up in speeches and conversations more than most.
Through ESAF the IMF offers credits at concessional interest rates to some
of the poorest developing nations, provided they carry out Fund-supervised
economic reform programmes. Some 73 countries are eligible for the 0.5 per
cent credits, which are paid back in up to 10 years.
Since the late 1980s, about Dollars 5.6bn (Pounds 3.63bn) has been
channelled to 42 countries under ESAF and its predecessor, the structural
adjustment facility.
ESAF is generally considered a success. An IMF study of 19 recipient
countries found that their annual growth rates rose from 2 per cent to 3 per
cent after ESAF finance and reform programmes. Average export volume growth
rose to about 7 per cent from 2 per cent. Official reserves rose markedly
and average inflation, although still high and in double digits, fell by
about a fifth.
But ESAF expires in November. Unless a successor is agreed, developing
countries will lose an important source of finance. The IMF's problem is the
deadline comes when many industrial country members are strapped for cash.
The Fund wants to set up a new facility which can lend SDR 5bn (Pounds
4.66bn) over three years. But this sum, while large, is not very contentious
because it is provided in loans from industrial countries at market related
interest rates.
The money required for interest rate subsidies goes into a separate account,
is substantial and is charged to the budgets of countries that provide it.
With aid budgets under pressure, countries are thinking twice about their
contributions. Because ESAF loans have long repayment periods, the IMF
estimates SDR 2.lbn will be needed.
The IMF's industrial country members say they want a new ESAF. But comments
this week by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the UK chancellor of the exchequer, that
Britain was unlikely to contribute to the new ESAF are a measure of the
difficulties confronting Mr Michel Camdessus, the IMF managing director, in
drumming up finance for the facility.
Britain has been a generous supplier of funds to finance interest rate
subsidies in the existing ESAF. By the end of the IMF's last financial year
on April 30, some SDR 2.54bn were pledged to the ESAF subsidy account by 24
mainly industrial nations. The UK share, at SDR 361m, was well over 10 per
cent. Only Japan and France promised more.
Both Japan and France have said that they will contribute to the new
facility.
Mr Hirohisa Fujii, the Japanese finance minister, announced that Japan was
ready to provide an amount 'comparable' to its existing contributions. Japan
has lent SDR 2.2bn at market rates towards the capital of the existing ESAF
and has pledged SDR 393m in interest subsidies.
Mr Edmond Alphandery, the French finance minister, has said that France will
provide 15 per cent of the capital to the new facility, a sum roughly in
line with the SDR 800m lent at present to the ESAF capital account at market
rates.
Mr Alphandery also said France would provide funds for the subsidised
interest rates so long as an equitable burden sharing could be arranged.
The UK is pushing for more generous relief of official debt to ease the
plight of the poorest developing countries.
But the chancellor's threat to cease contributions to the ESAF subsidy
account raises the prospect of a burden sharing row.
Germany is also reluctant to dig into its coffers for ESAF. Mr Theo Waigel,
the finance minister, said he had 'only very limited possibilities' because
of budget constraints.
Various ideas have been put forward for plugging the gap. Mr Clarke has
exhumed a proposal advanced by Mr Norman Lamont, his predecessor, the IMF
should sell some gold to finance ESAF.
But this commands little support.
The IMF has done its bit. It reduced the estimated capital needs of the new
ESAF to SDR 5bn from SDR 6bn. Mr Camdessus has offered to provide SDR
500m-SDR 600m from IMF resources for the subsidy account in a move that
would reduce its financing requirement to about SDR 1.5bn.
With the deadline still two months away, some brinkmanship over ESAF is
inevitable.
Mr Clarke is certainly in a good position to fend off supplicants for
renewed UK support because UK government spending plans for the years ahead
are still being decided ahead of the November 30 budget.
But the betting is still against an outcome in which ESAF would die. 'There
will be some squabbling,' a senior official from the Group of Seven leading
industrial countries predicted. 'But we will get it done. . .in enough time
so that there won't be any interruption in the IMF's capacity to support
Africa.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    QQZ  Developing Countries.
    XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
