<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Leading senator to stand down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENATOR Donald Riegle of Michigan, chairman of the Senate banking committee,
announced yesterday he would not seek re-election next year. Mr Riegle is
the sixth senator standing down in 1994, and the third to fall victim at
least in part to financial scandal.
His departure is expected to bring Senator Paul Sarbanes of Maryland, until
now most active in budget and economic policy, to the banking committee
chairmanship.
Like Senator Dennis DeConcini of Arizona, who announced his retirement
earlier this month, Mr Riegle was one of the 'Keating Five' linked to Mr
Charles Keating, head of Lincoln Savings and Loan whose bankruptcy cost the
government more than Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.2bn).
Although the Michigan state Democratic party has rallied behind Mr Riegle,
his withdrawal will cause some relief.
The likely Republican candidate, Mr Spencer Abraham, once an aide to former
Vice-President Dan Quayle, is an astute though uncharismatic politician who
is expected to mount a strong campaign.
With 34 Senate seats up for re-election in 1994 - 21 of them held by
Democrats - Republicans have a sporting chance of reclaiming the Senate
majority they lost in 1986.
</TEXT>
