<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Camdessus calls for refocusing of economic policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michel Camdessus, managing director of the International Monetary Fund,
yesterday called on the industrialised countries 'to refocus boldly' their
economic policies to strengthen growth and employment.
Spelling out the latest IMF doctrine for its 178 members from the
industrialised, developing and former communist worlds, Mr Camdessus warned
that global economic problems were formidable but 'opportunities are in some
respects unprecedented'.
In his speech at the formal opening of the annual meetings of the IMF and
World Bank, Mr Camdessus said globalised financial markets would not
tolerate imbalances in the mix or stance of macroeconomic policy or
inconsistencies between exchange rates and fundamentals.
Warning that 'business as usual' would not solve the profound changes
brought about by globalisation of the world economy, he urged:
More liberal trade. Successful conclusion of the Uruguay Round of trade
liberalisation talks was an 'opportunity governments cannot allow themselves
to miss'. More developing IMF countries should liberalise exchange controls.
Structural reform. A key mistake of the 1980s was the failure to realise
that rising unemployment was a result of factors apart from the ups and
downs of the business cycle.
'Part of the problem is that our well-meaning efforts to protect the
unemployed and people in insecure and low-paid jobs have actually been
adding to labour market rigidities,' he said. 'I believe there is increasing
recognition of the need to reform social insurance schemes, to promote job
search and wage flexibility, to limit taxes and regulations that discourage
employment and at the same time devote more resources to education and
training.'
Lower budget deficits. Apart from Japan, countries had lost the ability to
use fiscal policy to support demand. Deficit cutting plans by the US,
Germany, Italy and Canada did not go far enough. Nearly all industrial
countries should draw up stronger medium-term deficit-cutting plans and
introduce them as recovery strengthened. They should cut subsidies and
excessive military spending.
Cutting interest rates. In Europe lower interest rates could ease stagnation
and unemployment. 'Continuing decline of inflationary pressures in Germany,
as well as further fiscal consolidation, promise relief.'
Mr Camdessus also called for a strengthening of the international monetary
system through closer policy co-ordination among the Group of Seven
industrialised countries and strengthened policy surveillance by the IMF.
Progress to European monetary union should be encouraged. Widening bands in
the European exchange rate mechanism should help recovery but 'it also
entails a risk of a relaxation of discipline. This must be resisted by a
major effort at policy convergence.'
Developing nations should follow the example of fast-growing countries by
adopting sound macroeconomic policies, liberal trade policies and stamping
out corruption.
Mr Camdessus said the world faced daunting problems. Industrial countries
had to contend with unemployment, anaemic growth and budget deficits.
Poverty still afflicted 'hundreds of millions' in developing nations,
despite strong growth in some countries.
But there were some hopeful signs. The world monetary and financial
situation had 'significantly improved'. Inflation in the industrial world
remained subdued, increasing the scope for lower interest rates. Currencies
were not seriously misaligned. The debt crisis had receded as a threat.
Strong growth in developing countries had supported global trade and growth.
Among former communist countries, Albania, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Poland and Slovenia were expected to show positive growth this year.
Global economic co-operation was improving as shown by policy changes since
the spring meetings of the IMF. In that period, the US and Germany had
adopted budget consolidation measures, Japan had taken steps to boost its
economy and interest rates had fallen in Europe.
</TEXT>
