<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Hillary steps up campaign on healthcare
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS no apple pie but a whole lot of motherhood yesterday as Mrs
Hillary Rodham Clinton took the administration's campaign for healthcare
reform to the committee rooms of Congress, writes George Graham in
Washington.
Speaking 'as a mother, a wife, a daughter, a sister, a woman,' Mrs Clinton
urged members of Congress to 'craft the most important social policy that
our nation will have confronted in many decades.'
But members of the House Ways and Means committee, the scene of yesterday's
hearings, have mothers too, and they wanted more reassurance.
'My reference is my mom, and she's concerned that you want to cut two
hundred billion bucks out of Medicare,' said Mr Pete Stark, a California
Democrat who is a staunch defender of the government-run Medicare programme
which finances healthcare for the elderly.
Mrs Clinton was not to be outmothered, however.
'I have a mother too, Mr Stark, so if we can't pass the mother test we are
not going to be able to succeed, are we?' she retorted.
The administration is expected to take another two to three weeks to produce
detailed legislative plans for the reforms outlined by President Bill
Clinton in a speech to both houses of Congress last week, so Mrs Clinton
stuck to generalities in her opening statement yesterday. But in answering
questions from members she had to tackle a clear current of concern, even
among Democrats, about the effects of the administration's proposals on
small businesses.
Mrs Clinton firmly defended the administration's proposal to require all
employers to provide health insurance to their workers and pay for most of
the premium, a proposal that has provoked apocalyptic warnings of massive
firings in small businesses in the US.
'It doesn't strike us as fair that those businesses that have made the
commitment to healthcare should not only bear the burden for their own
employees but literally the burden of the employees of others who have not
made the same choice,' she said.
This proposal is expected to be one of the most controversial in the debate
on healthcare legislation.
