<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Argentina to pay overdue interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER, Latin America Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ARGENTINA'S bank creditors will receive Dollars 700m (Pounds 454.5m) in cash
and Dollars 9bn in bonds by the end of next month in the last stage of the
restructuring accord between the government and international banks, writes
Stephen Fidler, Latin America Editor.
The payment will settle overdue interest dating back into the 1980s.
Problems in reconciling the ownership of the interest payments - caused by
active secondary market trading of the underlying loans and of the interest
payments themselves - led to a delay in the release of the bonds and cash.
Peru and its foreign bank creditors have scheduled a meeting for November 2
in New York to discuss debt restructuring. Bankers said prospects were good
that lawsuits against the government - in particular a suit by Chemical Bank
over a Dollars 20m loan to the now-defunct Compania Peruana de Vapores
repudiated in 1985 by President Alan Garcia's government - could be resolved
by November.
