<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Labour troubles boil up at foreign plants in China
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER and AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at foreign-funded factories in the Chinese port of Tianjin have gone
on strike over low pay and bad conditions at least 10 times this year,
according to an official newspaper, Reuter reports from Beijing.
The Beijing Youth News, in a rare report on labour unrest amid China's
economic boom, said the Tianjin strikes had hit mainly South Korean
enterprises, although one Japanese company was also affected. A spokesman at
the Tianjin Municipal Foreign Affairs Office confirmed he had heard of some
strikes but declined to provide detailed information.
The rash of strikes had prompted concern at high levels of the central
government, including a special study meeting at the Ministry of Labour, the
newspaper said.
It said one strike now under way 'is being handled by the relevant
authorities' but gave no details. It did not name any of the foreign
companies involved.
China has worked hard to play down the threat of strikes at its
foreign-funded factories, which have been among the best performers in the
economic upswing. Foreigners putting money into China have been promised a
compliant and nimble workforce and a government-controlled umbrella union.
A son of China's supreme leader Deng Xiaoping predicted yesterday his
father's policies would survive after his death because they represented the
wishes of China's population, AP reports from Beijing.
'I believe that China, under his leadership, has embarked on an irreversible
course of reform and opening up,' the Chinese leader's eldest son, Deng
Pufang, said at a news conference. His comments come soon after publication
of his sister's biography of their father - part of a campaign to glorify
the 89-year-old Deng and ensure his pragmatic modernisation policies survive
his death.
Asked about his father's health, he said: 'He is enjoying very good health.'
