<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / French Privatisation: France sees the Renault-Volvo merger
as Act One - Balladur's privatisation policy will take a lead from the union
of the car groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MERGER between Renault and Volvo, agreed this month and to take effect
from the beginning of 1994, was described by one French Industry Ministry
official as 'the first grand act of this government's industrial policy.' It
is unlikely to be the last.
Mr Gerard Longuet, industry minister in the centre-right government of Prime
Minister Edouard Balladur, has other ambitious proposals in his in-tray.
They involve the formation of corporate alliances to increase the
competitiveness of French public companies and ease the shackles of state
control. They also involve a paradox - to reduce the role of the state in
industrial affairs, it may first be necessary to intervene more.
Such intervention is likely to follow a pattern established by the
Renault-Volvo merger. The most important objectives of this alliance from
the perspective of the French government - the strengthening of Renault in
international markets, and the preparation of the company for privatisation
 -are themes in the government's other proposals. Among these are plans to
change the legal status of France Telecom from a state agency to a joint
stock company. A law to effect this is expected to be proposed by early next
year.
The aim is to enable France Telecom to exchange shareholdings with other
telecommunications groups and strengthen its position ahead of the
liberalisation of the European telecommunications market at the beginning of
1998. The French government already has foreign allies in mind. Mr Longuet,
for example, has described Germany's Deutsche Bundespost Telekom as 'a
natural partner on the European continent'.
Also under consideration is a proposal to combine Pechiney, the aluminium
manufacturer with Compagnie Nationale du Rhone, the electricity generator.
Pechiney, like Renault, is on the list of 21 state-controlled groups which
the government has said it intends to privatise. A tie-up with CNR might
make the sale of the loss-making aluminium concern more attractive.
Officials at the Industry Ministry describe the idea as 'a working
hypothesis' and say the proposal is at an early stage. However, it met with
a warm response from Mr Jean Gandois, Pechiney's chairman.
According to Mr Gandois, CNR could bring a stable supply of low-cost
electricity to his group, France's single biggest electricity consumer. From
the point of view of the government, CNR could represent a stable investor
to help replace the state on Pechiney's share register.
Further down the in-tray is the possibility of a restructuring at Thomson,
the electronics group. Of the companies on the government's privatisation
list Thomson is unique in having two distinct operations, the loss-making
consumer electronics division, and the profitable defence electronics
business.
Government officials emphasise that the goal is to increase efficiency with
the ultimate aim of reducing the state's role. 'Many state-controlled groups
require reorganisation,' said one official.
This is particularly the case as the government moves down the list of
companies to be privatised. The first four privatisation issues - Banque
Nationale de Paris, Rhone Poulenc, the chemicals group, Banque Hervet, and
Elf-Aquitaine, the oil group - are all in relatively good shape. Banque
Hervet is loss-making, but small.
Along with the three bigger groups, its sale is not expected to present any
substantial problems.
Beyond these four, however, the task becomes more difficult. About half of
the companies on the auction block are loss-making. Some, such as Bull, the
computer manufacturer, and Air France require substantial restructuring to
return to profitability and eventual sale. Given that the government has
committed FFr40bn (Pounds 4.6bn) of privatisation proceeds to its budget
this year and FFr50bn next year, it is under pressure to shake up the public
sector.
There are, however, limits. On a practical level, industrial restructuring
is a complex process. 'You can't just play Meccano with industry,' said one
official. Renault and Volvo took three years to transform their strategic
alliance into a full merger. An alliance or merger between Pechiney and CNR,
for example, would probably be resisted by EDF, the state electricity group,
which holds 17 per cent of CNR.
On a political level, too, there are constraints. This month Mr Balladur
urged state groups to minimise job losses in an attempt to curb rising
unemployment. To the extent that public industry is restricted in cutting
costs, such intervention could delay, rather than hasten, France's grand
acts of privatisation.
</TEXT>
