<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Germans and French scheming EC reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE and Germany are preparing potentially far-reaching reforms to
strengthen the position of big powers in the European Community.
The proposals, to be presented at the special EC summit on October 29,
threaten to open up old wounds over institutional reform already inflamed by
the debate over the Maastricht treaty.
France and Germany want to ensure that an enlarged Community remains capable
of decisions. But along with the UK, they also fear their influence being
diluted.
A broader impulse in Paris and Bonn - not necessarily shared in London  - is
to maintain momentum towards European integration at a time when doubts
about European economic and monetary union are growing.
Smaller EC members such as Luxembourg and Denmark are said to be 'appalled'
at French and German pressure to introduce new rules for majority voting in
the EC council of ministers, arguing that the reforms could relegate them to
second-class EC membership.
They warn that French and German efforts to streamline the EC and make it
less bureaucratic risk upsetting the delicate political balance which -
since 1958 - has made it a Community of equals preserving the need for
unanimity on some important issues.
Finland, Sweden, Norway and Austria fear that an argument over institutional
reform could alienate domestic public opinion already sceptical about
joining the EC.
They are worried about the impact on enlargement negotiations and possible
delay of their planned entry into the Community by January 1, 1995.
'Do the Germans know what they are doing?' said one senior Nordic official
who said Bonn had set an informal deadline of March 1 for settlement of the
institutional questions.
British officials predict a 'vigorous debate', but argue that Germany's
determination not to delay the enlargement negotiations is likely to triumph
over its interest in wide-ranging institutional reform.
The French and German proposals for reform are still in draft stage, but one
senior official said French and German positions appeared to be 'very
closely co-ordinated'. He said the ideas appeared similar to two papers
drawn up by Mr Karl Lamers, foreign affairs spokesman of the German
Christian Democrat Union, and Mr Jean-Louis Bourlanges, a French member of
the European Parliament.
These papers do not enjoy official status, but are believed to represent
strands of thinking within the French and German governments. Among the
proposals are:
A voting system in the council of ministers requiring both a majority of
member states and a majority taking into account their populations -
condition that would strengthen unified Germany.
A maximum 10-member European Commission, to be selected by the Commission
President from nominees by the member states, and approved by both the
European Parliament and the Council of Ministers.
Under this plan, the Nordic countries could no longer boast to their public
that they had preserved the right to send a commissioner to Brussels.
</TEXT>
