<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Bosnian Moslems insist on land for peace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of the Bosnian Moslem community yesterday endorsed the principle of
ethnic partition for Bosnia but rejected the partition map proposed under
the latest peace plans, and insisted that Moslem territories seized by force
should be returned.
This conditional acceptance left unclear whether Mr Alija Izetbegovic,
Bosnia's president, would now sign the peace plan and try to negotiate for
more land - or hold out for land concessions from his Serb adversaries
before approving the proposal to divide Bosnia into three ethnic
mini-states.
Serb leaders have repeatedly refused to hand over any more land, threatening
instead to rout their out-gunned Moslem opponents on the battlefield.
Sarajevo radio said 218 of 349 Moslems, including writers, religious leaders
and politicians, voted for conditional acceptance. Fifty-three voted to
accept the plan without any preconditions, and 78 voted against.
The 'qualified yes' decision of the Moslem leadership, during the first
exclusively Moslem political assembly, was non-binding. But it was expected
to sway the Bosnian parliament, which yesterday adjourned a meeting until
today.
The prominent Moslems, in raising objections to the failure of the latest
version of the partition plan to restore mostly Moslem territory, set no
deadline for when the 'ethnically cleansed' land should be returned.
Mr Izetbegovic may be hoping that severe United Nations sanctions will prod
his Serb foes into more land concessions. UN sanctions have been in force
for 16 months.
Western diplomats yesterday said the vote was a setback to the peace
process, but suggested that the result was a face-saving solution, allowing
the Moslem leaders to appease radical elements while leaving the door open
for a further agreement.
Although diplomats say an outright rejection by the Moslems could endanger a
pledge to deploy Nato troops in Bosnia, British and French officials
yesterday indicated that a 'sign now, negotiate later' solution could still
pave the way for the deployment of peacekeepers.
But in an ominous note for the new Bosnian state, Mr Izetbegovic earlier
yesterday called on the Bosnian army to defend the integrity of Bosnia after
Mr Fikret Abdic, a local powerbroker from the north-western Bihac pocket,
had apparently orchestrated his 400-member assembly to declare an
'Autonomous Province of Western Bosnia'.
The area, although encircled by Serbs rebels in Croatia and Bosnia, has
managed to survive the war by trading with its enemies.
Meanwhile, in Belgrade, the ruling Socialist party lashed out at the
ultra-nationalist leader, Mr Vojislav Seselj, after he proposed a vote of
no-confidence in the government of Mr Slobodan Milosevic. A party statement
described Mr Seselj, once Mr Milosevic's favourite politician and a
parliamentary deputy, as the 'personification of evil' who embodied
primitivism.
The Croatian president, Mr Franjo Tudjman, yesterday met the UN Security
Council in New York to present his demand that the UN peacekeepers should
either disarm the Serb rebel forces in Croatia or withdraw completely.
Mr Tudjman warned the General Assembly later that Croatia would terminate
the UN mission by the end of November, if its mandate was not strengthened
within the next 48 hours.
But UN officials insisted that the peacekeepers could not be expected to
forcibly disarm the Serb rebels, who currently control about a third of
Croatia's territory.
</TEXT>
