<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Poles build centre-left coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROSPECTS for a centre-left government in Poland improved yesterday as the
leaders of the two parties to emerge with the biggest share of the vote in
the September 19 election signed an 'initial' agreement on forming a
coalition government.
The agreement followed a meeting between Mr Alexander Kwasniewski, head of
the Left Democratic Alliance (SLD), which has 171 out of 460 seats in the
new parliament, and Mr Waldemar Pawlak, the leader of the Polish Peasant
Party (PSL), which controls 132 seats.
Both groups have their roots in the communist past when the Polish United
Workers' Party, the SLD's predecessor, governed the country and the PSL
collaborated to survive.
A statement issued by the SLD spoke of a PSL-SLD coalition, with the order
of the parties suggesting that Mr Pawlak was the likely candidate for the
post of prime minister in the next government.
Mr Pawlak, 34, won wide respect when he was prime minister for one month in
1992, but failed to put together a coalition. His party still has most of
its support in the countryside.
However, SLD spokesmen yesterday refused to comment on who would be the
leader and said that their party would talk to President Lech Walesa about
the issue. The SLD has written to Mr Walesa to ask for a meeting at which it
will report on its talks with the PSL. Constitutionally, it is up to the
president to ask a representative of one of the parties in the new
parliament to form a government.
The third prospective partner, the left-leaning Labour Union (UP), with its
beginnings in the Solidarity movement and which has 41 seats in the new
parliament, announced it would not enter an SLD-led government.
The agreement leaves the Democratic Union (UD), a mainstream Solidarity
grouping with 74 seats, in opposition.
The PSL is interested in having a say over the key economic ministries and
not just being relegated to those areas of government which impinge on the
rural population.
Thus Mr Pawlak has already said that the finance, foreign trade and labour
ministries are regarded as the key posts. His party will also be eyeing the
industry portfolio, which the PSL wants to merge with the privatisation
ministry.
Poland has been led by centrist coalition governments since the Solidarity
movement swept away communist rule in 1989 and their tough market reforms
have started to pull the country out of recession. However, many Poles have
become disillusioned with reforms that have sent real wages plummeting and
pushed unemployment above 15 per cent.
Both the SLD and the PSL support free market reforms but independent
economists expect them to advance with reforms more slowly than previous
governments.
</TEXT>
