<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Greek Elections: Greece's politicians avoid the M-word - A
campaign in which the vital question of neighbouring Macedonia is being
ducked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOWHERE is the contradiction between rhetoric and reality in Greek politics
more apparent than in Florina, a northern Greek town close to the borders
with Macedonia and Albania. A decade-long drought has reduced cereal and
dairy production there and exporting companies on Florina's industrial
estate are reported close to bankruptcy as export subsidies have been
abolished and transport costs have soared because of the war in Bosnia.
However, the region's most serious problem is the loss of contact with
Macedonia since Greece stopped issuing entry visas for Macedonians last
year. Greek political leaders have avoided raising the Macedonian question
in an election campaign fought so far on economic issues. Prime Minister
Constantine Mitsotakis, leader of the New Democracy party, is not keen to
draw attention to what many voters see as his failure to solve the
nomenclature dispute in Greece's favour.
Refusing visas is one of the ways that Greece's conservative government has
tried to pressure Macedonia into changing its name. Greece argues that the
former Yugoslav republic's choice of name amounts to a territorial threat
against the northern Greek province of Macedonia.
The opposition Panhellenic Socialist Movement, expected to win a clear
victory in the October 10 poll, is promoting a new, pro-European Community
image that could be ruined if nationalist rhetoric is allowed to take over.
The message to steer clear of foreign policy issues has been passed down to
parliamentary candidates in both main parties.
Even in Florina, where the Macedonian issue has had a severe impact on the
economy, candidates have been giving it only a passing mention in speeches.
Because Greek visas are no longer easily available, Florina has lost its
main source of income, the 20,000 Macedonians who crossed the frontier daily
on business and shopping trips. Ties with Macedonia were particularly close
because a large percentage of the district's population belongs to a
Slav-speaking minority, many of whom have relatives living across the
border.
Dozens of shops in Florina have closed and the unemployment rate has risen
to about 30 per cent. As a pre-election concession to local traders, the
government has agreed to freeze interest payments for three years on loans
from state-controlled banks amounting to Dr2bn (Pounds 5.6m).
Mr Pavlos Altinis, a foreign-educated lawyer in his 30s running for the New
Democracy party, wants to persuade local farmers to adopt better irrigation
methods to defeat the drought. Communications must be improved, with the
help of European Community structural aid, he says, in order to attract
investment.
However, like most other local candidates, he insists on taking a hardline
view of the Macedonian issue. 'We are not prepared to accept terms, such as
recognition, that will compromise our national interests, just in order to
make money out of Skopje (Macedonia),' he says.
At the same time, he acknowledges that his constituency has little chance of
climbing out of recession unless cross-border trade can resume.
Like New Democracy, the socialists say they will refuse to recognise
Macedonia under that name. However, Mr George Lianis, a Pasok candidate in
Florina, says their approach would be moderate. 'We must communicate with
Skopje,' he says. 'We can start with cultural links, and there's no reason
why we shouldn't get on to trade.'
</TEXT>
