<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 93 / Clarke would tax spending rather than income
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, yesterday gave a clear hint that any tax
increases in the Budget would be on spending rather than incomes.
He was aiming for a recovery that would be 'sustained over the rest of the
decade and beyond' and which would be 'driven by investment and exports not
consumption, by the private sector not the state'.
A tax structure 'which favours enterprise, entrepreneurship and thrift'
played an important role in achieving that goal. Taxation should not prevent
business from earning a satisfactory rate of return.
'And when we tax consumers, we should target their spending, rather than
their savings or incomes,' Mr Clarke told the annual meeting of the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank. 'That means relying, wherever
possible, on indirect rather than direct taxation.'
Treasury officials stressed that the chancellor would not be making his
Budget decisions on taxation until early November. But Mr Clarke made a
conscious decision yesterday to insert a passage about tax policy in his IMF
speech confirming his long-held preference for indirect taxes such as value
added tax.
He stressed in his speech that taxation and public spending policies had an
important role in influencing saving and investment.
Mr Clarke wanted to increase both saving and investment in the UK over the
medium term. While 'working with the grain of industry and commerce', this
meant:
Keeping inflation in its tight 1 to 4 per cent target range.
Reducing public borrowing over the medium term to underpin recent falls in
long-term interest rates.
Ensuring that public-sector pay is 'under the firmest possible control to
leave maximum scope for expenditure on productive capital projects and
essential public services'.
Gearing up the government's own investment spending through the greater use
of private finance.
The chancellor said that Britain, because of its labour market reforms of
the 1980s, was better placed than many countries in Europe to translate a
sustained recovery in output into new jobs and falling dole queues.
He said labour markets everywhere must be allowed to adapt and be more
flexible if employment were to be increased in the industrial world as a
whole.
Governments had a key role to play in improving the flexibility of labour
markets. They could concentrate resources on raising standards of education
and training and provide help for people looking for jobs.
'But the greatest contribution governments can make is to refrain from
well-meant but harmful forms of labour market regulation,' Mr Clarke said.
Tax rises may harm recovery, directors warn, Page 9
</TEXT>
