<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Arts: Smashing Pumpkins - Pop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BERLIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Far below the Brixton Academy's cavernous black ceiling, beneath the shadowy
Italianate mock-buildings that decorate its upper walls, 1,000, perhaps
2,000 young people crush together, often crash together, illuminated
occasionally by harsh white lights from the stage. Bodies rise, feet first,
from this churning sea and are passed from hand to hand before sinking
again. From time to time the mass raise their arms and point as one towards
the front of the stage on which stand three skinny individuals lit in lurid
greens, reds, blues holding guitars.
The noise is overpowering, a screaming, thudding, relentless assault not
just on the ears but on the body. This is the Smashing Pumpkins
emphatically affirming its status as one of the hottest alternative rock
bands. It is a highly enjoyable experience. (Although it helps to have been
put in the mood by security guards whose purpose in life is to stop
passholders seeing the concert.)
What lifts the band above most of its contemporaries is its ability to use
the limited and increasingly hackneyed vocabulary of loud thrash guitar rock
to express a distinctive musical personality.
On Siamese Dream, the latest album, the Pumpkins vary the pace with
moderately complex arrangements, acoustic guitar and even a dash of cello.
Live, such signposts of subletly are abandoned for simple churn and kerrang.
The effect is visceral. The fact that the speakers are so loud that every
bass note feels like a punch in the stomach has something to do with it, but
although other bands play as loud, few are as emotionally engaging.
The assault is not unrelenting. The lull in the storm is one of leader Billy
Corgan's favourite tricks. The wall of guitar noise from Corgan and James
Iha abates, to expose the powerful skeleton of the Pumpkins' music: the
edgy, sinuous, crunching rhythm of D'Arcy, the bass player, and drummer
Jimmy Chamberlin. The effect can be disconcerting. When 'Today' begins in
relative calm, the audience chants the lyrics with Corgan, a sort of
singalong-a-max-volume, before it builds to a roar that drowns even singing
along in your head.
Each song is distinctly sculpted from the noise and the brief abatement of
noise. Each possesses its own crushing logic. But the ceaseless ebb and flow
in the tidal wave of noise prevents the set as a whole building momentum.
The effect is too controlled. It is a relief when the Pumpkins finish the
set by smashing through 'Cherub Rock' in one unbroken surge.
The encore is also reassuring. It is a shambles. Corgan emerges in a clown
suit and after 'Spaceboy' - so laid back it even contains some bottleneck
guitar from Iha - the control evaporates halfway through the next song which
starts with a surge of adrenalin and dribbles to an end with Corgan
hectoring the audience in enjoyable ego-crazed rock-star style. After a
confusing final blast of parody power chords they are gone. The audience
seems unsure whether to laugh or cheer and stands as if stunned until
someone turns the house lights on.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7929 Entertainers and Entertainment Groups.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
