<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (31): The billionaire king
of sex and shopping / Media
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOWARD HUGHES: THE SECRET LIFE By Charles Higham Sidgwick &amp; Jackson Pounds
16.99 360 pages
THE MOST popular form of modern fiction is the sex and shopping novel,
mainstay of airport bookstalls worldwide. The genre mixes a racy plot with
generous bouts of sex, conducted in titillating places or positions, and
orgies of shopping, usually for designer clothes.
Charles Higham's new biography of Howard Hughes, the late American playboy,
eccentric and businessman, is the non-fiction equivalent of a sex and
shopping novel.
Hughes' life, by turns romantically adventurous, sordid and bizarre, is racy
enough for a dozen novels. The son of a Texan oil wildcatter who invented an
immensely profitable drilling bit, Hughes took charge of the family tool
business at the age of 18, on the death of his father. He developed a
passion for the movie industry and by 24 had become established as an
important independent producer in Hollywood. Simultaneously, he became
hooked on flying, and one of America's most daring pioneer aviators.
Bankrolled by his father's fortune, Hughes was able to indulge these
enthusiasms with fabulous shopping sprees: he bought RKO, the Hollywood
movie studio; he bought TWA, the airline; and he founded Hughes Aircraft,
the aerospace manufacturing business now owned by General Motors.
After moving to Las Vegas and becoming a recluse, he proceeded to buy up a
good part of America's gambling capital. He died, aged 69, in 1975, in
appropriate surroundings - an airplane cabin, on a flight to Houston.
Hughes generated controversy. In Jewish-dominated Hollywood, he had a
reputation for anti-semitism. His sexually suggestive films had trouble with
the censors.
He was, suggests Higham, a master of the art of bribery. 'I can buy any man
in the world,' he is said to have declared. He fought an epic, ultimately
successful legal battle with TWA. Higham asserts that Hughes' shady dealings
even included involvement in the Watergate burglary which toppled Richard
Nixon.
Always prone to eccentricity, he became especially bizarre as he grew older:
holed up in hotels, he would spend hours constructing neat piles of Kleenex
boxes or sitting on toilet seats.
And then there was his sex life. Higham portrays Hughes as a bisexual with
an insatiable appetite, particularly for Hollywood stars. His conquests are
said to have included Ginger Rogers, Katharine Hepburn, Bette Davis, Cary
Grant and Tyrone Power. The author even asserts that Hughes may have been an
early, but undiagnosed, victim of Aids.
However, Higham, whose previous books are mainly biographies of film stars,
largely ignores Hughes's career as a businessman - dismissing him as a
hopeless manager so obsessed by sex, flying and partying that he left the
running of his empire to others.
In Hughes' youth, says Higham, 'when balance sheets and tax charges reached
him, he tossed them impatiently aside. Had he been the industrialist he was
credited with being, he would have lost everything.'
This seems too harsh a judgment. Hughes may have been an unpleasant human
being and a poor manager, yet he was also a man of no small vision who
played a pioneering role in the growth of the modern US aviation industry.
Higham is also disappointing in his handling of his stated subject - Hughes'
private life. The reader gets bogged down by his flat writing style, wealth
of detail and strict adherence to chronology. Worse, Hughes never really
comes alive, remaining a two-dimensional enigma. In biography, as in life,
an unremitting diet of sex and shopping makes for a pretty shallow
experience.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
