<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (32): Is it really the Wall
Street of shame? - Raymond Snoddy on a racy, pacy - and possibly
preposterous - history of the Journal / Media
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POWER AND THE MONEY: INSIDE THE WALL STREET JOURNAL by Francis X. Dealy,
Jr Birch Lane Press Dollars 22.50 374 pages
THE Wall Street Journal could hardly be more respectable or respected
throughout the world of business - at least, that part of it influenced in
any way by the US.
Its staid columns, enlivened only by the occasional line drawing, are almost
eccentric in the degree to which they ignore the conventions of modern
newspaper design and presentation.
Yet according to Francis Dealy's account of the Journal and the people who
produce it, appearances are deceptive. His case is not only that the paper's
parent Dow Jones has demonstrated business incompetence on a considerable
scale, or that the Journal 'missed' some of the biggest stories of the 1980s
such as the savings and loan or the Michael Milken scandals, but that there
has been behaviour at a senior level verging on the corrupt.
Favourable stories could be planted, it is alleged, or the unfavourable
played down by taking to lunch a senior figure with a taste for social
climbing. Then there is at least one serious case of nepotism at a senior
editorial level, the suggestion that promotion owed more to living in the
same neighbourhood as senior executives and even the implication that one
senior Journal editorial figure slept with a head of state to get a
prize-winning interview.
For a book that goes on to produce such lurid allegations the narrative
begins conventionally enough with a good account of the early years of the
paper and its purchase at the turn of the century by the legendary Clarence
Barron for Dollars 156,000, including the Dow Jones Ticker Service.
Barron was a formidable business journalist whose Seven Points to Better
Reporting and Writing could still enlighten contemporary journalism
students. For example: '7. The lead is everything. Rework it thirty times.
And invariably on the thirty-first try, a perfect paragraph flows from
somewhere.'
The book is also interesting on the thinking behind the launch of the Asian
Wall Street Journal, the role of the Journal in American business life and
the perennial debate in any financial publication about where the balance
should lie between specialist and more general news - how many 'frisky
furniture' stories, as the more mundane business stories are called
in-house, should be carried.
Inevitably, however, this book will be judged on the accuracy of the more
extreme allegations made. Is the Wall Street Journal really such a seething
mass of monstrous egos, alternatively missing major stories and cutting
ethical corners?
A number of those who know the paper well have dismissed the allegations as
'bunk', and although Dealy did work at the Journal it was as an advertising
salesman.
The habit of reconstructing events through the proliferation of extraneous
detail as if there was someone standing by with a video camera does not
exactly instill confidence. ('It was Monday, May 23, 1954 at 7.43am and
Eddie Schamp, Bill Kerby's chauffeur, had the motor idling as the Dow Jones
limousine waited outside 11 Columbia Terrace . . . ')
The Power and the Money is not a book to indulge in innocent explanations
where a decent conspiracy will do or give up the chance of portraying events
in an unfortunate light for the Journal.
For example, Dealy refers to New York Times coverage on a Saturday of a case
involving a possible tobacco industry research fraud and is disparaging
about the fact that the Journal carried the tobacco industry response in its
Monday columns, something that simply could have been caused by trying to
find a fresh angle on an 'old' story. However, the author quotes an unnamed
Journal reporter as saying: 'I don't know for sure, but it is not
unreasonable to assume we downplayed the story not to offend an advertiser.'
While this is undoubtedly a racy read for anyone interested in newspapers
and how they cover business I am left with the nagging feeling that it is
not unreasonable to wonder how much of this book I should believe.
At least one important conclusion rings true - that the Wall Street Journal
has already reinvented itself a number of times, the last in the 1940s, and
that the process should not be over.
'For the Journal to continue into the twenty-first century it needs to be
transformed again. Yet like Cassandra's prophecy, the prognosis goes
unheeded,' Dealy argues. Maybe this time the transformation could include a
redesign.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
