<PROFILE>_AN-DI1CRAHGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930928
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (27): Big issues, from guru
to guru / Assessing the latest offerings in new media - Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PRABHU GUPTARA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IS THE WORLD economy going through a mere recession or a profound
restructuring? What lies ahead for companies and individuals? Large
questions such as these have exercised the mind of Peter Drucker, who was
the first modern management guru and, in spite of his advancing years,
remains the most incisive, original and stimulating management thinker of
our time.
The difficulty with Drucker's work is that it is dense and demanding: one
needs stamina and commitment to carry oneself through even his shorter
books.
So how to introduce or be introduced to Drucker's seminal insights if one
has less stamina and inclination? Warren Bennis is a guru in his own right,
and has a personable avuncular manner which enables him to carry off a
conversation with Drucker in front of the camera as if it were an everyday
event (Facing the Challenge, two videos with trainer's notes, BBC Training
Videos, Pounds 395).
With video comes variety too - here introduced not merely to provide pace,
but tactfully to illustrate and enliven the more cerebral points. And with
video comes control: you can stop the recording in mid-flow, if you wish to
pause for clarification of precisely what is an Information-Based
Organisation or a Knowledge-Worker, or of why change is a particular
challenge today.
Warren Bennis himself presents Coaching the Team (two videos with trainer's
notes, BBC Training Videos, Pounds 345) covering what he believes to be the
essential skills of management in the 1990s. These turn out to be Coaching
and Team-working; Coaching consisting of Direction, Listening, Observation
and Encouraging a Positive Attitude, and Teamworking consisting of Finding
Direction, Generating Ideas, Decision Making, Planning, Learning from
Experience, Listening, Observation and Encouraging.
I remain sceptical about how 'new' the need for these skills is; the great
leaders of the past were great coaches and produced great teams, whether one
thinks of Alexander or of Jesus. Repackaged for presentation as the concepts
of Coaching and Teamworking may be, they remain more common in the world of
talk than of reality. Lectures and video packages may not translate talk
into reality, but they do help make people aware of the need, and thus
contribute at least indirectly to bringing them to birth.
In a previous column, I mentioned the far-sighted policy of IMEC Publishing,
which issues its reference materials in computer-accessible form as well as
in print. Its Directory of Eastern European Management Education
(co-published with the European Foundation for Management Development, 40
Rue Washington, B-1050 Brussels; A-4 paperback, 520 pages, BFr 1000) is a
pioneering venture, which contains documentation on the educational systems
in Eastern European countries, as well as the programmes, profiles and
business-related faculty of all universities and business schools. The work
is surprisingly comprehensive in the context of a situation as formless,
complex and rapidly-changing as any in the world .
To make sense of this kind of a world, and to enable your company to survive
in it, you need good old leadership. If you think this, you may find your
ideas somewhat challenged by The Power of Leadership (two videos, each in a
separate pack with a copy of the script as well as a copy of the trainer's
notes, Industrial Society, Pounds 500).
This started life as a six-part Anglia TV series called Leaders, which took
the unusual step of letting an array of putative leaders and experts on the
subject speak for themselves without a great deal of editorial shaping or
comment, beyond dividing the material into the two broad themes (one per
video) of 'What makes a good leader?' and 'Leadership in action'. The result
is a fascinating variety of opinion on the subject, some of it
contradictory. This makes the videos an excellent discussion-starter on
almost any aspect.
However, the pack does editorialise to the extent of suggesting a new model
of leadership, which goes beyond the now-hackneyed contrast of management
and leadership, and includes command-based leadership, team-leadership as
well as what it dubs 'Super-Leadership' (focusing on Transformation and
Vision-Sharing).
This holistic model is quite a useful one for leaders and followers to
internalise. After all, the only true definition of leadership is the
capacity to create followers. Leadership cannot exist without followership.
It follows that if leaders and followers are to be effective, they must be
in consonance with each other.
Being in tune with each other is more difficult if one is from a different
culture, and this is the area explored by Building the Transnational Team
(one video with brief trainer's notes, Transnational Management Associates,
London &amp; Paris, no price given). Well acted by professional actors, though a
shade less well directed, the script explores stereotypically, though
wittily, the habits and perceptions of Europeans and Americans in a meeting
concerned with solving a simple problem.
The resolution of the inter-cultural problems is less persuasive because it
is presented with too little preparation - inevitable given the short
duration of this video. I wonder what it is that tempts us to want to
present a whole issue and the whole solution in 30 or 40 minutes.
I make these caveats in spite of my interest in this video, having been
invited to comment on the script in draft form. Perhaps video is better for
the presentation of issues than for the conveyance of direct instruction.
Anyway, there is little material available on transnational management, so
this video must be welcome.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7812 Motion Picture and Video Production.
    P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT933-539</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DI1CRAHFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930928
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (29): The music of strategy
/ Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REAL-TIME STRATEGY by Lee Tom Perry, Randall Stott and Norman Smallwood John
Wiley &amp; Sons Dollars 27.95 250 pages
MOST COMPANIES realise the need for change - but when the opportunity arises
can they actually seize it?
Such a question might well be addressed to US competitors of the Perrier
Group, which allowed the French bottled water company to jump back into the
game remarkably quickly after catastrophe struck in February 1990.
The discovery of traces of benzene, a known carcinogen, in the Perrier
product was arguably a once-in-a-lifetime chance for its rivals.
But while Perrier displayed considerable skill in limiting the damage - and
in reasserting its position as market leader - the lame response from its
competitors was extraordinary. Some of the excuses - lack of marketing
money, limited bottling capacity, fears that a weak Perrier might weaken the
overall market - made sense. But according to Lee Tom Perry, Randall Stott
and Norman Smallwood 'they did not go after the leader because they did not
want to change their strategies. The Perrier tragedy actually upset their
plans because they had settled into the role of industry followers'.
This book argues that in an increasingly interdependent world of
accelerating economic cycles such complacency is dangerous, and that
successful companies need to embrace the concept of strategic improvising.
Strategic improvising, the authors contend, responds to the concerns which
have been voiced about traditional strategic planning. As a real-time
process it promotes flexibility and action-oriented responses; creates a
high rate of focused innovation; and encourages greater individual
involvement and team-based thinking.
They develop a musical metaphor, based on the differences between jazz
groups (for which read strategic improvising) and symphony orchestras
(strategic planning). Strategic improvising is not directionless - hence the
analogy is with the lead sheet of a standard jazz composition rather than
the avant garde variety. Strategic improvisers are jazz players in that they
are participative, they listen and are listened to; they are responsive -
like jazz musicians acting on musical ideas rather than slavishly following
the orchestral score; and they are communicative, organised into small teams
for lateral communications. It is no accident that a jazz group is typically
five to nine members, against as much as 110 for a fully fledged orchestra.
However, this book consists of more than flights of musical fancy. It
incorporates down-to-earth case study experiences of corporations like Taco
Bell, the fast food subsidiary of Pepsico, WL Gore and General Electric,
whose improvising cultures are admired.
From these it is shown that strategic decisions are best made at all
organisational levels, not exclusively at the top; that strategic
improvising involves a 'high frequency', and typically 'low impact'
approach, the taking of lots of initiatives rather than the agonising over
each one; and that whereas strategic plans are 'front loaded' - ie a lot of
effort is put in before managers actually act - strategic improvisers
believe the process can be improved by acting before they plan.
Published in the portable MBA series this book provides a useful summary of
the criticisms of traditional strategic planning. Whether it offers anything
original is more doubtful. It makes some elegant points and provides useful
advice. The suspicion remains, though, that strategic improvising is a
mishmash of empowerment, team development, core capabilities, and other
fads.
</TEXT>
