<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (25): Imagine this - an
organised manager / Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILF ALTMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMAGINIZATION: THE ART OF CREATIVE MANAGEMENT by Gareth Morgan Saga Pounds
19.95 347 pages
THE HALLMARKS FOR SUCCESSFUL BUSINESS by David Rail Mercury Books Pounds
14.95 279 pages
EVERY management which has experienced the traumas of rationalisation and
ferocious competition has to be interested in new forms of organisation.
Gareth Morgan's Imaginization argues that we are leaving the age of
'organised' organisations and moving into an era where the ability to
understand, facilitate and encourage processes of self-organisation will
become a key competence.
But how do you avoid ending up with bureaucratic management in another form,
rather than creating an organisation with a strong degree of self-organising
while still developing a corporate culture and necessary systems?
Morgan quotes the example of an Pounds 8bn company in the natural resources
industry renowned for a hard-nosed bottom line approach and cyclical nature.
Training and development are handled through a network of consultants hired
on a task-by-task basis to keep overheads to a minimum. Costs are charged
directly to line managers using their services. For general strategy, there
is also a small group of consultants. Successful organisations grow, but
ultimately size becomes a barrier to flexibility.
Can you grow while staying small? Yes, says Morgan, by replicating yourself
in a decentralised fashion, in the style of franchising and other retailing
systems.
In the fashion industry, building an organisation to exploit a market niche
is simpler because almost everything can be sub-contracted. What happens in
a mass production unit dependent on expensive machines and equipment? The
problems of remodelling organisations remains as intractable as ever.
The author admits there is no simplistic 'cure all' technique. His
contribution is to show how new ways of organising and dealing with change
can be developed, including teamwork. 'Imaginization', he argues 'offers a
means whereby people in everyday situations can explore and challenge their
taken-for-granted assumptions while opening new ventures for understanding
and action.'
Decentralisation, franchising, sub-contracting, networking, flexitime - all
these clearly work, but the reader still remains in some doubt how many
types of bureaucratic organisation allow scope for self-organisatlon
systems. Unless you are in the middle of strategic changes, complex
operations will still need to be carefully planned and well-organised.
The Hallmarks for Successful Business is a resourceful but partly flawed
confection. As a guide for smaller and medium-sized companies, based on
research and case material, it is unlikely to leave either struggling or
fast-growing firms satisfied as an approach.
Based on six so-called hallmarks - Focus/Direction, Customising, Partnering,
Personality, Quality and Systems - the key message is that finding and
keeping customers and building relationships for repeat business is the
first and most important step.
The advice that it is better to skip less important internal matters and
visit key customers should be learned, digested and repeated aloud daily by
every executive employed even by large companies. Smaller and medium-sized
businesses are unlikely to have much time for internal meetings; satisfying
their customers must be top priority, but continually delighting them, as
the author suggests, is perhaps asking the impossible.
The author's approach is to define his hallmarks as a model for managers
planning and implementing change which he believes, probably correctly, is
missing from many businesses.
Thus personality - the character of the businesses - calls for exceptional
vitality, vision and values to be developed and communicated to all target
audiences. A learning model based on questionnaires aims to establish
awareness, assessment and action in respect of all six hallmarks in order to
develop the business.
This could have been a powerful work given a more rigorous analysis of the
determinants of success of some of Britain's best run companies, as well as
lessons from some of the failues, and applying both more challengingly as
insights to development and growth.
</TEXT>
<XX>
