<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (24): Getting rich,
cautiously / Finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK ARCHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTMENT ILLUSIONS By Martin S Fridson Wiley, Pounds 12.99, 230 pages.
THE SUB-TITLE - 'A Savvy Wall Street Pro Explodes Popular Misconceptions
About the Markets' - makes one want to ask why, if this pro is so savvy, he
still writes books when he should have retired with millions long ago.
But Marty Fridson, a managing director of Merrill Lynch and editor of 'The
Journal of High Yield Bond Research', is a Wall Street pro in the sober
rather than the speculative sense. His aim in Investment Illusions is to
debunk several of the popular fallacies underlying the get-rich-quick
attitude to investing. To appreciate Fridson's dose of common sense, you
must either have doubts about the intelligence of the US private investor,
or believe that the nation's investment diet consists of a stream of
one-stop mail shops promising enrichment.
If either is the case, then Fridson's investment homilies are long overdue.
He advises investors to read annual reports for themselves and not to take
company accounts or management statements at face value. They should
distrust chartists, understand how mutual funds performance statistics can
distort the facts; and they should not pride themselves on being contrarian
when the majority may be right.
Sometimes, Fridson's exploded misconceptions go off with a bit of a whimper.
No, he says, the stock market is not always right to assume that a share
price will rise when the company's eminent chief executive retires or dies.
And no, not every potential winner benefits from a natural disaster (in
other words, don't buy every housebuilder in the wake of a hurricane - the
US bias shows throughout).
In the UK we seem to have fewer of the over-the-top investment gurus that
Fridson sends up. Such a one is Joe Granville, who besides appearing to get
most things wrong, dressed as a chicken and liked to drop his trousers to
allow his audience to read stock recommendations printed on his boxer
shorts.
Fridson's message is that there is no quick-fix to investment success. If a
stock looks cheap, Fridson would say that it probably deserves to stay cheap
because of the risks involved. For a private investor, 'the positive pay
back of patient, conservative investing is one of the few things you can
count on in the securities markets.'
More advice of the 'how to' rather than the 'how not to' variety would have
gone a long way to smoothing the platitudinous edge off many of Fridson's
investment maxims - even if this were as uncomplicated as Warren Buffet's
four characteristics of a sound investment: a growth market, a secure
franchise, positive cash flow, and tested management.
Fridson's book will not help you make much money, but it should at least
stop you losing any. Not every stockbroker manages that.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT933-547</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DI1CRAG7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930928
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (20): Currencies and the
case for intervention / Finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOES FOREIGN EXCHANGE INTERVENTION WORK? by Kathryn M. Dominguez and Jeffrey
A. Frankel Institute for International Economics / Longman, Pounds 14.99 192
pages
AFTER THE events in the currency markets in the last year, it is a surprise
to come across a book that dares to ask whether foreign exchange
intervention can work. It is an even greater surprise to find its authors
coming up with an answer that sounds like 'Yes.'
There are times in the last 12 months when central bankers in the leading
industrial countries must have thought they were in the throes of a hideous
nightmare. Most of them have pledged to defend exchange rates within stated
or unstated boundaries. Few have succeeded.
Concerted intervention failed to stop the dollar falling to new historic
lows against the D-Mark in August 1992. Intervention by the Bank of England
failed to stop sterling falling out of the exchange rate mechanism the
following month. And intervention from the Bundesbank and the Bank of France
failed to prevent the effective suspension of the European Monetary System.
All that the latter did was to leave the French with a negative reserves
position, and the Germans with a fouled-up money supply.
But that does not mean that the principle of central bank intervention to
support or depress an exchange rate is dead. One forgets all too easily that
that late 1980s saw many successful operations by central banks first to
depress and then support the US dollar. More recently, the Federal Reserve
managed to confound the markets and prevent the yen falling through the Y100
level against the US currency, at least for a while.
And, as Kathryn Dominguez and Jeffrey Frankel say in this timely book,
central banks do not need huge reserves to outwit the speculators, even if
global currency turnover is now at a trillion dollars a day. 'The foreign
exchange market is a herd of steers, and central banks are herd dogs,' they
write, using an analogy from the American West. 'They bark and nip at the
heels of the steers, with the aim of moving the herd in the desired
direction.'
How, then, can the central banking dogs get the best performance out of the
pack?
The authors first ask why any governments should want to intervene in
foreign exchange markets at all - why the dogs have gone herding in the
first place.
It is a reasonable question. Leading monetarists have argued that the price
of a foreign currency reflects demand and supply in the market. By
definition it is the 'correct price.' Any attempt to subvert it ought to be
doomed in the long run.
Dominguez and Frankel partially concede this point when they say that
intervention is unlikely to work when it runs against the grain of
prevailing monetary policy. Intervention could not keep the French franc
within its former ERM bands because of the perception that French interest
rates were too high, given the level of unemployment in the country.
Conversely, the recent US intervention to depreciate the yen has only worked
because dealers believe that the Japanese government will introduce fiscal
measures to stimulate its economy. If Tokyo fails the dollar, the dollar
will fall.
However, intervention can sometimes be necessary - and succeed - whatever
the prevailing monetary policy.
The authors believe serious misalignments in exchange rates can occur
because of factors which are not related to underlying trade and investment
flows - and that central bankers need to respond.
They argue that a currency's exchange rate can 'overshoot,' for example,
after a change in money supply. In theory, a currency should depreciate by
an amount that is consistent with the injection of money into the market. In
practice, the currency falls further because international investors are
immediately discouraged by the prospect of investing in a currency with
lower short term interest rates.
Moreover, markets are prone to speculative bubbles which have little to do
with fundamental economic data. 'Distressing as it is for economists to
admit, many professional exchange rate forecasters and some traders do not
base their forecasts on any model based on money supplies or fundamental
economical variables,' they say. Instead, dealers use charts to extrapolate
past trends in price movements, and this can produce bandwagon effects.
These excessive currency fluctuations should worry governments: they make
trade relations more uncertain and can destabilise other markets. But what
can central banks do to ensure that their intervention is successful?
Much depends on the manner in which central banks intervene. Using data
released by the German, US and Swiss central banks, the authors discovered
that intervention was most effective in the 1980s when the authorities made
public statements to the news media, explaining exactly what they were
doing.
Moreover, if central banks want to manage exchange rates, Dominguez and
Frankel think they will have more luck if they operate flexible target
zones. 'A target zone is more likely to be sustainable when the central
parities are allowed to change over time in line with the fundamentals,'
they argue. There, in one sentence, is the epitaph on the ERM's gravestone.
The research that has gone into reaching these conclusions is highly
detailed. Beware of phrases like 'autoregressive conditional
heteroskedasticity.' Beware, too, of the algebra that stares from many
pages.
Nevertheless, the book should be useful to anyone who deals in, or writes
about, currency markets. It is a mine of intervention on the intervention
policies by central banks in the 1980s. And it traces the main arguments
over whether or not to influence exchange rates.
</TEXT>
<XX>
