<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (18): Change for its own
sake / Government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PRABHU GUPTARA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE REFORMING ORGANISATION By Nils Brunsson &amp; Johan P Olsen Routledge Pounds
12.99 240 pages
The Reforming Organisation is an excellent example of current European
thinking about organisational rejuvenation or renewal. Modern organisations
often believe it is possible to change organisational structures and
processes by rational choice and design. Indeed, organisations often go
through a series of different reforms.
The success or failure of such initiatives is never evaluated, and the
failure of old reforms that supposedly make new reforms necessary does not
seem to reduce the belief in reform in general as an approach to
accomplishing change.
The Reforming Organisation sets itself a threefold agenda. First, why it is
that reform efforts occur. Second, why reformers propose specific solutions.
Third, the effects of reforms. The authors' contention is that the origins,
content and effects of reforms are best explained, not by the rational model
so loved in the US, but by environmental and other external factors. Their
conclusion is that attempted reform often stabilises and legitimises common
conceptions in organisations, rather than leading necessarily to real
change.
But true optimism about organisational learning and renewal can only arise
from a thorough understanding of what condemns most organisations to
sub-optimal performance. The Reforming Organisation is unlikely to star in
the show-biz gravy trail of management consultancy, but it is essential for
anyone interested in organisational transformation.
</TEXT>
