<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (15): How Donald got trumped
 -Richard Lambert feels a twinge of sympathy for an '80s icon /
Economics/Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAMBERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOST TYCOON: THE MANY LIVES OF DONALD J. TRUMP By Harry Hurt III Weidenfeld
&amp; Nicolson Pounds 18.99 447 pages
DONALD J. Trump may never have existed. Rather than a flesh and blood
figure, he was perhaps the creation of a marketing genius who managed to
introduce a brand name to a class of products - real estate, casinos - that
had never been branded before. The result, for a while, was a triumph.
As Fortune magazine once wrote of The Donald: 'That name indisputably adds
value.' It went on: 'There is undeniably a Trump mystique. Some people love
him, others despise him, but everybody talks about him. He has become a cult
hero for many people around the world who seem to regard this flamboyant
billionaire as the most heartening example of the American dream come true
since Ross Perot.'
The brand was built on a unique blend of money and chutzpah. Take the yacht,
for instance. The Trump Princess, 282ft long, featured among other things a
helipad, a 16-seat main dining room with a gurgling waterfall, chamois
ceilings and onyx shower stalls.
The hotels were classy too, if you liked pink marble.
There were just two problems with this approach, but they were big ones. The
first was that the Trump name was subject to the law of diminishing returns.
It was one thing to be associated with a glossy new tower block on Fifth
Avenue, the home of kings and movie stars. But a fleet of clapped-out Boeing
727s running the shuttle service between New York and Washington was another
matter.
The second big problem was that The Donald's generous life-style depended on
an endless river of cash, and that in turn rested with those nice folks at
Citibank and the Chase Manhattan. When things started to get sticky for them
in the late 1980s, the Trump brand rapidly lost its allure. If The Donald
wasn't a zillionaire, he was nothing.
Lost Tycoon is one of those biographies that is in perfect harmony with its
subject: tacky, and a little overweight. Its author's previous bestseller
was called Texas Rich, and there is no denying that this latest oeuvre is
strongly flavoured with soap. Adjectives spray around like machine gun fire:
'A short, sharp tongued, hard drinking Jewish gaming industry gadfly in his
late fifties, Glasgow, whose birth name was Jerry Segal, came from a
moderately wealthy family whose money he had invested in a variety of
ill-fated ventures in the concrete industry.'
And so on.
The narrative is divided into three parts - 'The Crash', 'The Art of the
Spiel' and, simple but to the point, 'Best Sex Ever Had'. It's rich with
recreated dialogue and startling insights, such as the detailed account of
an event which, according to The Donald, never happened: the removal of his
surplus fat by a plastic surgery technique known as liposuction.
'The procedure. which takes a little more than two hours, is similar to
coring Swiss cheese.'
By the closing chapters, the reader begins to feel a strange and unsettling
sensation: sympathy for The Donald. Can he really be that dreadful? And
could someone with the intellectual, emotional, moral and personal
shortcomings described here really have succeeded in building an empire -
even one as fragile as the Trump Organisation?
One of the few really intriguing moments, in my UK edition at least, comes
in a footnote which bears the heavy imprint of the lawyers, and which for no
apparent reason ends in mid sentence: 'As a woman, I felt violated, as the
love and tenderness which he normally' . . . and then nothing. The editors
seem overcome with emotion at this point, since the next few pages are
splattered with errors.
Trump was a great brand name for New York in the late 1980s. For the austere
1990s, though, we need something different. Instead of a plump American,
better to go for a lean, hard Hispanic. A warrior figure, leading a small
but ruthless band of mercenaries who are ready to sell their swords to the
highest bidder. You could call him something like Jose Ignacio Lopez de
Arriortua.
But the marketing men had better hurry. This brand name might have an even
shorter shelf life than The Donald's.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
