<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (14): Competitive edginess /
Economics/Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PRABHU GUPTARA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN COMPETITIVENESS edited by Kirsty H Hughes Cambridge University
Press Pounds 29.95 312 pages
THE LEARNING IMPERATIVE edited by Robert Howard Harvard Business School
Press Dollars 29.95 352 pages
COMPETITIVENESS can be analysed at the level of individual firms, of an
industry, of a country or group of countries. And the word 'competitiveness'
itself is understood and used in many ways, though there are two broad
categories: the first views competitiveness as a question of relative
efficiency as reflected in productivity and productivity growth; the second
views competitiveness as reflecting relative international trade
performance.
Recognising the complex nature of the subject, European Competitiveness uses
all these concepts and perspectives to examine patterns of competitiveness
within Europe, as well as between Europe and its main competitors, the US
and Japan.
The essays focus on aspects of the internationalisation process, to examine
some of its key characteristics, with special attention to multinational
activities of firms in Europe, their organisational form and location
decisions.
The role of technology in competitiveness is analysed, and the book
discusses likely changes which will result from increased integration of
various markets. Finally, it discusses the role of key factors such as the
public sector and national culture, which will continue to differentiate
countries and to shape their competitiveness.
The overall message of the book is not earth-shatteringly different from
conventional wisdom, but what it does contribute is academic rigour and
thoroughness.
Relentless change demands relentless improvement. To achieve relentless
improvement faster and faster, various panacea have been attempted and found
fashionable. The most popular of these is Quality Management, the most
recent is Learning Organizations, the concern of Learning Imperative, a
selection of 17 essays on the subject from the management journal, Harvard
Business Review.
And what, pray, are Learning Organizations? Well, there is no clear
consensus among the luminaries whose work is gathered in the volume, the
first essay of which was originally published only three years ago, but that
does not reduce the variety of perspectives and routes offered.
There is some agreement, though. All the contributors see a dynamic and
volatile economy in which competition is getting tougher, technology is
moving ever faster, customers and business partners are becoming more
demanding.
All the contributors agree that the only source of continuous competitive
advantage is the people of an organisation, provided one somehow manages to
motivate them to learn faster than the competition, and to harness and apply
that learning across the whole of the organisation.
Easier said than done, even at the individual level; the thorny question is,
as one would expect, at the organisational level. The Learning Imperative
gathers together much American discussion of the subject (including the
single and highly influential non-American contribution to American
discussion by the Japanese scholar lkujiro Nonaka). However, it does not
even indicate the European discussion of the subject, which has taken place
largely in parallel to the American discussion.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
