<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (11): The man who beat the
widow's curse - Economics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TYRIE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUSTIN ROBINSON: THE LIFE OF AN ECONOMIC ADVISER Sir Alec Cairncross St
Martins Press Pounds 40 198 pages
THIS BOOK has a strong flavour of autobiography. Sir Alec Cairncross has
drawn heavily on Austin Robinson's personal papers, supplemented by long
letters from him, commenting on the draft. Much of the best in the book
comes from the horse's mouth.
It is the story of one of the last of the great Cambridge economists who
worked closely with Keynes between the wars. No theorist, Robinson's lasting
contributions came mainly as an organiser, helping to found the Central
Statistical Office, launching the International Economic Association,
participating in the creation of the Overseas Development Institute, editing
the Economic Journal for over a quarter of a century. He also flew the
earliest flying boats, taught a juvenile Maharajah, and advised governments
for over a decade.
Drawn to Keynes' Cambridge circus (as it afterwards became known) Robinson
made his mark by, among other things shattering the 'Widow's Curse' fallacy
which had caught Keynes' imagination. This held that when a businessman made
profits, those profits would not be depleted because by spending them they
would force up prices, creating profits for other businessmen. Robinson is
generally supposed to have been the one who pointed out that output might
rise instead of prices. As he said: 'If an entrepreneur loaded with profits
decided on his way home to have a shoe shine, was the effect solely to raise
the price of shoe shines, rather than affect the number of shoes shone?'
Although he contributed a good deal to the economic debates of his time, not
least with his book Monopoly and early work on development economIcs, an
interest stirred by two years in India and an extended visit to the Zambian
Copper Belt, he has not left a clearly indelible mark on economic thought in
the way that has his more theoretical wife, Joan. His gift was for rigorous
analysis of a particular problem without recourse to an overarching theory
but with the clear determination to find answers which could be translated
into policy. So it is right that this book should be subtitled The Life of
an Economic Adviser.
It seems he first flirted with the idea of working in government as early as
1931. That came to nothing, and it was the war which brought him in. He was
influential in the preparation of the first set of national accounts and
heavily involved in translating lessons learnt from war-time planning into
peace-time purposes.
Robinson doubted that investment could be directed by price signals alone.
Planning could regulate disequilibria 'by administrative and budgetary
action and by control of investment, more quickly than would happen through
the ordinary operations of the price mechanism'. In this, and in other
ideas, such as his espousal of import controls and complacency about the
sustainability of growth, he marched with the times.
It is as a product of his times that some of his observations make
entertaining reading. On a comparison of Indian and African servants: 'These
(African) people are incredibly inept and noisy servants and clat around the
room . . . in India where servants are perfect we say 'this is evidently a
servile race. They can't rule themselves'; in South Africa we say 'these
people can't even lay a table. How can they run a country?''
There is less about his wife than might have been expected. From the war
time on it seems they lived apart in a large Cambridge house. We learn that
this most famous of female economists 'slept, summer and winter, in the
garden shed, which was open to the winds, while the tits lined their nests
with her hair'.
In spite of some repetition this is a useful guide to the atmosphere of
inter-war and post-war intellectual economic life. It is not hagiography but
a tribute, enlivened by the diaries and letters of the man himself.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
