<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (10): Pitfalls of
outsourcing / Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INFORMATION SYSTEMS OUTSOURCING:MYTHS, METAPHORS AND REALITIES by Mary C
Lacity and Rudy Hirschheim John Wiley Pounds 24.95, 272 pages
FEW DECISIONS in corporate computing can be as politically charged or as
spattered with hyperbole as a resolution to move to facilities management,
or 'outsourcing'. This volume in Wiley's information systems series
illuminates the part office politics and the hidden agenda plays in what
should be a seemingly straightforward strategic decision.
Outsourcing is the use of an outside agency to fulfil a company's data
processing requirements to an agreed service level for an agreed fee. In
some cases, the agency takes its customers' computers and data processing
staff on to its own books; in others, the company retains ownership of staff
and machines.
The UK government's 'market testing' plans - where a department's ability to
deliver IT and other services efficiently are to be measured against the
market alternative - are outsourcing on a grand scale.
Whatever the flavour of outsourcing, the advantages to the customer are
perceived to be a cap on information technology costs and freedom from the
chore of running a department which may have nothing to do with the
company's core business. These have powerful appeal to chief executives who
see the information systems(IS) department as a burden on resources. Twenty
per cent of Fortune 500 companies are likely to sign outsourcing deals by
1994, it is said.
The dangers are that the company loses control of its crown jewels - its
data - and its source of competitive advantage - its information technology
strategy. At a personal level, the company's information systems(IS) manager
stands to lose his or her job in the changeover.
Anyone wrestling with whether to outsource his or her organisation's data
processing operations would do well to digest Mary Lacity and Rudy
Hirschheim's carefully researched study. The two academics analysed 13
companies where outsourcing had been examined as an option. Their
conclusions cast doubt on many popularly held views of outsourcing and
should help to cut through the hyperbole.
They suggest, for example, that publicly available information about
outsourcing presents an overly optimistic view: 'Outsourcing is not a
panacea for information systems problems,' they say. 'Several participants
suffered severe service degradation and paid significant excess charges that
negated expected savings.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
