<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (6): Near-perfect parable of
the phoenix's rise - Kevin Rafferty admires an elegant account of Japan's
rebirth from the ashes of war / Economic History
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN RAFFERTY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S CAPITALISM: CREATIVE DEFEAT AND BEYOND by Shigeto Tsuru Cambridge
University Press Pounds 24.95 277 pages
ONCE UPON a time, a Japanese village had three brothers, Strong, Rich and
Warmhearted.
At first Strong was the dominant force, using his might to make things
right, until age began to tell, his strength faded and he yielded his power
to Rich. Rich built a big empire, but his wealth was stored in warehouses
which were burned to the ground in a fire, leaving him penniless.
Warmhearted, meanwhile, had been studying medicine, which knowledge was put
to good use in diagnosing, isolating and treating the epidemic that raged
after the fire, saving countless lives.
Warmhearted became the real and lasting hero of the village, commemorated by
a statue in its centre. 'Warmhearted triumphed over Strong and Rich,' notes
Shigeto Tsuru, concluding the children's story.
The inclusion of such fairytales tells a lot about Tsuru's broad and
humanitarian approach. Of his scholarship there can also be no doubt.
Distinguished as both a practical and an academic economist, his
understanding of the politics as well as the economics of war and peace was
honed successively as student leader against the Japanese military; as a
Harvard academic assisting Gottfried Haberler and Wassily Leontief; as
Japanese wartime infantry private and later foreign ministry official; under
the same roof as his wife's uncle and Lord Privy Seal Marquis Kido when Kido
was attempting to end the war; as vice minister on the post-war Economic
Stabilisation Board; then as professor of economics and later president of
Hitotsubashi University.
This book is quite simply the best history yet written of Japan's
Phoenix-like rise from the defeat and ashes of the War. It is spare but
incisive. Tsuru's mastery of sources is marvellous. He has consulted
dry-as-dust government documents, corporate reports, classical and modern
economists, the oriental classics, fairytales - even modern journalism. He
has distilled their essence, added the lessons of his own practical
experience and political understanding, and turned the account into English
prose that is easy, even sweet to read.
One of the pleasant things is to see remembered with affection unsung heroes
such as Wolf Ladejinsky, who helped in the post-war land reforms and went on
to assist Taiwan, then India. Tsuru carefully explains important and
powerful Japanese practices like window guidance (the Bank of Japan's
dealing out of credit) and administrative guidance (under which government
agencies without explicit legal authority direct or induce private Concerns
to take or refrain from actions).
He concludes: 'It may well be that the traditional dislike of open legal
procedures in the social climate of Japan has nurtured the practice of
resolving an issue through informal, quasi-voluntary jawboning and
finger-pointing of the type peculiar to Japan.' He also offers a valuable
assessment of the extent to which Japan relied on export-led growth.
In spite of its slimness, there are few deficiencies in the history. Tsuru
has illuminating insights into how Japan succeeded in building its sewing
machine, camera and watch industries and how collusion between government
and manufacturers helped nurture the growth. It would, however, have been
nice also to have examples of the failures of the Ministry of International
Trade and Industry in guiding Japan's miracle.
Tsuru's natural sympathies are with the left, revealed in his quotation of
John Ruskin's address to manufacturers at Bradford in 1859: 'You must
remember always that your business, as manufacturers, is to FORM THE MARKET
as much as to supply it . . . But whatever happens to you, this, at least,
is certain, that the whole of your life will have been spent in corrupting
public taste and encouraging public extravagance.'
He expresses great anger at Japan's other GNP or 'Great National Pollution',
righteously and rightfully indignant at the way the Inland Sea, a rich
natural treasure-house of resources, has been violated by heavy industry.
The author's concluding concern is whether modern Japan will become
Warmhearted, or instead be selfishly Rich. In Tsuru's view, this is probably
the most important part of the book. It is certainly the most
thought-provoking, but also the weakest. He needed more space to expand his
ideas. The greatest weakness is the gap between the author's five
prescriptions for future Japanese policy - essentially that it should be a
centre for excellence and promotion of international understanding and aid -
and the real world of grubby politics.
His highly pertinent comments on the US-Japan Security Treaty, and his
criticisms of the GNP Growthmanship of Rich Japan, lose their impact
precisely because his ideal world is so far from the real one, whereas. in
the historical sections Tsuru was 'at nose length' from the major events.
Historians, political scientists and economists alike should nevertheless be
grateful for this account, and practising politicians and bureaucrats in and
outside Japan would do well to consider its implications. Right to the end
Tsuru is cheering Warmhearted. He mixes folk-wisdom with scholarship,
remembering that it is 'the sun, not the north wind, (that) may make the
traveller take off his coat.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
