<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (5): The condensed art of
literary deception - Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THEIRS WAS THE KINGDOM: LILA AND DeWITT WALLACEAND THE STORY OF THE READER'S
DIGEST by John Heidenry Norton Dollars 29.95 701 pages
IN 1921 a young man armed with sheafs of yellow notepaper took to spending
long hours in the periodicals room of the New York Public Library, sitting
alongside local down-and-outs sheltering from the cold. Many of the library
staff dismissed him as just another eccentric.
Had they but known it, they were witnessing the birth labours of the world's
most successful magazine, Reader's Digest, the foremost literary exponent of
conservative, middle-brow, middle American values and one of the country's
leading cultural exports.
The man in the periodicals room was DeWitt ('Wally') Wallace, founder of the
Digest, who was trawling through the library's magazine racks for articles
he could summarise in his new publication or pithy quotations he could
recycle under the title 'remarkable remarks.'
Wally, the son of a mid-western academic, was in the grip of one of the best
publishing ideas of the century, which had come to him one summer night on a
sheep farm in the vastness of rural Montana, where he was working
temporarily as a hired hand.
He believed a market might exist among ordinary, hard-working American
families, with little spare time and less money, for a magazine with no
advertisements and no illustrations which condensed the most useful
non-fiction articles published by other journals.
Numerous publishers whom he approached rejected the idea. But Wally, stirred
out of the resulting bouts of depression by his new wife Lila, raised
sufficient funds from his family to start it himself, as a mail order
venture. It was an instant success.
From its first issue, says John Heidenry, Reader's Digest became a secular
Bible of a 'deeply religious and immensely disaffected and fearful majority
 -three-fourths of whom still lived on farms. Even when its circulation
numbered only in the thousands, the RD was a mass magazine in sensibility,
taking the side of the vast conservative majority on almost every issue.'
Heidenry, a freelance author, has produced a gripping, wry and gracefully
written narrative history of the Wallaces and their publishing empire.
He makes clear that Wally's genius was twofold. First, he possessed an
extraordinary common touch - a feeling for just exactly what the general
reading public wanted.
Second, he was a master of the art of mail order solicitation. In the early
days, he used to read the YWCA house magazine for news of job transfers, on
the principle that a young woman sent to a strange town would welcome 'any
letter, even a promotion piece.' The Digest became proprietor of the world's
largest mailing list.
Wally's keen marketing sense was evident from the Digest's very first issue.
Assuming, correctly, that the magazine would be primarily bought by women,
he named his wife and her cousin as co-editors, even though neither ever had
any real involvement in the editorial side of the publication.
In later life, Wally rankled at the fact that his wife was given joint
credit for his creation. Yet Lila was throughout her life a powerful
presence behind the scenes. That was brought home in traumatic fashion on
Christmas Eve, 1965, when Wally used a staff party to summarily oust his
long-time general manager, Al Cole, and demote Cole's protege Fred Thompson,
who happened to be Wally's nephew-in-law.
Thompson had been widely regarded as the heir to the Wallaces' business, on
the strength of his business ability rather than nepotism.
Heidenry says the 'Christmas Eve' massacre was the work of Lila, who, having
endured her husband's infidelities for years, drew the line at his recent
affair with her tall, blue-eyed niece, Thompson's wife Judy.
'Lila, like Salome, demanded the head of Fred Thompson on a platter. Wally
finally had to render to his wife the most valuable thing he possessed - the
power to determine the future of the company.'
Sex, in one form or another, had always played a significant role in the
life of the Digest. Heidenry points out that in its early days the
publication was to 'publish more and better sex information, and take a more
progressive attitude towards sex in general, than any other commercial
publication in the English language.' It was also to publish more off-colour
jokes than any other respectable magazine in history.
Yet this liberalism was combined in the editorial pages with the reactionary
political views, including an ugly racist chord the Digest was to sound for
decades.
A further paradox was that this most wholesome of magazines had it origins
in literary piracy. In the Digest's early years, Wally lifted articles
without permission or payment of fees from other magazines - and made sure
that all of his subscribers lived far from the publishing centres of the
East coast, where his theft might be discovered.
It was the start of the company's culture of secrecy, which persisted until
very recently. In the 1930s, when the Great Depression took a toll on
magazines, and thus the source of Digest fodder, the magazine resorted to
another great deception: it commissioned and paid for articles which it
planted in other magazines, purely so it could itself run condensed
versions.
Heidenry is at his best when describing these early decades, and the group's
phenomenally successful move into fiction publishing after World War Two.
The second half of the book, which deals with the Digest's development from
a huge 'mom and pop' business into a global bureaucracy, is equally
authoritative, but the story is less compelling and burdened with too much
detail.
This is a very good book, but one which could perhaps have learnt something
from the Digest's art of condensation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
