<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (3): High-tech is a means,
not an end / Review of an admirably balanced examination of innovation in
industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEOFFREY OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL INNOVATION SYSTEMS, A COMPARATIVE ANALYSIS by Richard R Nelson
(editor) Oxford University Press Pounds 25.00 541 pages
THERE IS a widespread belief in Europe that high-technology industries such
as electronics and aerospace have a special economic importance and deserve
to be supported by governments. Some influential members of the Clinton
administration hold the same view, arguing that the US should be more
aggressive in defending what are sometimes called strategic sectors or
critical technologies against state-subsidised competition from abroad.
Yet as Richard Nelson observes in his conclusion to this admirable study of
national innovation systems: 'There does not seem to be strong empirical
support for the proposition that national economies are broadly advantaged
if their firms are especially strong in high tech and disadvantaged if they
are not'.
The US economy, Nelson Points out, has been lagging badly for nearly 20
years in spite of continuing dominance in some high-tech industries; France,
he suggests, has been economically successful 'more despite her efforts to
nurture and subsidise her high-technology industries than because of them'.
Even if the existence of successful, nationally-owned high-tech companies is
thought to be a desirable objective, the record of government policies in
this field is at best uneven. In his chapter on Germany Otto Keck notes that
in the post-war period the federal government 'was hesitant in assuming
responsibilities for science and technology, and where it did, as in nuclear
power, aerospace and electronic data processing, its programmes for
supporting industrial technology were ineffective'.
Francois Chesnais writes that a large part of French high-tech industry has
been shaped by military demand; competitiveness in commercial markets has
not been helped by 'the highly customised, non-generic features of military
technology and their very low degree of transferability to civilian uses'.
He also argues that the overwhelming bias in favour of defence-related
technologies has been to the detriment both of the chemical, biological and
life-science sectors and of industries such as machine tools which tend to
be dominated by small companies.
US experience shows that, in certain circumstances, especially when a
technology is at an early stage of development, defence-related procurement
can be a stimulus to commercial application. This was the case in
semiconductors in the 1950s and 1960s, when the existence of a large
military demand in the US lowered the marketing-based barriers to entry.
Small firms such as Texas Instruments could direct their development effort
to the needs of a single large customer and use that business as the basis
for building a broader range of customers and applications.
The American contributors to this volume, David Mowery and Nathan Rosenberg,
suggest that commercial spillovers from defence research and procurement
fluctuate over time within a specific technology; the trend in recent years
has been for the needs of the two markets to diverge and thus for spillovers
to diminish in importance.
So what should governments do? Two crucial determinants of a nation's
innovative capacity are the education and training system and the
macro-economic environment. It was institutional innovation, particularly
the close links between research-oriented companies and the science
departments of universities, which gave Germany the lead in dyestuffs and
pharmaceuticals at the end of the 19th century; some 3,000 chemists were
employed in German industry in 1897, far ahead of Britain and the US. In
more recent times Korea and Taiwan are examples of education-led growth.
Their ability to move quickly from simple to complex products was made
possible by the availability of a young, highly-educated workforce.
As for the economic environment, fiscal, monetary and trade policies need to
be designed in a way which encourages firms to compete in world markets,
rather than 'hunkering down' in protected national markets. With the partial
exception of the US, exposure to international competition has been a
characteristic of most successful innovating nations.
In addition, governments have an important role in supporting basis
research. Problems arise when they go 'downstream' and back specific
industries and companies. In an interesting chapter on Japan, Hiroyuki
Odagiri and Akira Goto concede the importance in the 1950s and 1960s of
MITI's control over the importation of technology and the restriction on
inward investment. These policies probably contributed to Japan's catch-up
with more advanced countries, but since the early 1970s the involvement of
MITI has been much less and government-business relationships have been
weakening.
The authors stress internal competition as one of the keys to the country's
technical progress. Entry into growing industries has been fast and
frequent, inducing in the companies 'a strong sense of crisis and a
motivation to be innovative'.
Picking winners in the hope of establishing world leadership in an emerging
technology is risky and potentially expensive. As Nelson argues, active
government policies are often more effective when they are aimed at
encouraging industry to take up new technologies than when oriented towards
subsidising big breakthroughs.
In Germany, for example, after their lack of success in targeting specific
sectors, the authorities have recently been focusing on the diffusion of
technology and on strengthening cooperation among firms or between companies
and public research organisations; the aim is to alert companies to
technological frontiers and to create links between suppliers and users of
specialised inputs. British policy has been moving in a similar direction.
The 15 countries covered in this book include large and small industrial
states (Sweden, Denmark, Canada, Australia and Israel, as well as the four
bigger European countries, the US and Japan), and successful and less
successful developing countries (Brazil and Argentina as well as Korea and
Taiwan). As a collection of papers from different authors, the book is
unusually coherent in its scope and analysis. It provides a wealth of
information not just about technology policies, but about the institutional
and cultural factors which influence each country's industrial performance.
There is no single route to success. Thus Korea and Taiwan are similar in
their commitment to education, but in other respects have followed quite
different policies. Korea has encouraged the creation of large conglomerates
and resisted inward investment; Taiwan has been less favourable to large
firms and has admitted foreign companies selectively.
In some cases, as in relations between Japan and the US, differences in
innovation systems have become a source of trade friction. But Nelson is
surely right to describe as somewhat hysterical the current concern about
allegedly unfair competition in high-tech industries. Much of the concern is
based on misunderstandings about how governments intervene and about the
effects of intervention on competitiveness. This book is an important
contribution towards more balanced discussion of high-tech issues and more
rational government policies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
