<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (4): The amorous accountant
/ Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANCY'S FAULTY SUMS by Keron Bhattacharya Macmillan, Pounds 25
BEYOND THE BOTTOM LINE by Alan Warner Gower Pounds 19.50
Phil turned to Christine as she started explaining how to value the company.
But he found it hard to concentrate on the numbers as he remembered the time
they spent together in London . . .
Well, even though you and I might consider the answer obvious, your
high-fallutin' accountant has another way of dealing with the figures which
he manages to justify, oh yes.
IF THERE IS one trap that two new accountancy textbooks manage to avoid, it
is a conventional or boring approach to their subject.
Accountancy's Faulty Sums, by Keron Bhattacharya, a business consultant, is
a guide to the basics of external financial reporting and internal
management accounting. He touches on many interesting and topical issues,
including the favourite of the year, the creative accounting devices used to
flatter profits or conceal liabilities. He also provides an introduction
into theories such as Activity Based Costing.
Probably the greatest strength of the book lies in its examples. Some draw
on well-known corporate events to illustrate a point, such as the problems
at Cray Electronics and Atlantic Computers.
Others come from Bhattacharya's own experiences. He talks about the
accountant at one company he was helping to sell who valued stock based on
budgeted expenditures devised a year previously at a time of high inflation,
substantially swelling losses.
He mentions another company he was closing as an illustration of poor cash
control. He at first planned to pay all creditors, but then decided to write
and ask them if they had any claims. About 90 per cent wrote back to say
they did not, so he kept it.
The style of writing and the degree of detailed analysis is a rather more
awkward point. The chatty approach may appeal to some, but others will
consider it a little too irritatingly long-winded, unstructured and full of
waffle.
He refers to Pacioli, the man credited with inventing double-entry
bookkeeping, as 'that old codger from Venice 500 years ago'. A little more
research and re-writing would have been worth the investment.
Beyond the Bottom Line is written rather more racily. Alan Warner, a
management training consultant, uses the highly original approach of a
romantic business novel to teach the rudiments of management finance.
Phil Moorley works for Chapman Foods in New York, becoming president shortly
after a takeover bid from Universal, his previous employer. Christine
Goodhart is the management consultant he hires to help him understand the
accounting issues.
But Phil is also middle-aged and insecure. Christine is blonde and
beautiful. They had something of a fling in Britain in the past, or so we
gather in numerous references to Warner's previous book, The Bottom Line,
published in 1988.
Will Phil remain loyal to his wife, or once more succumb to Christine's
charms? Will he ever get to grips with the jargon of the takeover and defend
Chapman against Universal?
All we can hope is that Warner's understanding of management accounting is
somewhat better than his rather crude characterisations. However, Beyond the
Bottom Line is certainly a readable way to wade through financial issues
pegged to real examples in a practical way.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
