<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: TSB advances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Banking group TSB moved ahead 6 to 217p, as volume rose to 6.7m, after two
brokers upgraded profits expectations, a move which boosted sentiment in the
sector as a whole.
Lehman Brothers, the US investment bank, and SG Warburg raised forecasts
following a meeting with the board last Friday. Lehman increased its
forecasts by Pounds 30m to Pounds 260m for this year and by Pounds 15m to
Pounds 440m for the following year; while Warburg is now predicting that TSB
will make Pounds 280m this year, against its previous projection of around
Pounds 245m.
Speculation that TSB had at last found a buyer for Hill Samuel, its merchant
banking arm, was again heard. The positive mood on TSB, together with the
strong market trend, helped other stocks in the sector. Barclays hardened 2
to 506p, while Lloyds appreciated 9 to 566p. Royal Bank of Scotland gained 6
at 313p.
A squeeze in Forte sent the shares smartly forward to close 11 ahead at
240p. Leisure specialists said there was also a relief factor following
weekend press reports that the group is unlikely to make a long-rumoured
rights issue with its results tomorrow. Turnover was 1.9m.
Presentations to analysts by Hazlewood Foods prompted a raft of slim
downgrades, the shares reacting badly and finishing 8 off at 175p. BZW cut
its profits forecast to March 1994 to Pounds 57.5m, with Smith New Court
trimming to Pounds 59m. Analysts attributed the downgrades to general dull
trading.
Rumours of a more positive attitude towards Northern Foods after last week's
downgrades left the shares 7 better at 257p.
Food retailers rallied after last week's mauling which followed Tesco's
results, some in the market believing the falls to be overdone. Tesco firmed
2 to 204p and J. Sainsbury 6 to 434p.
Confirmation that Severn Trent is to lose its chairman in a board shake-up
left the stock 7 lighter at 546p in a weak waters sector.
A big seller of Boots set the stock back 4 to 479p. SG Warburg was said to
be positive on Kingfisher, up 6 at 672p.
Talk of continuing good sales at Marks and Spencer saw the shares add 3 at
379p.
Hammerson was the odd stock out in a strong property sector as the shares
reacted to dull results, the 'A' slipping 5 to 353p. Property specialists
said that although the new management had started well, its hands were tied
in a continuing difficult market. Land Securities climbed 6 to 678p and
Great Portland Estates 7 to 211p.
Engineering group Siebe gained 6 at 525p after both Kleinwort Benson and
NatWest Securities came out with positive comments on the group. While
saying it remained 'neutral' on the stock, NatWest said Siebe was one of the
stocks that 'would do well in any year-end rally'.
Positive weekend press comment, together with talk that a recent stock
overhang had been cleared, saw shipbuilding and engineering group VSEL move
up 9 to 857p.
Brokers remained positive about British Steel, which ended 4 higher at 123
1/2 p on trade of 8.6m.
In motors, GKN closed a penny down at 479p, with Kleinwort Benson said to
have reduced current year profits expectations.
Channel tunnel operator Eurotunnel was back in favour with investors ahead
of interim results due within a fortnight. The stock jumped 18 to 508p.
Favourable sentiment in Mersey Docks following its recent acquisition of
Medway Port continued to lift the shares, which added 9 at 388p.
Bargain hunters were seen for P&amp;O shares, which have been underperforming
since the group's recent disappointing figures. They put on 14 at 575p.
Dealers said container rental group Tiphook remained friendless in an
otherwise strong market, losing 7 at 257p.
Shares in Prudential Corporation were boosted by a recommendation from SG
Warburg and finished 7 ahead at 346p after trade of 1.8m.
Steel Burrill Jones continued to languish after its recent poor set of
figures, the shares receding a further 15 to 123p.
A profits warning and the passing of the dividend from Andrew Sykes saw the
shares tumble 30 to 75p.
Reuters finished 6 stronger at 1538p, with sentiment boosted by news that
the London International Financial Futures Exchange is to resume talks on
joining Globex, the round the clock futures trad-ing system co-developed by
Reuters.
Dealers expect the shares to continue moving forward today following a
presentation of the Dealing 2,000 system at Henderson Crosthwaite to
institutional clients.
</TEXT>
