<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Oil sector firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Reports that Opec ministers meeting in Geneva had agreed to set the ceiling
on their total output for the fourth quarter at 24.5m barrels per day
cheered the market and drove several oil stocks sharply forward.
The positive progress of the Opec talks also brought a slight improvement in
the oil price, which helped to underpin the day's advance in oil shares, as
did a slight shortage of stock earlier in the session.
The day's main advances included British Petroleum, which rose 11 to 313p
with just over 6m shares traded, Enterprise Oil, 12 up at 444p, and Shell
Transport, 9 stronger at 660p in trade of 1.8m.
However, talks about the distribution of quotas within the ceiling were
still in progress by yesterday's market close and one analyst remained
cautious and said: 'Today's rise may be premature given that nothing has
been decided about the quotas.'
</TEXT>
