<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Brewery nerves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Troubled Brent Walker, reporting increased losses and warning of continued
caution over current trading, was said to have prompted a large seller of
Allied-Lyons on nervousness regarding the pub leasing arrangement between
the two companies.
Allied has leased Brent Walker more than 730 pubs as part of the
government's Beer Orders, and the poor Walker figures combined with warnings
from the group over its hefty interest charges led some to speculate that
Walker may wish to terminate the arrangement. Allied fell 12 but rallied to
close just 3 off at 560p. Turnover was an average 2.5m. Walker edged up to
7p.
Speculation that Allied is about to sell its Grant of St James spirits
business to Matthew Clark intensified after the latter was suspended at
470p. However, Clark would have to raise close to its market capitalisation
of around Pounds 60m to secure the business. Analysts said the move would be
seen favourably for Allied.
</TEXT>
