<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Footsie climbs away from 3,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON joined in the strong rebound in European stock markets yesterday,
which welcomed the calmer news from Russia, and the Footsie ended
convincingly above 3,000 for the first time in a fortnight. Calls for
interest rate cuts from Sir Leon Brittan, chief EC trade negotiator, found a
ready response in the stock market, and a strong opening to the new Wall
Street session gave further encouragement.
Equities were easier at first and the Footsie 3,000 mark came in for another
testing in early trade. But once the December futures contract on the
Footsie opened at a strong premium, the direction of the stock market was
never in doubt. The pace of the advance was dictated throughout by the
December contract but its premium of 36 against the underlying equity market
ensured a sound stock market. Dealers in both equities and futures agreed
that it was the strength of the German stock market which lay behind
London's rise.
At the close, the FT-SE 100 Index was 21.1 up at 3,026.3, just under the
best of the day. Trading volume was slow at first but picked up as investors
gained confidence. The day's Seaq total of 540.9m shares compared with
527.3m on Friday, when retail business worth Pounds 1.46bn maintained the
improvement in turnover volumes achieved this year.
Arbitraging between the December future and the underlying stocks returned
the focus to the blue chip issues. Consequently, the FT-SE Mid 250 Index, up
5.2 at 3,437.1, saw less activity than in recent sessions.
Firmness in government bonds ahead of tomorrow's auction of Pounds 3.25bn
securities and also in sterling fuelled hopes of a cut in domestic base
rates, perhaps around the time of the annual conference of the governing
Conservative party.
Optimistic views on the outlook for corporate profits from two leading UK
securities houses also helped sentiment. Shares in Grand Metropolitan, the
brewery and hotels group, closed higher despite the market's slightly
cautious reception of its latest trading statement.
The Footsie Index benefited from strong gains in leading oil shares as the
meeting of Opec ministers in Geneva got under way. But the pharmaceuticals
sector lagged behind both London and New York as the less positive trend in
the US dollar helped unsettle share prices.
The renewed hopes that base rate cuts might not be too far away brought
firmness in bank shares, where lower interest rates would ease the burden of
bad debts. Similar factors helped the consumer retail sector, which will be
featured this week by boardroom statements from two leading names. Some
building and construction stocks also responded to base rate optimism.
Traders noted that trading volume in the futures market, where the big
securities firms often re-position themselves before buying the underlying
stocks, had been high yesterday. If the institutions have turned more
optimistic towards UK equities, then traders would expect to see this
reflected in higher Seaq trading figures later this week.
Equity strategists, favourably impressed by the stock market's resilience in
the face of the potentially disturbing developments in Russia, now hope for
an improvement in the trend of corporate results from British companies.
</TEXT>
