<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARPLY improved trading volume in stock index futures restored the December
contract to a good premium and provided the driving force behind the stock
market yesterday, writes Terry Byland.
London took its cue from the recovery in the German stock market, although
UK equities were slow to move until the futures market opened.
The strength of the December Footsie contract, which stood at a 36-point
premium, brought arbitraging between futures and equities, chiefly by one
large UK securities house and a leading Japanese firm. They were able to
sell the future at its peak and buy the underlying stocks, taking advantage
of a US house which found itself short of the future and was obliged to buy.
December closed at 3,066, a 34-point premium against cash and 12 to fair
value. Volume increased to 10,864 contracts, compared with under 8,000 in
the previous session. However, the future traded 15,000 contracts at the
beginning of last week.
With dealers concentrating on the Footsie future contract, traded options
had a calmer session, with 23,835 contracts transacted against 36,996 on
Friday.
Even the FT-SE 100 option was significantly less active than on Friday,
recording 9,375 lots compared with 14,891. British Steel topped the active
stocks list for options with a figure of 3,812, followed by J. Sainsbury at
1,397.
</TEXT>
