<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow helped by resurgent bond
prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HAVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
PROGRAM trading and a surge in bond prices, which pushed long-term yields
back below 6 per cent, provided a strong lift to US stock markets yesterday,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was 24.59 higher at 3,567.70.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 climbed 4.17 to 461.80, nearing
its closing all-time peak of 463.56 of August 31, while the American SE
composite gained 1.91 at 456.44. The Nasdaq composite, which last week
climbed to historic highs in spite of weakness in the wider market,
maintained its surge and ended 5.30 stronger at a record 759.95. New York SE
volume came to 245m shares.
The week got off to a positive start, thanks primarily to the resurgent bond
market. Last week's news that the Federal Reserve's policy-making Open
Market Committee had shifted the bias of its monetary policy from an
inclination to tightening back to a neutral stance was the fuel propelling
the bond market yesterday. By late afternoon the 30-year bond was up more
than one point, and the yield was back down to 6 per cent for the first time
in several weeks.
The bond rally heartened equity investors who, after seven days of flat or
lower share prices, were in the mood to buy stocks again. Computerised buy
programs kicked in almost from the start, and by the end of the first 30
minutes of trading the Dow was up 22 points. Investors were also encouraged
by overnight gains on European equity markets, although the day's domestic
news - a 1.3 per cent decline in August existing home sales - had a
dampening effect upon sentiment.
Paramount Communications rose Dollars 2 to Dollars 77 5/8 in volume of 2.4m
shares on reports that the entertainment group's management, which two weeks
ago accepted a Dollars 67.50 a share takeover bid from Viacom, is prepared
to consider the rival Dollars 84.25 a share offer from the television
shopping network QVC. Amid the uncertainty, Viacom advanced Dollars 1 5/8 to
Dollars 62 1/2 on the American SE, and QVC, listed on the Nasdaq market,
fell Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 59 5/8 , a possible indication that investors
believe that QVC will win the Paramount takeover battle.
Falling interest rates were good for bank shares. JP Morgan, a Dow
constituent, climbed Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 77 1/8 , Citicorp added
Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 37, Chemical put on Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 44 7/8 ,
Chase Manhattan rose Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 37 1/4 and Banc One firmed
Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 41 7/8 . The exception was BankAmerica, which
declined Dollars 1 to Dollars 45 3/4 .
Drug issues, still troubled by uncertainty surrounding President Clinton's
health care reform plan, which was unveiled last week, mostly bucked the
market trend. Pfizer eased Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 60 7/8 , Merck shed
Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 31 1/4 , Bristol-Myers Squibb slipped Dollars  3/8
to Dollars 57 1/4 and Warner-Lambert weakened Dollars  3/4 to 67 3/4 .
Canada
TORONTO stocks closed firmer for choice after moderate trading which was
boosted by a large block trade in Czar Resources shares.
The TSE 300 index gained just 1.5 at 3,983.8 and rising issues outnumbered
declines by 397 to 334. Volume amounted to 52.1m shares valued at CDollars
485.5m. The day's turnover included a block trade of 8m Czar Resources
shares.
Ten of the 14 stock groups ended higher, with transportation up 1.06 per
cent. The gold shares sector recorded the day's biggest change, falling 1.95
per cent as the New York spot bullion price receded USDollars 2.70 an ounce.
</TEXT>
<XX>
