<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Union Carbide set to pull out
of ferrochrome
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY HAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HARARE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNION CARBIDE Corporation of the US, one of Zimbabwe's two ferrochrome
producing and exporting companies has taken the first step towards
disinvestment with the appointment of an international management team to
operate its ferrochrome plant.
In an opaque statement, that makes no reference to disinvestment, Union
Carbide Corporation of the US says the new management team will be headed by
two Zimbabweans, Mr Patrick Quirke and Mr Don Bailey, both of whom are
former employees of the RTZ group.
Union Carbide has long been keen to divest itself of the ferrochrome
operation, largely because it did not fit well with the group's core
business of industrial gases and chemicals. It came close to selling the
Zimbabwe subsidiary to RTZ of the UK last year but the deal fell through at
the 11th hour largely because of the collapse of the ferrochrome market in
the face of unprecedented Russian exports.
Mr Bailey was a key figure on the RTZ side in these negotiations and he will
now direct the ferrochrome operation in Zimbabwe, while also exploring
prospects for developing one of three platinum prospects currently under
investigation in the country.
Union Carbide Zimbabwe owns the Mimosa platinum prospect, while BHP-Utah and
Delta Gold of Australia are investigating the Hartley deposit and a
consortium of Anglo America Corporation of Zimbabwe, Rio Tinto Zimbabwe and
Robertson Mining also have a project under investigation.
Mining industry executives say that the development is positive from both
the ferrochrome and the platinum viewpoints. It has long been clear that
Union Carbide in the US was not interested in investing in either the
ferrochrome or platinum mines. The apparent hope is that the new management
team will be able to strengthen the ferrochrome operation, which is
struggling at present because of the depressed global market and sharply
higher domestic costs, as well as developing Mimosa platinum mine.
The country's other ferrochrome producer, Zimbabwe Alloys, owned by Anglo
American says energy costs, which have risen dramatically in the last few
years, now account for about half total costs. Last year, Union Carbide's
Zimbabwe subsidiary, Zimasco, had total sales of some ZDollars 500m
(USDollars 100m).
</TEXT>
