<PROFILE>_AN-DI1CRAF6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930928
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Stocks of base metals show
remorseless growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECESSION IN much of the industrialised world has brought remorseless growth
in stocks of traded metals. With the exception of tin, all other major
non-ferrous metal stocks in the hands of producers, consumers, traders and
the London Stock Exchange, have doubled since the end of 1990.
Figures released by the World Bureau of Metal Statistics show aluminium
stocks up 2m to 4.15m tonnes at the end of June; copper stocks up from
692,000 to 1.246m tonnes; lead stocks up from 382,000 to 667,000 tonnes;
nickel stocks up from 89,000 to 198,000 tonnes; and zinc stocks up from
567,000 to 1.207m tonnes.
Tin stocks, which were at record levels after the collapse of a price
support scheme in 1985, slipped from 39,000 tonnes at the end of 1990 to
31,000 tonnes in June this year.
Nickel suffered the sharpest drop in output among the traded metals in the
first half of this year, according to the bureau.
Refined nickel output in the western world dropped by 8.1 per cent to
285,000 tonnes. Tin was also badly hit by lacklustre world economic activity
and production was down by 6.9 per cent to 67,000 tonnes.
However, despite aluminium prices being the lowest ever in real terms,
output climbed by 1.8 per cent to 7.45m tonnes at a time when consumption
was falling by 1 per cent to 7.688m tonnes.
The statistics show clearly how lead and zinc mines cut back drastically in
the face of low prices but smelters continued to keep producing refined
metal at a relatively high rate. Mine output of lead was down 5.4 per cent
but production of refined lead was up 1.4 per cent. Zinc mine output slipped
4.2 per cent but the refineries produced 0.6 per cent more slab zinc.
The statistics give a confusing picture of the copper market by showing
refined production at 4.487m tonnes, consumption at 4.747m tonnes, a deficit
in east-west trade and a supply deficit of 323,000 tonnes. Yet total western
world stocks have grown from just over 1m tonnes at the end of 1992 to
1.246m tonnes, which suggests a supply surplus - a better reflection of the
market as most analyst see it.
Behind this confusion is a lack of metals statistics from the Commonwealth
of Independent States, a hang-over from the days when these were deemed to
be state secrets, which continues to cause big headaches for analysts in the
west.
Metal imported to the west from the CIS can take months to appear on
official statistics. It may be put in bonded warehouses and remain there for
a long time before being cleared through customs.
Mr Lloyd Davies, general manager of the WBMS, says that consumption data
must also be treated with some caution since it is based on essentially
incomplete trade statistics for European Community countries. This is a
consequence of the introduction of the so-called Intrastat system of
recording intra-EC trade, which is only now beginning to produce useful
information.
