<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / International Capital Markets: European banks expect returns
on equity of 10%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST senior European bank executives expect competition over the next decade
to force down banks' annual returns on capital to an average of 10 per cent
 -well below the level many have set as a target for their own banks.
A survey of 65 executives has found that despite the number setting target
returns on equity of at least 15 per cent, most privately think this is
unsustainable. They believe mergers will be forced by competition and
falling profits from corporate banking.
Nearly a third of executives interviewed by the consultants Gemini
Consulting and EFMA believed there would be a significant number of bank
bankruptcies by the year 2005 as banks try to cut costs. Some 68 per cent
believed only 15 to 20 significant European retail banks would remain.
Mr Mark Tilden, a vice-president of Gemini Consulting, said the study had
shown that executives were privately pessimistic about the industry and the
erosion of lending margins caused by competition. 'They think there is a
difficult period ahead,' he said.
The executives, from 15 countries, were particularly doubtful about the
future profitability of corporate banking. Some 78 per cent thought
'disintermediation' - the provision of their own financial services by big
corporations - would continue to undermine bank profits.
The chief effect of this process to date has been to reduce margins on
corporate loans as large companies find it cheaper to issue their own
securities than to borrow from banks. But executives also expected companies
to provide other forms of banking services themselves.
Some 88 per cent of executives thought that large corporations would provide
their own cash management services, 67 per cent thought they would carry out
foreign-exchange dealing, and 63 per cent thought they would provide their
own medium- and long-term finance.
About a quarter thought that fewer than 10 European banks would be
undertaking corporate banking by 2005. Mr Tilden said that banks were
already finding it hard to gain a role in corporate banking aside from
offering to manage company risk through derivative products.
Only 48 per cent of executives thought that corporate banking would be a
significant contributor to profits at the end of the period. However, some
bankers believed they would have to continue to offer loans to companies in
order to attract other business.
Executives mostly believed that the retreat from banks having retail branch
networks in other countries would continue. Only 28 per cent thought that
their own bank would have a significant retail banking presence in another
country, given the competitive pressures.
European Banking: A View to 2005. Gemini Consulting/EFMA. 11-14 Grafton
Street, London W1X 3LA.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XGZ  Europe.
</CN>
