<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / International Company News: Schwab expects sharp rise in
third term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHARLES SCHWAB, the largest discount brokerage company in the US, said
yesterday it expects to post a sharp increase in third-quarter profits to
between Dollars 18m and Dollars 21m when it releases its latest
three-monthly earnings next month. In the same quarter a year ago, it earned
just Dollars 7.8m.
Although Schwab said its third-quarter earnings this year would show a big
improvement on a year ago, the third quarter of 1992 was an unusually weak
period for the firm.
Its latest earnings, while up sharply from a year ago, will still be below
the first and second quarters of this year, when the broker reported net
income of Dollars 35.4m and Dollars 31.6m, respectively. This steady, if
modest, decline in earnings during 1993 suggests that, while stock markets
have been reaching record highs and investor interest in equities has been
booming, the overall level of trading activity may have peaked.
Results for the full year, however, will still come in considerably higher
than the Dollars 81.2m earned in 1992, which was itself a record.
Schwab said its latest earnings would have been higher but for a Dollars
6.8m one-time extraordinary charge, which it is taking to cover the costs of
refinancing some of its debt.
The firm also said customer assets at the end of this quarter will total
Dollars 86bn, up Dollars 20bn from the start of the year and up almost 50
per cent from the end of the 1992's third quarter.
</TEXT>
