FT  28 SEP 93 / International Company News: Credit Lyonnais rejects MGM
offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CREDIT Lyonnais, the French bank which owns Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, yesterday
said it had no immediate plans to sell the Hollywood film studio following
an announcement by Mr William Koch that he plans to make an offer for the
company.
Mr Koch, winner of the 1992 Americas Cup yacht race, is chairman and biggest
shareholder of Kendall Square Research, a supercomputer company.
He said yesterday that he had retained International Creative Management
(ICM), the powerful Hollywood talent agency, and its chairman to advise him.
'At this point, it is my goal for our team to amass enough information to
put together a preliminary offer within the next 30 to 60 days,' he said.
Credit Lyonnais took control of MGM last year after forclosing on loans it
made to Mr Giancarlo Parretti, an Italian entrepreneur who bought the
company in 1990 from Mr Kirk Kerkorian for Dollars 1.3bn. Credit Lyonnais is
involved in litigation with Mr Kerkorian.
In a letter to MGM's chairman, Mr Frank Mancuso, Credit Lyonnais said last
week: 'Everyone at MGM/UA should rest assured MGM/UA is not for sale.' Under
US banking law Credit Lyonnais must sell the studio by 1997.
