<PROFILE>_AN-DI1CRAFGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930928
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / International Company News: Carlzon takes flight to
'fortress' - Hugh Carnegy and Paul Betts examine the SAS chief's resignation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY and PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF there were any doubts about Mr Jan Carlzon's commitment to Alcazar, the
ambitious project to merge Scandinavian Airlines System (SAS), KLM Royal
Dutch Airlines, Swissair and Austrian Airlines, the charismatic Swede
dispelled them yesterday.
By announcing his resignation as chief executive of SAS, a position he has
held since 1981, in order to concentrate on Alcazar, Mr Carlzon made it
clear that for him the project, named after a four-towered Moorish fortress,
is a question of all or nothing. 'I have told the board that if Alcazar does
not succeed, I will not remain in this position,' he said.
What he did not say was whether he intended to lead the merged airline
should it happen. His ambition is almost certainly to do so, but he said
only that he would join its senior management. The vision of building a
fourth force in European airlines - after British Airways, Air France and
Lufthansa - out of a handful of the continent's smaller operators is one
that Mr Carlzon has pursued since 1985. But it has become a make-or-break
issue in a career that rose during the 1980s but faltered as the 1990s
brought the airline industry down to earth. Mr Carlzon has been a symbol of
far-sighted Swedish management since he came to SAS at the age of 40 having
transformed the fortunes of a domestic airline, Linjeflyg, through a
low-fares policy.
At SAS, his Global Travel Service System strategy of combining businesses
such as hotels, aircraft servicing and catering with the core airline
service won plaudits. But three and a half years of losses have led SAS to
sell much of its hotel and other non-core investments.
Throughout, Mr Carlzon has roamed Europe and the Americas looking for
partners to give SAS added muscle to battle the US and European groups in an
increasingly deregulated industry. Investments in British Midland and
Continental Airlines of the US, and the European Quality Alliance with
Swissair and Austrian, were among moves which presaged the Alcazar project.
Now, Alcazar is portrayed as a lifeline for SAS, which suffered a SKr609m
(Dollars 77m) loss in the first six months of this year and has not shown a
full-year profit since 1989.
A sign that SAS finds it hard to envisage a future without Alcazar was the
announcement that Mr Jan Reinas, Mr Carlzon's successor as chief executive,
would leave the company in April to take up an appointment at Norske Skog,
the Norwegian pulp and paper group.
Alcazar is still not a foregone conclusion. The intention to produce by last
June a memorandum of understanding outlining how the four airlines will be
moulded under one management slipped to September.
Mr Carlzon said he hoped the MoU would be completed by October, but would
not give guarantees. KLM and Swissair confirmed that the mid-September
deadline had been moved into October. For its part, Austrian, the smallest
of the gang of four, said it was still considering an alternative option to
co-operate with Lufthansa rather than join the Alcazar partnership.
From the outset, none of the four airlines expected the negotiations to be
straightforward and many in the industry felt the timetable for formal
agreement by the end of this year was optimistic.
Although the airlines remain convinced that a partnership can significantly
strengthen their competitive position, several complex issues still need to
be ironed out.
These include:
The relative financial share of the airlines. One official close to the
talks yesterday said progress had been made within the proposed framework of
a 30 per cent share each for SAS, KLM and Swissair and 10 per cent for
Austrian, but agreement was not complete.
The Swiss financial community has expressed concern that this structure
would undervalue Swissair.
The participation of Austrian Airlines remains uncertain. Indeed, there are
strong indications that the Austrian carrier is leaning towards Lufthansa,
which has a stake in Lauda Air, the other Austrian airline.
Austrian yesterday confirmed that it had yet to make up its mind. But, even
if Austrian were to opt for co-operation with Lufthansa, KLM, SAS and
Swissair are still expected to continue seeking a merger of the three
instead of four airlines.
The location of the headquarters is proving another thorny question because
of the strategic and national implications of the ultimate decision. The
candidates include Amsterdam, Zurich, Copenhagen, or Vienna (if Austrian
agrees to join the venture).
Amsterdam seems the frontrunner because of its strategic position and the
advantages the partners would gain from the 'open skies' agreement between
the Netherlands and the US.
However, SAS is likely to make a strong pitch for Copenhagen, which it has
developed successfully into its main international hub.
The management question of who will be first among equals among the
four-strong top management team. Even though the partners claim to share a
common vision and have co-operated through the so-called European Quality
Alliance marketing partnership, the composition of the joint management team
remains a problem.
Coupled with the management problem is the reaction of the powerful airline
unions in each country, which fear job cuts.
The selection of a US airline partner. KLM has close links with Northwest;
Swissair with Delta, and SAS has had a long association with Continental.
Any of these issues could undermine Mr Carlzon's vision of creating a
European fortress airline. His decision to resign as SAS chief executive to
devote his time to the Alcazar project suggests that the construction of the
fortress still remains in the balance.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Scandinavian Airlines System.
    KLM Royal Dutch Airlines.
    Swissair.
    Austrian Airlines.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
    DKZ  Denmark, EC.
    NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
    NLZ  Netherlands, EC.
    ATZ  Austria, West Europe.
    CHZ  Switzerland, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4512 Air Transportation, Scheduled.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT933-611</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DI1CRAFFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930928
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 93 / International Company News: Cerus trims losses to FFr97m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CERUS, the French holding company controlled by Mr Carlo de Benedetti, the
Italian industrialist, managed to trim its net losses to FFr97m (Dollars
16.7m) in the first half of 1993 from FFr377m in the same period in 1992.
This was mainly due to a cut in the deficit of Banque Dumenil Leble, its
banking subsidiary.
The problems of Banque Dumenil, which has been affected by the difficulties
of its Swiss branch and turmoil in the French money markets, have clouded
Cerus for two years.
However, Cerus raised FFr1.4bn during the first half by selling its 3.1 per
cent stake in Suez, the French industrial and financial holding company. The
proceeds of the sale were used to finance a FFr1.3bn recapitalisation of
Banque Dumenil and to reduce Cerus's net debt.
The recapitalisation, which resulted in Cerus taking full control of Banque
Dumenil, helped the latter reduce its interim net loss to FFr39m in the
first six months of this year from FFr374m at the same stage of 1992 .
The other main French investment held by Cerus, which is 49 per cent owned
by Mr de Benedetti through CIR, his holding company, is a 35.4 per cent
stake in Valeo, the car parts group.
</TEXT>
